INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (8, 2, '2006-08-17 21:37:44', '2006-08-18 05:37:44', 'So I read about the Holographic Principle on Wikipedia. Was blown away by what it meant, kind of a WYSIWIG universe (here\'s hoping no salivating physicists will snarl at this puerile description).\r\n\r\nAnyway, for the moment, AW\'s basic work involves something related. Should be fun...could be gruelling. Who knows? Well, my wordcount suddenly has gone <em>down</em>, because I cut some extra sentences at the end I was hoping I could use. It\'s still above 15000; 1500<em>2</em> to be exact, but it\'s not bad.\r\n\r\nNone of the books on PF I wanted were on Questia, or in the Chapters stores. I probably will have to order them from Amazon/Chapters.', 'The Holographic Principle, or <i>Totus Agnitium Contineum</i>. Was that bad Latin...?', 0, '', 'private', 'open', 'open', '', 'the-holographic-principle-or-totus-agnitium-contineum-was-that-bad-latin', '', '', '2011-06-09 03:22:37', '2011-06-09 11:22:37', '', 0, 'http://www.avishek.net/blog/?p=8', 0, 'post', '', 0); 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (4, 2, '2006-07-30 15:32:50', '2006-07-30 23:32:50', 'It is a *lazy* Sunday afternoon; while rain patters against the glass of the now-empty apartment, my fingers wrestle with the keys. PPM and AH argue with each other; AH will not accept PPM\'s Mechanics. I\'ve had to quote a line or two from <em>Summa</em>. Tried learning a little Latin this morning; it positively rules; wonder why it died.\r\n\r\nOn a whim, I decided to redo one of my 4 year-old drawings again, <a title="Assassins\' preparation for the assault on Ungor Bede" href="http://www.avishek.net/images/Awaiting/Assassins\'%20preparation%20for%20the%20assault%20on%20Ungor%20Bede.jpg">"The Assassins\' preparation for assault on Ungor Bede"</a>. This time, it\'d be be using a stylus on the laptop, but still black-and-white. The Digital Watercolor medium in Painter is very nice, I must say. In other news, I really need a image gallery for the site: the one I have right now is a joke.\r\n\r\nTill then, images/Awaiting will get larger :-)', 'It\'s in the rain...', 0, '', 'private', 'open', 'open', '', 'its-in-the-rain', '', '', '2011-06-09 03:24:12', '2011-06-09 11:24:12', '', 0, 'http://www.avishek.net/blog/?p=4', 0, 'post', '', 0); 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (5, 2, '2006-08-10 01:55:26', '2006-08-10 09:55:26', 'All right...\r\n\r\nSo I was going crazy trying to get information on AoSG. Googling yielded very results, because the thing had been demolished to make way for a new building. So I finally subscribed to Questia in hopes of getting some data.\r\n\r\nInitially, I as disappointed because I could not get any information save for random mentions of AoSG in the context of neighbouring buildings. There\'s some information about the general category of buildings in VPL, but it pertains to other places and not my quarry.\r\n\r\nBut I found it. I just found it. Floor plans and stuff. There\'s this book which was on my Questia bookshelf but I\'d not paid attention to because it pertained to a period a little later than my subject. But it has tons of information, much of which I can use. Thanks, Questia.\r\n\r\nAnyway, pay dirt hit, have to go and write. It\'s 3:00 am, so that can be postponed till tomorrow. Oh wait, tomorrow\'s fencing...so what? :-)', 'Pay dirt...', 0, '', 'private', 'open', 'open', '', 'pay-dirt', '', '', '2011-06-09 03:24:29', '2011-06-09 11:24:29', '', 0, 'http://www.avishek.net/blog/?p=5', 0, 'post', '', 0); 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (6, 2, '2006-08-13 03:37:54', '2006-08-13 11:37:54', 'OK, so it\'s <strong>15003</strong> words and it\'s <strong>4:33</strong> a.m. But I\'m not nitpicking. But it feels nice...AW continues to prod and poke RB; RB is somewhat indignant at this. Currently stuck at a point, but it\'s just a case of writing for the last 4-5 hours. Not at a stretch though. But it feels nice.\r\n\r\nDamn, morning is coming. I can see the light through the blinds. I <em>hate</em> mornings.\r\n\r\nMore to come later. Oh, and AW=PPM.', '15000 at 4:30 a.m.', 0, '', 'private', 'open', 'open', '', '15000-at-430-am', '', '', '2011-06-09 03:24:21', '2011-06-09 11:24:21', '', 0, 'http://www.avishek.net/blog/?p=6', 0, 'post', '', 0); 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (7, 2, '2006-08-13 05:55:28', '2006-08-13 13:55:28', 'Questia is awesome. For the most part. One issue I have with it, though, is its image viewer. Sure, it has zoom and pan, but reloading the frame every time is not very nice. Well, you <em>could</em> look at the entire map, but the resolution is mercilessly small. Frying pan...fire. I\'d just love to view the map in IrfanView or any image viewer, where I\'d be able to scroll smoothly without reloads.\r\n\r\nAnyway, here\'s what you can do. Right click on any of the maps in the Questia Image Viewer and "Copy Image Location". It\'ll look something like this:\r\n\r\nhttp://images.questia.com/? fif=<u>b211597/b211597pn08.fpx&obj=iip,1.0&wid=300&hei=369</u>& rgn=0.0,0.0,1.0,1.0 &lng=en_US &vtrx=1 &cvt=jpeg\r\n\r\nThe important stuff you\'ll want is underlined above. The <em>wid</em> and <em>hei</em> parameters are the sizes of the retrieved images. Also, note the value of the <em>rgn</em> parameter; it defines what area of the entire image the retrieved image will cover. So, (0,0,1,1) and <em>wid=300</em> and <em>hei=369</em> will return the <em>entire</em> image in a 300x369 image. That\'s the low resolution version.\r\n\r\nSome experimenting reveals that for most images, a <em>rgn</em> parameter of (0,0,0.1,0.1) gives me the highest resolution available on the server. It also makes good sense to use the same <em>wid-hei</em> parameter values as in the URL.\r\n<h3>Invasion of the Image Snatchers</h3>\r\nSo, with that in mind, copy-paste this (snotty) piece of code. Heck, just run <em>javac</em> on the file.\r\n\r\n<em>import javax.imageio.ImageIO;\r\nimport javax.swing.*;\r\nimport java.awt.*;\r\nimport java.awt.image.BufferedImage;\r\nimport java.net.URL;\r\nimport java.io.File;\r\nimport java.io.IOException;</em>\r\n\r\n<em>public class QuestiaImageGrabber {\r\npublic static void main(String[] args) throws IOException {\r\nString urlStart1 = "http://images.questia.com/?fif=xxxxxx/ xxxxxxxxxxx.fpx&obj=iip,1.0&wid=300&hei=426&rgn=";\r\nString urlEnd = "&lng=en_US&vtrx=1&cvt=jpeg";</em>\r\n\r\n<em>int iterations = 16;\r\ndouble xIncrement = .10;\r\ndouble yIncrement = .10;</em>\r\n\r\n<em>double length = .10;\r\ndouble breadth = .10;</em>\r\n\r\n<em>for (double y = 0; y <= 0.9; y = Increment(y, yIncrement)) {\r\nfor (double x = 0; x <= 0.9; x = Increment(x, xIncrement)) {\r\nString imageUrl = urlStart1 + Build(x, y, length, breadth) + urlEnd;\r\nToolkit tk = Toolkit.getDefaultToolkit();\r\nImage image = tk.getImage(new URL(imageUrl));</em>\r\n\r\n<em>ImageIO.write(getBufferedImageFromImage(image), "jpeg", new File(y + "-" + x + ".jpg"));\r\nSystem.out.println(imageUrl);\r\n}\r\n}\r\n}</em>\r\n\r\n<em>private static BufferedImage getBufferedImageFromImage(Image img)\r\n{\r\nimg = new ImageIcon(img).getImage();\r\nBufferedImage bufferedImage = new BufferedImage(img.getWidth(null), img.getHeight(null), BufferedImage.TYPE_INT_RGB);\r\nGraphics g = bufferedImage.createGraphics();\r\ng.drawImage(img, 0, 0, null);\r\ng.dispose();</em>\r\n\r\n<em>return bufferedImage;\r\n}</em>\r\n\r\n<em>private static double Increment(double y, double yIncrement) {\r\ndouble l = Math.round((y + yIncrement) * 10.);\r\nreturn l /10.0;\r\n}</em>\r\n\r\n<em>private static String Build(double x, double y, double length, double breadth) {\r\nStringBuffer stringBuffer = new StringBuffer();</em>\r\n\r\n<em>stringBuffer.append(x);\r\nstringBuffer.append(",");\r\nstringBuffer.append(y);\r\nstringBuffer.append(",");</em>\r\n\r\n<em>stringBuffer.append(length);\r\nstringBuffer.append(",");\r\nstringBuffer.append(breadth);</em>\r\n\r\n<em>return stringBuffer.toString();\r\n}\r\n}\r\n</em>\r\n\r\nThings you\'ll need to customise in the code above are the fif parameter, and the wid-hei parameters. There might be some other changes needed but that is unlikely, and any of those would be trivial enough.\r\n\r\nOnce you run this, it will download the high resolution images into your output directory. Which is great, except that now you have to piece those 100 images together...grrr.\r\n<h3>Piecing the Evidence</h3>\r\nI\'ve absolutely no idea why I wrote that in Java...Ruby\'d have done just as well. For this part, I\'ll use exactly that. You\'ll need to download ImageMagick to put the pieces back together. Fortunately, if you go to the <a href="http://rmagick.rubyforge.org/">RMagick</a> site, you\'ll see a Windows gem installer for both the Ruby API and the RMagick library; download that, and run <em>gem install </em>.\r\n\r\nYou\'re all set. Run SciTE (or whatever) and paste this bit of (equally snotty) code.\r\n\r\n<em>require \'RMagick\'\r\ninclude Magick</em>\r\n\r\n<em>def normalized(number)\r\n(number / 10.0).to_s\r\nend</em>\r\n\r\n<em>fragment_x = 300\r\nfragment_y = 426</em>\r\n\r\n<em>final_image = Image.new(fragment_x * 10, fragment_y * 10)\r\n</em>\r\n\r\n<em> </em><em>directory = "C:\\\\Sandbox\\\\Images\\\\"</em>\r\n\r\n<em>(0..9).each do |y|\r\n(0..9).each do |x|\r\nfilename = directory +\r\nnormalized(y) + "-" + normalized(x) + ".jpg"</em>\r\n\r\n<em>fragment = ImageList.new(filename)\r\npixels = fragment.export_pixels(0,0, fragment_x, fragment_y, "RGB")</em>\r\n\r\n<em>final_image_x = x * fragment_x\r\nfinal_image_y = y * fragment_y</em>\r\n\r\n<em>char_buffer = pixels.pack("C*")\r\nfinal_image.import_pixels(final_image_x, final_image_y,\r\nfragment_x, fragment_y,\r\n"RGB", char_buffer)</em>\r\n\r\n<em>print filename + "\\n"\r\nend\r\nend</em>\r\n\r\n<em>final_image.write(directory + "final.jpg")</em>\r\n\r\nThere, that should reconstitute the entire image back into one <em>huge</em> image. And...you are DONE!! View your map in peace.', 'Questia high resolution images', 0, '', 'private', 'open', 'open', '', 'questia-high-resolution-images', '', '', '2011-06-09 03:22:50', '2011-06-09 11:22:50', '', 0, 'http://www.avishek.net/blog/?p=7', 0, 'post', '', 0); 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (9, 2, '2006-08-18 02:16:26', '2006-08-18 10:16:26', 'Lots of stuff to contend with, as the outline romps to Chapter 8. The end is <em>still</em> unclear, but most of the middle is fleshed out reasonably well for the moment. I\'m still in Chapter 2, and have put in some logical arcs I didn\'t add first time around.\r\n\r\nCurrently:\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>The Stationer is introduced.</li>\r\n	<li>A. Beauvais will become FH\'s primary mentor.</li>\r\n	<li>AW is more organised and not just a shadowy figure.</li>\r\n	<li>JS and JI now proceed on a proper route to Via Francigena.</li>\r\n	<li>The struggle for papacy not yet put in.</li>\r\n	<li>There needs to be some description from the I battlefront.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nContinuing on the consistency part, Honnecourt is dead in 1241, so some dialogue changes in Chapter 1.\r\n\r\nOn an unrelated note, am thinking of ordering a hulk of a book related to manuscript makers; might be worth it. The Stationer should have a cooler role than just dying.', 'Unaddressed story arcs', 0, '', 'private', 'open', 'open', '', 'unaddressed-story-arcs', '', '', '2011-06-09 03:22:23', '2011-06-09 11:22:23', '', 0, 'http://www.avishek.net/blog/?p=9', 0, 'post', '', 0); 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (10, 2, '2006-08-22 01:11:25', '2006-08-22 09:11:25', 'It <em>is</em> true: I passed <strong>16000</strong> words right now. The last 100 words were not something to be damn happy about, but it was a case of me using my imagination. Till I get the <em>Margins</em> book, I\'ll have to rely on educated guesses, rummaging my books, raiding McLeod\'s and general brain computing.\r\n\r\nOh, and the good news is I didn\'t just pass 16000, I hit <strong>16130</strong> before I even checked the count. This is going to be a *challenging* scene. Readying myself...', 'Yesss...16000+!', 0, '', 'private', 'open', 'open', '', 'yesss16000', '', '', '2011-06-09 03:21:49', '2011-06-09 11:21:49', '', 0, 'http://www.avishek.net/blog/?p=10', 0, 'post', '', 0); 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (11, 2, '2006-09-01 01:22:45', '2006-09-01 09:22:45', 'Finding a new apartment is a hassle, besides I have to sell furniture...this is why I hate unfurnished places. Besides, my books have not arrived yet. I do get a refund (I ordered premium shipping) but it stings a bit.\r\n\r\nThe practical upshot is that right now, I\'m not writing.\r\n\r\nSucks.', 'A compendium of bad news...', 0, '', 'private', 'open', 'open', '', 'a-compendium-of-bad-news', '', '', '2011-06-09 03:24:43', '2011-06-09 11:24:43', '', 0, 'http://www.avishek.net/blog/?p=11', 0, 'post', '', 0); 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (12, 2, '2006-09-04 01:10:36', '2006-09-04 09:10:36', '<p>Well, this is getting pretty regular, though I just can\'t bring myself to write a lot during weekdays. <strong>17062</strong> words to be exact, and the last 40-odd words suck: I\'ll need to revisit it tomorrow, but another threshold passed, in any case.</p><p>AW is about to speak with AB, just in case I forget :-)</p><p>Also I did get all the books I wanted. A tad expensive, but who cares?</p>', '17000 at 2:05 am...', 0, '', 'private', 'closed', 'closed', '', '17000-at-205-am', '', '', '2011-06-09 03:24:56', '2011-06-09 11:24:56', '', 0, 'http://www.avishek.net/blog/?p=12', 0, 'post', '', 0); 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (132, 1, '2006-08-22 01:11:25', '2006-08-22 09:11:25', 'It <em>is</em> true: I passed <strong>16000</strong> words right now. The last 100 words were not something to be damn happy about, but it was a case of me using my imagination. Till I get the <em>Margins</em> book, I\'ll have to rely on educated guesses, rummaging my books, raiding McLeod\'s and general brain computing.\r\n\r\nOh, and the good news is I didn\'t just pass 16000, I hit <strong>16130</strong> before I even checked the count. This is going to be a *challenging* scene. Readying myself...', 'Yesss...16000+!', 0, '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '10-revision', '', '', '2006-08-22 01:11:25', '2006-08-22 09:11:25', '', 10, 'http://www.avishek.net/blog/?p=132', 0, 'revision', '', 0); 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (133, 1, '2006-08-18 02:16:26', '2006-08-18 10:16:26', 'Lots of stuff to contend with, as the outline romps to Chapter 8. The end is <em>still</em> unclear, but most of the middle is fleshed out reasonably well for the moment. I\'m still in Chapter 2, and have put in some logical arcs I didn\'t add first time around.\r\n\r\nCurrently:\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>The Stationer is introduced.</li>\r\n	<li>A. Beauvais will become FH\'s primary mentor.</li>\r\n	<li>AW is more organised and not just a shadowy figure.</li>\r\n	<li>JS and JI now proceed on a proper route to Via Francigena.</li>\r\n	<li>The struggle for papacy not yet put in.</li>\r\n	<li>There needs to be some description from the I battlefront.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nContinuing on the consistency part, Honnecourt is dead in 1241, so some dialogue changes in Chapter 1.\r\n\r\nOn an unrelated note, am thinking of ordering a hulk of a book related to manuscript makers; might be worth it. The Stationer should have a cooler role than just dying.', 'Unaddressed story arcs', 0, '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '9-revision', '', '', '2006-08-18 02:16:26', '2006-08-18 10:16:26', '', 9, 'http://www.avishek.net/blog/?p=133', 0, 'revision', '', 0); 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (134, 1, '2006-08-17 21:37:44', '2006-08-18 05:37:44', 'So I read about the Holographic Principle on Wikipedia. Was blown away by what it meant, kind of a WYSIWIG universe (here\'s hoping no salivating physicists will snarl at this puerile description).\r\n\r\nAnyway, for the moment, AW\'s basic work involves something related. Should be fun...could be gruelling. Who knows? Well, my wordcount suddenly has gone <em>down</em>, because I cut some extra sentences at the end I was hoping I could use. It\'s still above 15000; 1500<em>2</em> to be exact, but it\'s not bad.\r\n\r\nNone of the books on PF I wanted were on Questia, or in the Chapters stores. I probably will have to order them from Amazon/Chapters.', 'The Holographic Principle, or <i>Totus Agnitium Contineum</i>. Was that bad Latin...?', 0, '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '8-revision', '', '', '2006-08-17 21:37:44', '2006-08-18 05:37:44', '', 8, 'http://www.avishek.net/blog/?p=134', 0, 'revision', '', 0); 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (135, 1, '2006-08-13 11:03:26', '2006-08-13 19:03:26', 'Questia is awesome. For the most part. One issue I have with it, though, is its image viewer. Sure, it has zoom and pan, but reloading the frame every time is not very nice. Well, you <em>could</em> look at the entire map, but the resolution is mercilessly small. Frying pan...fire. I\'d just love to view the map in IrfanView or any image viewer, where I\'d be able to scroll smoothly without reloads.\r\n\r\nAnyway, here\'s what you can do. Right click on any of the maps in the Questia Image Viewer and "Copy Image Location". It\'ll look something like this:\r\n\r\nhttp://images.questia.com/? fif=<u>b211597/b211597pn08.fpx&obj=iip,1.0&wid=300&hei=369</u>& rgn=0.0,0.0,1.0,1.0 &lng=en_US &vtrx=1 &cvt=jpeg\r\n\r\nThe important stuff you\'ll want is underlined above. The <em>wid</em> and <em>hei</em> parameters are the sizes of the retrieved images. Also, note the value of the <em>rgn</em> parameter; it defines what area of the entire image the retrieved image will cover. So, (0,0,1,1) and <em>wid=300</em> and <em>hei=369</em> will return the <em>entire</em> image in a 300x369 image. That\'s the low resolution version.\r\n\r\nSome experimenting reveals that for most images, a <em>rgn</em> parameter of (0,0,0.1,0.1) gives me the highest resolution available on the server. It also makes good sense to use the same <em>wid-hei</em> parameter values as in the URL.\r\n<h3>Invasion of the Image Snatchers</h3>\r\nSo, with that in mind, copy-paste this (snotty) piece of code. Heck, just run <em>javac</em> on the file.\r\n\r\n<em>import javax.imageio.ImageIO;\r\nimport javax.swing.*;\r\nimport java.awt.*;\r\nimport java.awt.image.BufferedImage;\r\nimport java.net.URL;\r\nimport java.io.File;\r\nimport java.io.IOException;</em>\r\n\r\n<em>public class QuestiaImageGrabber {\r\npublic static void main(String[] args) throws IOException {\r\nString urlStart1 = "http://images.questia.com/?fif=xxxxxx/ xxxxxxxxxxx.fpx&obj=iip,1.0&wid=300&hei=426&rgn=";\r\nString urlEnd = "&lng=en_US&vtrx=1&cvt=jpeg";</em>\r\n\r\n<em>int iterations = 16;\r\ndouble xIncrement = .10;\r\ndouble yIncrement = .10;</em>\r\n\r\n<em>double length = .10;\r\ndouble breadth = .10;</em>\r\n\r\n<em>for (double y = 0; y <= 0.9; y = Increment(y, yIncrement)) {\r\nfor (double x = 0; x <= 0.9; x = Increment(x, xIncrement)) {\r\nString imageUrl = urlStart1 + Build(x, y, length, breadth) + urlEnd;\r\nToolkit tk = Toolkit.getDefaultToolkit();\r\nImage image = tk.getImage(new URL(imageUrl));</em>\r\n\r\n<em>ImageIO.write(getBufferedImageFromImage(image), "jpeg", new File(y + "-" + x + ".jpg"));\r\nSystem.out.println(imageUrl);\r\n}\r\n}\r\n}</em>\r\n\r\n<em>private static BufferedImage getBufferedImageFromImage(Image img)\r\n{\r\nimg = new ImageIcon(img).getImage();\r\nBufferedImage bufferedImage = new BufferedImage(img.getWidth(null), img.getHeight(null), BufferedImage.TYPE_INT_RGB);\r\nGraphics g = bufferedImage.createGraphics();\r\ng.drawImage(img, 0, 0, null);\r\ng.dispose();</em>\r\n\r\n<em>return bufferedImage;\r\n}</em>\r\n\r\n<em>private static double Increment(double y, double yIncrement) {\r\ndouble l = Math.round((y + yIncrement) * 10.);\r\nreturn l /10.0;\r\n}</em>\r\n\r\n<em>private static String Build(double x, double y, double length, double breadth) {\r\nStringBuffer stringBuffer = new StringBuffer();</em>\r\n\r\n<em>stringBuffer.append(x);\r\nstringBuffer.append(",");\r\nstringBuffer.append(y);\r\nstringBuffer.append(",");</em>\r\n\r\n<em>stringBuffer.append(length);\r\nstringBuffer.append(",");\r\nstringBuffer.append(breadth);</em>\r\n\r\n<em>return stringBuffer.toString();\r\n}\r\n}\r\n</em>\r\n\r\nThings you\'ll need to customise in the code above are the fif parameter, and the wid-hei parameters. There might be some other changes needed but that is unlikely, and any of those would be trivial enough.\r\n\r\nOnce you run this, it will download the high resolution images into your output