INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (181, 2, '2011-07-13 01:38:03', '2011-07-13 09:38:03', '<strong>This was an old proof that was up on my old blog, but since I\'m no longer posting to that, I\'m reposting it here for posterity. Also, rewriting the equations in LaTeX, now that I have installed a plugin for that.</strong>\r\n\r\nI present a simple mathematical device to prove that tests improve our understanding of code. It does not really matter if this is code written by the test author himself or is legacy. To do this, some simplification of the situation is necessary.\r\n\r\nWe assume X is the unit of code under consideration. X may be a function, a class or a compiled binary. The only restriction on X is that it can accept inputs and produce measurable outputs.\r\n\r\nWithout loss of generality, we may assume that the X\'s output consists of n bits. If complicated structures like objects are present in the result, they may simply be decomposed into bits and laid out in a convenient order to fit this model. This assumption exists to simplify quantizing the output space only.\r\n\r\nWe also assume that unique inputs yield unique outputs, but this assumption does not affect the fundamental conclusion.\r\n\r\nLet us define the probabilities:\r\n\r\n[latex]P\\left(A\\right)[/latex] = Probability that X uses the correct algorithm = p\r\n[latex]P(B)[/latex] = Probability of test T1 passing (getting the correct output) for a given input I1 = [latex]1/(2^n)[/latex]\r\n[latex]P(B|A)[/latex] = Probability of test T1 passing (getting the correct output) for a given input I1, given X uses the correct algorithm = 1\r\n\r\nTherefore, using Bayes\' Theorem:\r\n\r\n[latex]P\\left(A|B\\right)[/latex] = Probability that X uses the correct algorithm given test passes for a given input I1\r\n[latex]\r\n            = P\\left(B|A\\right).P\\left(A\\right)/P\\left(B\\right)\r\n            = p.2^n\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\n[latex]P\\left(1\\right)=p.2^n[/latex]\r\n\r\n*Note that after writing one test, the probability of X using the correct algorithm has increased (n>=1) by a factor of 2^n.*\r\n\r\nLet us now write another test with input I2. Note that I assume that T1 passing does not affect any probabilities other than the updated probability of X using the correct algorithm, i.e., the tests are statistically independent (I believe that\'s the term used :-).\r\n\r\n[latex]P\\left(A\\right)[/latex] = Probability that X uses the correct algorithm = [latex]p.2^n[/latex]\r\n[latex]P\\left(B\\right)[/latex] = Probability of test T2 passing (getting the correct output) for a given input I2 = [latex]1/\\left(2^n\\right)[/latex]\r\n[latex]P\\left(B|A\\right)[/latex] = Probability of test T2 passing (getting the correct output) for a given input I2, given X uses the correct algorithm = 1\r\n\r\nTherefore, using Bayes\' Theorem:\r\n\r\n[latex]P\\left(A|B\\right)[/latex] = Probability that X uses the correct algorithm given test passes for a given input I2\r\n[latex]\r\n            = P\\left(B|A\\right).P\\left(A\\right)/P\\left(B\\right)\r\n            = p.2^n.2^n[/latex]\r\n\r\n[latex]P\\left(2\\right)=p.2^n.2^n[/latex]\r\nAfter having written t tests, we may write:\r\n\r\n[latex]P\\left(t\\right)=p.[2^{nt}][/latex]\r\n\r\n*<i>t</i> tests, therefore, increase the probability (or our knowledge, in very rough terms) of X being implemented correctly, by a factor of [latex]2^nt[/latex].*\r\nProbability is inversely correlated with entropy; thus, we have also reduced the entropy of the system.\r\nIt might be useful to state that I use the term \'test\' in a broad sense. The test may range from an automated unit test to human verification.\r\n\r\nIt turns out that it should be possible to determine p. Note that t is the number of *statistically independent tests* that we can write. This implies that t has a fixed upper bound. Thus:\r\n\r\nT = total number of statistically independent tests for X\r\n[latex]\r\np.[2^{nT}] <= 1, or,\r\np <= 1/[2^{nT}]\r\n[/latex]\r\n', 'Tests increase our Knowledge of a System: A Probabilistic Proof', 0, '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'tests-increase-our-knowledge-of-a-system-a-probabilistic-proof', '', '', '2011-07-25 08:13:49', '2011-07-25 16:13:49', '', 0, 'http://www.avishek.net/blog/?p=181', 0, 'post', '', 0); 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (182, 2, '2011-07-13 01:28:55', '2011-07-13 09:28:55', '<strong>This was an old proof that was up on my old blog, but since I\'m no longer posting to that, I\'m reposting it here for posterity.</strong>\n\nI present a simple mathematical device to prove that tests improve our understanding of code. It does not really matter if this is code written by the test author himself or is legacy. To do this, some simplification of the situation is necessary.\n\nWe assume X is the unit of code under consideration. X may be a function, a class or a compiled binary. The only restriction on X is that it can accept inputs and produce measurable outputs.\n\nWithout loss of generality, we may assume that the X\'s output consists of n bits. If complicated structures like objects are present in the result, they may simply be decomposed into bits and laid out in a convenient order to fit this model. This assumption exists to simplify quantizing the output space only.\n\nWe also assume that unique inputs yield unique outputs, but this assumption does not affect the fundamental conclusion.\n\nLet us define the probabilities:\n\nP(A) = Probability that X uses the correct algorithm = p\nP(B) = Probability of test T1 passing (getting the correct output) for a given input I1 = 1/(2^n)\nP(B|A) = Probability of test T1 passing (getting the correct output) for a given input I1, given X uses the correct algorithm = 1\n\nTherefore, using Bayes\' Theorem:\n\n*P(A|B)* = Probability that X uses the correct algorithm given test passes for a given input I1\n            = P(B|A).P(A)/P(B)\n            = *p.(2^n)*\n\nP(1)=p*(2^n)\n\n*Note that after writing one test, the probability of X using the correct algorithm has increased (n>=1) by a factor of 2^n.*\n\nLet us now write another test with input I2. Note that I assume that T1 passing does not affect any probabilities other than the updated probability of X using the correct algorithm, i.e., the tests are statistically independent (I believe that\'s the term used :-).\n\nP(A) = Probability that X uses the correct algorithm = p*(2^n)\nP(B) = Probability of test T2 passing (getting the correct output) for a given input I2 = 1/(2^n)\nP(B|A) = Probability of test T2 passing (getting the correct output) for a given input I2, given X uses the correct algorithm = 1\n\nTherefore, using Bayes\' Theorem:\n\nP(A|B) = Probability that X uses the correct algorithm given test passes for a given input I2\n            = P(B|A).P(A)/P(B)\n            = p.(2^n).(2^n)\n\nP(2)=p.(2^n).(2^n)\nAfter having written t tests, we may write:\n\n<div class="result">P(t)=p.[2^(n.t)]</div><div class="newline">&nbsp;</div>\n\n*<i>t</i> tests, therefore, increase the probability (or our knowledge, in very rough terms) of X being implemented correctly, by a factor of 2^nt.*\nProbability is inversely correlated with entropy; thus, we have also reduced the entropy of the system.\nIt might be useful to state that I use the term \'test\' in a broad sense. The test may range from an automated unit test to human verification.\n\n*Correction to update:*\n\nIt turns out that it should be possible to determine p. Note that t is the number of *statistically independent tests* that we can write. This implies that t has a fixed upper bound. Thus:\n\nT = total number of statistically independent tests for X\np.[2^(n.T)] <= 1, or,\n<div class="result">p <= 1/[2^(n.T)]</div><div class="newline">&nbsp;</div>\n', '', 0, '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '181-revision', '', '', '2011-07-13 01:28:55', '2011-07-13 09:28:55', '', 181, 'http://www.avishek.net/blog/?p=182', 0, 'revision', '', 0); 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (183, 2, '2011-07-13 01:29:06', '2011-07-13 09:29:06', '<strong>This was an old proof that was up on my old blog, but since I\'m no longer posting to that, I\'m reposting it here for posterity.</strong>\r\n\r\nI present a simple mathematical device to prove that tests improve our understanding of code. It does not really matter if this is code written by the test author himself or is legacy. To do this, some simplification of the situation is necessary.\r\n\r\nWe assume X is the unit of code under consideration. X may be a function, a class or a compiled binary. The only restriction on X is that it can accept inputs and produce measurable outputs.\r\n\r\nWithout loss of generality, we may assume that the X\'s output consists of n bits. If complicated structures like objects are present in the result, they may simply be decomposed into bits and laid out in a convenient order to fit this model. This assumption exists to simplify quantizing the output space only.\r\n\r\nWe also assume that unique inputs yield unique outputs, but this assumption does not affect the fundamental conclusion.\r\n\r\nLet us define the probabilities:\r\n\r\nP(A) = Probability that X uses the correct algorithm = p\r\nP(B) = Probability of test T1 passing (getting the correct output) for a given input I1 = 1/(2^n)\r\nP(B|A) = Probability of test T1 passing (getting the correct output) for a given input I1, given X uses the correct algorithm = 1\r\n\r\nTherefore, using Bayes\' Theorem:\r\n\r\n*P(A|B)* = Probability that X uses the correct algorithm given test passes for a given input I1\r\n            = P(B|A).P(A)/P(B)\r\n            = *p.(2^n)*\r\n\r\nP(1)=p*(2^n)\r\n\r\n*Note that after writing one test, the probability of X using the correct algorithm has increased (n>=1) by a factor of 2^n.*\r\n\r\nLet us now write another test with input I2. Note that I assume that T1 passing does not affect any probabilities other than the updated probability of X using the correct algorithm, i.e., the tests are statistically independent (I believe that\'s the term used :-).\r\n\r\nP(A) = Probability that X uses the correct algorithm = p*(2^n)\r\nP(B) = Probability of test T2 passing (getting the correct output) for a given input I2 = 1/(2^n)\r\nP(B|A) = Probability of test T2 passing (getting the correct output) for a given input I2, given X uses the correct algorithm = 1\r\n\r\nTherefore, using Bayes\' Theorem:\r\n\r\nP(A|B) = Probability that X uses the correct algorithm given test passes for a given input I2\r\n            = P(B|A).P(A)/P(B)\r\n            = p.(2^n).(2^n)\r\n\r\nP(2)=p.(2^n).(2^n)\r\nAfter having written t tests, we may write:\r\n\r\n<div class="result">P(t)=p.[2^(n.t)]</div><div class="newline">&nbsp;</div>\r\n\r\n*<i>t</i> tests, therefore, increase the probability (or our knowledge, in very rough terms) of X being implemented correctly, by a factor of 2^nt.*\r\nProbability is inversely correlated with entropy; thus, we have also reduced the entropy of the system.\r\nIt might be useful to state that I use the term \'test\' in a broad sense. The test may range from an automated unit test to human verification.\r\n\r\n*Correction to update:*\r\n\r\nIt turns out that it should be possible to determine p. Note that t is the number of *statistically independent tests* that we can write. This implies that t has a fixed upper bound. Thus:\r\n\r\nT = total number of statistically independent tests for X\r\np.[2^(n.T)] <= 1, or,\r\n<div class="result">p <= 1/[2^(n.T)]</div><div class="newline">&nbsp;</div>\r\n', 'Tests increase our Knowledge of a System: A Probabilistic Proof', 0, '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '181-revision-2', '', '', '2011-07-13 01:29:06', '2011-07-13 09:29:06', '', 181, 'http://www.avishek.net/blog/?p=183', 0, 'revision', '', 0); 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (184, 1, '2011-07-13 01:34:03', '2011-07-13 09:34:03', '<strong>This was an old proof that was up on my old blog, but since I\'m no longer posting to that, I\'m reposting it here for posterity.</strong>\n\nI present a simple mathematical device to prove that tests improve our understanding of code. It does not really matter if this is code written by the test author himself or is legacy. To do this, some simplification of the situation is necessary.\n\nWe assume X is the unit of code under consideration. X may be a function, a class or a compiled binary. The only restriction on X is that it can accept inputs and produce measurable outputs.\n\nWithout loss of generality, we may assume that the X\'s output consists of n bits. If complicated structures like objects are present in the result, they may simply be decomposed into bits and laid out in a convenient order to fit this model. This assumption exists to simplify quantizing the output space only.\n\nWe also assume that unique inputs yield unique outputs, but this assumption does not affect the fundamental conclusion.\n\nLet us define the probabilities:\n\n<strong>P(A) = Probability that X uses the correct algorithm = p\nP(B) = Probability of test T1 passing (getting the correct output) for a given input I1 = 1/(2^n)\nP(B|A) = Probability of test T1 passing (getting the correct output) for a given input I1, given X uses the correct algorithm = 1\n</strong>\n\nTherefore, using Bayes\' Theorem:\n\n*P(A|B)* = Probability that X uses the correct algorithm given test passes for a given input I1\n            = P(B|A).P(A)/P(B)\n            = *p.(2^n)*\n\nP(1)=p*(2^n)\n\n*Note that after writing one test, the probability of X using the correct algorithm has increased (n>=1) by a factor of 2^n.*\n\nLet us now write another test with input I2. Note that I assume that T1 passing does not affect any probabilities other than the updated probability of X using the correct algorithm, i.e., the tests are statistically independent (I believe that\'s the term used :-).\n\nP(A) = Probability that X uses the correct algorithm = p*(2^n)\nP(B) = Probability of test T2 passing (getting the correct output) for a given input I2 = 1/(2^n)\nP(B|A) = Probability of test T2 passing (getting the correct output) for a given input I2, given X uses the correct algorithm = 1\n\nTherefore, using Bayes\' Theorem:\n\nP(A|B) = Probability that X uses the correct algorithm given test passes for a given input I2\n            = P(B|A).P(A)/P(B)\n            = p.(2^n).(2^n)\n\nP(2)=p.(2^n).(2^n)\nAfter having written t tests, we may write:\n\n<div class="result">P(t)=p.[2^(n.t)]</div><div class="newline">&nbsp;</div>\n\n*<i>t</i> tests, therefore, increase the probability (or our knowledge, in very rough terms) of X being implemented correctly, by a factor of 2^nt.*\nProbability is inversely correlated with entropy; thus, we have also reduced the entropy of the system.\nIt might be useful to state that I use the term \'test\' in a broad sense. The test may range from an automated unit test to human verification.\n\n*Correction to update:*\n\nIt turns out that it should be possible to determine p. Note that t is the number of *statistically independent tests* that we can write. This implies that t has a fixed upper bound. Thus:\n\nT = total number of statistically independent tests for X\np.[2^(n.T)] <= 1, or,\nzi<div class="result">p <= 1/[2^(n.T)]</div><div class="newline">&nbsp;</div>\n', 'Tests increase our Knowledge of a System: A Probabilistic Proof', 0, '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '181-revision-3', '', '', '2011-07-13 01:34:03', '2011-07-13 09:34:03', '', 181, 'http://www.avishek.net/blog/?p=184', 0, 'revision', '', 0); 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (185, 1, '2011-07-13 01:34:46', '2011-07-13 09:34:46', '<strong>This was an old proof that was up on my old blog, but since I\'m no longer posting to that, I\'m reposting it here for posterity.</strong>\r\n\r\nI present a simple mathematical device to prove that tests improve our understanding of code. It does not really matter if this is code written by the test author himself or is legacy. To do this, some simplification of the situation is necessary.\r\n\r\nWe assume X is the unit of code under consideration. X may be a function, a class or a compiled binary. The only restriction on X is that it can accept inputs and produce measurable outputs.\r\n\r\nWithout loss of generality, we may assume that the X\'s output consists of n bits. If complicated structures like objects are present in the result, they may simply be decomposed into bits and laid out in a convenient order to fit this model. This assumption exists to simplify quantizing the output space only.\r\n\r\nWe also assume that unique inputs yield unique outputs, but this assumption does not affect the fundamental conclusion.\r\n\r\nLet us define the probabilities:\r\n\r\n<strong>P(A) = Probability that X uses the correct algorithm = p\r\nP(B) = Probability of test T1 passing (getting the correct output) for a given input I1 = 1/(2^n)\r\nP(B|A) = Probability of test T1 passing (getting the correct output) for a given input I1, given X uses the correct algorithm = 1\r\n</strong>\r\n\r\nTherefore, using Bayes\' Theorem:\r\n\r\n*P(A|B)* = Probability that X uses the correct algorithm given test passes for a given input I1\r\n            = P(B|A).P(A)/P(B)\r\n            = *p.(2^n)*\r\n\r\nP(1)=p*(2^n)\r\n\r\n*Note that after writing one test, the probability of X using the correct algorithm has increased (n>=1) by a factor of 2^n.*\r\n\r\nLet us now write another test with input I2. Note that I assume that T1 passing does not affect any probabilities other than the updated probability of X using the correct algorithm, i.e., the tests are statistically independent (I believe that\'s the term used :-).\r\n\r\nP(A) = Probability that X uses the correct algorithm = p*(2^n)\r\nP(B) = Probability of test T2 passing (getting the correct output) for a given input I2 = 1/(2^n)\r\nP(B|A) = Probability of test T2 passing (getting the correct output) for a given input I2, given X uses the correct algorithm = 1\r\n\r\nTherefore, using Bayes\' Theorem:\r\n\r\nP(A|B) = Probability that X uses the correct algorithm given test passes for a given input I2\r\n            = P(B|A).P(A)/P(B)\r\n            = p.(2^n).(2^n)\r\n\r\nP(2)=p.(2^n).(2^n)\r\nAfter having written t tests, we may write:\r\n\r\n<div class="result">P(t)=p.[2^(n.t)]</div><div class="newline">&nbsp;</div>\r\n\r\n*<i>t</i> tests, therefore, increase the probability (or our knowledge, in very rough terms) of X being implemented correctly, by a factor of 2^nt.*\r\nProbability is inversely correlated with entropy; thus, we have also reduced the entropy of the system.\r\nIt might be useful to state that I use the term \'test\' in a broad sense. The test may range from an automated unit test to human verification.\r\n\r\nIt turns out that it should be possible to determine p. Note that t is the number of *statistically independent tests* that we can write. This implies that t has a fixed upper bound. Thus:\r\n\r\nT = total number of statistically independent tests for X\r\np.[2^(n.T)] <= 1, or,\r\n<div class="result">p <= 1/[2^(n.T)]</div><div class="newline">&nbsp;</div>\r\n', 'Tests increase our Knowledge of a System: A Probabilistic Proof', 0, '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '181-revision-4', '', '', '2011-07-13 01:34:46', '2011-07-13 09:34:46', '', 181, 'http://www.avishek.net/blog/?p=185', 0, 'revision', '', 0); 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (186, 1, '2011-07-25 08:13:16', '2011-07-25 16:13:16', '<strong>This was an old proof that was up on my old blog, but since I\'m no longer posting to that, I\'m reposting it here for posterity. Also, rewriting the equations in LaTeX, now that I have installed a plugin for that.</strong>\r\n\r\nI present a simple mathematical device to prove that tests improve our understanding of code. It does not really matter if this is code written by the test author himself or is legacy. To do this, some simplification of the situation is necessary.\r\n\r\nWe assume X is the unit of code under consideration. X may be a function, a class or a compiled binary. The only restriction on X is that it can accept inputs and produce measurable outputs.\r\n\r\nWithout loss of generality, we may assume that the X\'s output consists of n bits. If complicated structures like objects are present in the result, they may simply be decomposed into bits and laid out in a convenient order to fit this model. This assumption exists to simplify quantizing the output space only.\r\n\r\nWe also assume that unique inputs yield unique outputs, but this assumption does not affect the fundamental conclusion.\r\n\r\nLet us define the probabilities:\r\n\r\n[latex]P\\left(A\\right)[/latex] = Probability that X uses the correct algorithm = p\r\n[latex]P(B)[/latex] = Probability of test T1 passing (getting the correct output) for a given input I1 = [latex]1/(2^n)[/latex]\r\n[latex]P(B|A)[/latex] = Probability of test T1 passing (getting the correct output) for a given input I1, given X uses the correct algorithm = 1\r\n\r\nTherefore, using Bayes\' Theorem:\r\n\r\n[latex]P\\left(A|B\\right)[/latex] = Probability that X uses the correct algorithm given test passes for a given input I1\r\n[latex]\r\n            = P\\left(B|A\\right).P\\left(A\\right)/P\\left(B\\right)\r\n            = p.2^n\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\n[latex]P\\left(1\\right)=p.2^n[/latex]\r\n\r\n*Note that after writing one test, the probability of X using the correct algorithm has increased (n>=1) by a factor of 2^n.*\r\n\r\nLet us now write another test with input I2. Note that I assume that T1 passing does not affect any probabilities other than the updated probability of X using the correct algorithm, i.e., the tests are statistically independent (I believe that\'s the term used :-).\r\n\r\n[latex]P\\left(A\\right)[/latex] = Probability that X uses the correct algorithm = [latex]p.2^n[/latex]\r\n[latex]P\\left(B\\right)[/latex] = Probability of test T2 passing (getting the correct output) for a given input I2 = [latex]1/\\left(2^n\\right)[/latex]\r\n[latex]P\\left(B|A\\right)[/latex] = Probability of test T2 passing (getting the correct output) for a given input I2, given X uses the correct algorithm = 1\r\n\r\nTherefore, using Bayes\' Theorem:\r\n\r\n[latex]P\\left(A|B\\right)[/latex] = Probability that X uses the correct algorithm given test passes for a given input I2\r\n[latex]\r\n            = P\\left(B|A\\right).P\\left(A\\right)/P\\left(B\\right)\r\n            = p.2^n.2^n[/latex]\r\n\r\nP\\left(2\\right)=p.2^n.2^n[/latex]\r\nAfter having written t tests, we may write:\r\n\r\n[latex]P\\left(t\\right)=p.[2^{nt}][/latex]\r\n\r\n*<i>t</i> tests, therefore, increase the probability (or our knowledge, in very rough terms) of X being implemented correctly, by a factor of [latex]2^nt[/latex].*\r\nProbability is inversely correlated with entropy; thus, we have also reduced the entropy of the system.\r\nIt might be useful to state that I use the term \'test\' in a broad sense. The test may range from an automated unit test to human verification.\r\n\r\nIt turns out that it should be possible to determine p. Note that t is the number of *statistically independent tests* that we can write. This implies that t has a fixed upper bound. Thus:\r\n\r\nT = total number of statistically independent tests for X\r\n[latex]\r\np.[2^{nT}] <= 1, or,\r\np <= 1/[2^{nT}]\r\n[/latex]\r\n', 'Tests increase our Knowledge of a System: A Probabilistic Proof', 0, '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '181-autosave', '', '', '2011-07-25 08:13:16', '2011-07-25 16:13:16', '', 181, 'http://www.avishek.net/blog/?p=186', 0, 'revision', '', 0); 
