INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (353, 1, '2011-07-21 02:57:44', '2011-07-21 10:57:44', 'Let\'s start off by stating what the objective is. We are attempting to diagonalise a symmetric matrix.\r\nA symmetric matrix looks like this:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nA=\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\na & d & n & w \\\\\r\nd & b & h & e \\\\\r\nn & h & c & i \\\\\r\nw & e & i & d \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nNotice how the values are reflected across the diagonal a-b-c-d; this holds true for any symmetric matrix. Now, here\'s an example of a diagonal matrix.\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nD=\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\na & 0 & 0 & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & b & 0 & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & 0 & c & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & 0 & 0 & d \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nNotice how all the off-diagonal elements (elements not part of the diagonal) are zero; this holds true for any diagonal matrix.\r\nArmed with that information, we are now in a position to restate the first line: determine the set of matrix operations which will transform a symmetric matrix into a diagonal form. To follow through with the examples above, the question we are asking is, find me a <strong>P</strong> such that:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nP^T .\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\na & d & n & w \\\\\r\nd & b & h & e \\\\\r\nn & h & c & i \\\\\r\nw & e & i & d \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n.P\r\n=\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\np & 0 & 0 & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & q & 0 & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & 0 & r & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & 0 & 0 & s \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nor, more concisely,\r\n[latex]\r\nP^T.A.P = D\r\n[/latex]', 'Eigenvector algorithms for symmetric matrices: Jacobi rotations', 0, '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '331-revision-20', '', '', '2011-07-21 02:57:44', '2011-07-21 10:57:44', '', 331, 'http://avishek.net/blog/?p=353', 0, 'revision', '', 0); 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (354, 1, '2011-07-21 02:58:38', '2011-07-21 10:58:38', 'Let\'s start off by stating what the objective is. We are attempting to diagonalise a symmetric matrix.\r\nA symmetric matrix looks like this:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nA=\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\na & d & n & w \\\\\r\nd & b & h & e \\\\\r\nn & h & c & i \\\\\r\nw & e & i & d \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nNotice how the values are reflected across the diagonal a-b-c-d; this holds true for any symmetric matrix. Now, here\'s an example of a diagonal matrix.\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nD=\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\na & 0 & 0 & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & b & 0 & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & 0 & c & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & 0 & 0 & d \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nNotice how all the off-diagonal elements (elements not part of the diagonal) are zero; this holds true for any diagonal matrix.\r\nArmed with that information, we are now in a position to restate the first line: determine the set of matrix operations which will transform a symmetric matrix into a diagonal form. To follow through with the examples above, the question we are asking is, find me a <strong>P</strong> such that:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nP^T .\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\na & d & n & w \\\\\r\nd & b & h & e \\\\\r\nn & h & c & i \\\\\r\nw & e & i & d \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n.P\r\n=\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\np & 0 & 0 & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & q & 0 & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & 0 & r & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & 0 & 0 & s \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nor, more concisely,\r\n[latex]\r\nP^T A P = D\r\n[/latex]', 'Eigenvector algorithms for symmetric matrices: Jacobi rotations', 0, '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '331-revision-21', '', '', '2011-07-21 02:58:38', '2011-07-21 10:58:38', '', 331, 'http://avishek.net/blog/?p=354', 0, 'revision', '', 0); 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (355, 1, '2011-07-21 02:59:12', '2011-07-21 10:59:12', 'Let\'s start off by stating what the objective is. We are attempting to diagonalise a symmetric matrix.\r\nA symmetric matrix looks like this:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nA=\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\na & d & n & w \\\\\r\nd & b & h & e \\\\\r\nn & h & c & i \\\\\r\nw & e & i & d \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nNotice how the values are reflected across the diagonal a-b-c-d; this holds true for any symmetric matrix. Now, here\'s an example of a diagonal matrix.\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nD=\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\na & 0 & 0 & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & b & 0 & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & 0 & c & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & 0 & 0 & d \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nNotice how all the off-diagonal elements (elements not part of the diagonal) are zero; this holds true for any diagonal matrix.\r\nArmed with that information, we are now in a position to restate the first line: determine the set of matrix operations which will transform a symmetric matrix into a diagonal form. To follow through with the examples above, the question we are asking is, find me a <strong>P</strong> such that:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nP^T .\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\na & d & n & w \\\\\r\nd & b & h & e \\\\\r\nn & h & c & i \\\\\r\nw & e & i & d \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n.P\r\n=\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\np & 0 & 0 & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & q & 0 & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & 0 & r & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & 0 & 0 & s \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nor, more concisely,\r\n[latex]\r\nP^T.A.P = D\r\n[/latex]', 'Eigenvector algorithms for symmetric matrices: Jacobi rotations', 0, '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '331-revision-22', '', '', '2011-07-21 02:59:12', '2011-07-21 10:59:12', '', 331, 'http://avishek.net/blog/?p=355', 0, 'revision', '', 0); 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (582, 1, '2011-09-04 07:21:27', '2011-09-04 15:21:27', 'Partly to play around with the Jenkins Remote API, and partly to kickstart a build radiator setup at my current consulting engagement, I wrote a quick radiator page which might serve as a foundation for further experiment by the team. I\'ve seen several build radiators built using multiple technologies - Java, Python, etc.; I specifically chose HTML/jQuery for this effort because a modern browser seems to be the only piece of software universally available on any machine one might care to set up.\nThe code is up at <a href="https://github.com/asengupta/jquery-jenkins-radiator">GitHub</a>, and here .', 'A jQuery-based build radiator for Jenkins', 0, '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '580-revision', '', '', '2011-09-04 07:21:27', '2011-09-04 15:21:27', '', 580, 'http://avishek.net/blog/?p=582', 0, 'revision', '', 0); 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (356, 1, '2011-07-21 03:20:51', '2011-07-21 11:20:51', 'Let\'s start off by stating what the objective is. We are attempting to diagonalise a symmetric matrix.\r\nA symmetric matrix looks like this:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nA=\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\na & d & n & w \\\\\r\nd & b & h & e \\\\\r\nn & h & c & i \\\\\r\nw & e & i & d \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nNotice how the values are reflected across the diagonal a-b-c-d; this holds true for any symmetric matrix. Now, here\'s an example of a diagonal matrix.\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nD=\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\na & 0 & 0 & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & b & 0 & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & 0 & c & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & 0 & 0 & d \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nNotice how all the off-diagonal elements (elements not part of the diagonal) are zero; this holds true for any diagonal matrix.\r\nArmed with that information, we are now in a position to restate the first line: determine the set of matrix operations which will transform a symmetric matrix into a diagonal form. To follow through with the examples above, the question we are asking is, find me a <strong>P</strong> such that:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nP^T .\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\na & d & n & w \\\\\r\nd & b & h & e \\\\\r\nn & h & c & i \\\\\r\nw & e & i & d \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n.P\r\n=\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\np & 0 & 0 & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & q & 0 & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & 0 & r & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & 0 & 0 & s \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nor, more concisely,\r\n[latex]\r\nP^T.A.P = D\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nWhy such an unsightly transformation?\r\nWell, before we get into the mechanics of the method, let\'s clarify a thing or two about notation. First, the P<sup>T</sup> notation, this is read as \'P transpose\', or \'P tee\' (as I call it). The transpose of a matrix is simply a matrix whose rows are the columns of the original matrix, and whose columns are the rows of the original matrix. As an illustration:\r\n\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\na & b & c & d \\\\\r\ne & f & g & h \\\\\r\ni & j & k & l \\\\\r\nm & n & o & p \\end{array} \\right)\\^T\r\n=\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\na & e & i & m \\\\\r\nb & f & j & n \\\\\r\nc & g & k & o \\\\\r\nd & h & l & p \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n[/latex]\r\n', 'Eigenvector algorithms for symmetric matrices: Jacobi rotations', 0, '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '331-revision-23', '', '', '2011-07-21 03:20:51', '2011-07-21 11:20:51', '', 331, 'http://avishek.net/blog/?p=356', 0, 'revision', '', 0); 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (360, 1, '2011-07-21 03:26:27', '2011-07-21 11:26:27', 'Let\'s start off by stating what the objective is. We are attempting to diagonalise a symmetric matrix.\r\nA symmetric matrix looks like this:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nA=\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\na & d & n & w \\\\\r\nd & b & h & e \\\\\r\nn & h & c & i \\\\\r\nw & e & i & d \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nNotice how the values are reflected across the diagonal a-b-c-d; this holds true for any symmetric matrix. Now, here\'s an example of a diagonal matrix.\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nD=\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\na & 0 & 0 & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & b & 0 & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & 0 & c & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & 0 & 0 & d \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nNotice how all the off-diagonal elements (elements not part of the diagonal) are zero; this holds true for any diagonal matrix.\r\nArmed with that information, we are now in a position to restate the first line: determine the set of matrix operations which will transform a symmetric matrix into a diagonal form. To follow through with the examples above, the question we are asking is, find me a <strong>P</strong> such that:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nP^T .\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\na & d & n & w \\\\\r\nd & b & h & e \\\\\r\nn & h & c & i \\\\\r\nw & e & i & d \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n.P\r\n=\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\np & 0 & 0 & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & q & 0 & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & 0 & r & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & 0 & 0 & s \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nor, more concisely,\r\n[latex]\r\nP^T.A.P = D\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nWhy such an unsightly transformation?\r\nWell, before we get into the mechanics of the method, let\'s clarify a thing or two about notation. First, the P<sup>T</sup> notation, this is read as \'P transpose\', or \'P tee\' (as I call it). The transpose of a matrix is simply a matrix whose rows are the columns of the original matrix, and whose columns are the rows of the original matrix. As an illustration:\r\n\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\na & b & c & d \\\\\r\ne & f & g & h \\\\\r\ni & j & k & l \\\\\r\nm & n & o & p \\end{array} \\right)\\\\top\r\n=\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\na & e & i & m \\\\\r\nb & f & j & n \\\\\r\nc & g & k & o \\\\\r\nd & h & l & p \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n[/latex]\r\n', 'Eigenvector algorithms for symmetric matrices: Jacobi rotations', 0, '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '331-revision-27', '', '', '2011-07-21 03:26:27', '2011-07-21 11:26:27', '', 331, 'http://avishek.net/blog/?p=360', 0, 'revision', '', 0); 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (357, 1, '2011-07-21 03:22:28', '2011-07-21 11:22:28', 'Let\'s start off by stating what the objective is. We are attempting to diagonalise a symmetric matrix.\r\nA symmetric matrix looks like this:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nA=\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\na & d & n & w \\\\\r\nd & b & h & e \\\\\r\nn & h & c & i \\\\\r\nw & e & i & d \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nNotice how the values are reflected across the diagonal a-b-c-d; this holds true for any symmetric matrix. Now, here\'s an example of a diagonal matrix.\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nD=\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\na & 0 & 0 & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & b & 0 & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & 0 & c & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & 0 & 0 & d \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nNotice how all the off-diagonal elements (elements not part of the diagonal) are zero; this holds true for any diagonal matrix.\r\nArmed with that information, we are now in a position to restate the first line: determine the set of matrix operations which will transform a symmetric matrix into a diagonal form. To follow through with the examples above, the question we are asking is, find me a <strong>P</strong> such that:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nP^T .\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\na & d & n & w \\\\\r\nd & b & h & e \\\\\r\nn & h & c & i \\\\\r\nw & e & i & d \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n.P\r\n=\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\np & 0 & 0 & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & q & 0 & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & 0 & r & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & 0 & 0 & s \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nor, more concisely,\r\n[latex]\r\nP^T.A.P = D\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nWhy such an unsightly transformation?\r\nWell, before we get into the mechanics of the method, let\'s clarify a thing or two about notation. First, the P<sup>T</sup> notation, this is read as \'P transpose\', or \'P tee\' (as I call it). The transpose of a matrix is simply a matrix whose rows are the columns of the original matrix, and whose columns are the rows of the original matrix. As an illustration:\r\n\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\n(\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\na & b & c & d \\\\\r\ne & f & g & h \\\\\r\ni & j & k & l \\\\\r\nm & n & o & p \\end{array} \\right)\\)^T\r\n=\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\na & e & i & m \\\\\r\nb & f & j & n \\\\\r\nc & g & k & o \\\\\r\nd & h & l & p \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n[/latex]\r\n', 'Eigenvector algorithms for symmetric matrices: Jacobi rotations', 0, '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '331-revision-24', '', '', '2011-07-21 03:22:28', '2011-07-21 11:22:28', '', 331, 'http://avishek.net/blog/?p=357', 0, 'revision', '', 0); 
