INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (369, 1, '2011-07-21 03:40:03', '2011-07-21 11:40:03', 'Let\'s start off by stating what the objective is. We are attempting to diagonalise a symmetric matrix.\r\nA symmetric matrix looks like this:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nA=\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\na & d & n & w \\\\\r\nd & b & h & e \\\\\r\nn & h & c & i \\\\\r\nw & e & i & d \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nNotice how the values are reflected across the diagonal a-b-c-d; this holds true for any symmetric matrix. Now, here\'s an example of a diagonal matrix.\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nD=\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\na & 0 & 0 & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & b & 0 & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & 0 & c & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & 0 & 0 & d \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nNotice how all the off-diagonal elements (elements not part of the diagonal) are zero; this holds true for any diagonal matrix.\r\nArmed with that information, we are now in a position to restate the first line: determine the set of matrix operations which will transform a symmetric matrix into a diagonal form. To follow through with the examples above, the question we are asking is, find me a <strong>P</strong> such that:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nP^T .\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\na & d & n & w \\\\\r\nd & b & h & e \\\\\r\nn & h & c & i \\\\\r\nw & e & i & d \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n.P\r\n=\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\np & 0 & 0 & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & q & 0 & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & 0 & r & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & 0 & 0 & s \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nor, more concisely,\r\n[latex]\r\nP^T.A.P = D\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nWhy such an unsightly transformation?\r\nWell, before we get into the mechanics of the method, let\'s clarify a thing or two about notation. First, the P<sup>T</sup> notation, this is read as \'P transpose\', or \'P tee\' (as I call it). The transpose of a matrix is simply a matrix whose rows are the columns of the original matrix, and whose columns are the rows of the original matrix. As an illustration:\r\n\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\na & b & c & d \\\\\r\ne & f & g & h \\\\\r\ni & j & k & l \\\\\r\nm & n & o & p \\end{array} \\right)\\ ^{\\top}\r\n=\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\na & e & i & m \\\\\r\nb & f & j & n \\\\\r\nc & g & k & o \\\\\r\nd & h & l & p \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n[/latex]\r\n', 'Eigenvector algorithms for symmetric matrices: Jacobi rotations', 0, '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '331-revision-36', '', '', '2011-07-21 03:40:03', '2011-07-21 11:40:03', '', 331, 'http://avishek.net/blog/?p=369', 0, 'revision', '', 0); 
