dots P_n) = D\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nWell, before we get into the mechanics of the method, let\'s clarify a thing or two about notation. First, the P<sup>T</sup> notation, this is read as \'P transpose\', or \'P tee\' (as I call it). The transpose of a matrix is simply a matrix whose rows are the columns of the original matrix, and whose columns are the rows of the original matrix. As an illustration:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\na & b & c & d \\\\\r\ne & f & g & h \\\\\r\ni & j & k & l \\\\\r\nm & n & o & p \\end{array} \\right)\\ ^T\r\n=\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\na & e & i & m \\\\\r\nb & f & j & n \\\\\r\nc & g & k & o \\\\\r\nd & h & l & p \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\n', 'Eigenvector algorithms for symmetric matrices: Jacobi rotations', 0, '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '331-revision-55', '', '', '2011-07-23 00:22:09', '2011-07-23 08:22:09', '', 331, 'http://avishek.net/blog/?p=388', 0, 'revision', '', 0); 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (583, 1, '2011-09-04 07:22:51', '2011-09-04 15:22:51', 'Partly to play around with the Jenkins Remote API, and partly to kickstart a build radiator setup at my current consulting engagement, I wrote a quick radiator page which might serve as a foundation for further experiment by the team. I\'ve seen several build radiators built using multiple technologies - Java, Python, etc.; I specifically chose HTML/jQuery for this effort because a modern browser seems to be the only piece of software universally available on any machine one might care to set up.\r\nThe code is up at <a href="https://github.com/asengupta/jquery-jenkins-radiator">GitHub</a>, and here is the obligatory screenshot :-)\r\n\r\n<a href="http://avishek.net/blog/wp-content/uploads/2011/09/BuildRadiator.png"><img src="http://avishek.net/blog/wp-content/uploads/2011/09/BuildRadiator-300x168.png" alt="" title="BuildRadiator" width="300" height="168" class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-581" /></a>\r\n', 'A jQuery-based build radiator for Jenkins', 0, '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '580-revision-2', '', '', '2011-09-04 07:22:51', '2011-09-04 15:22:51', '', 580, 'http://avishek.net/blog/?p=583', 0, 'revision', '', 0); 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (389, 1, '2011-07-23 00:26:00', '2011-07-23 08:26:00', 'Let\'s start off by stating what the objective is. We are attempting to diagonalise a symmetric matrix.\r\nA symmetric matrix looks like this:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nA=\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\na & d & n & w \\\\\r\nd & b & h & e \\\\\r\nn & h & c & i \\\\\r\nw & e & i & d \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nNotice how the values are reflected across the diagonal a-b-c-d; this holds true for any symmetric matrix. Now, here\'s an example of a diagonal matrix.\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nD=\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\na & 0 & 0 & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & b & 0 & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & 0 & c & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & 0 & 0 & d \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nNotice how all the off-diagonal elements (elements not part of the diagonal) are zero; this holds true for any diagonal matrix.\r\nArmed with that information, we are now in a position to restate the first line: determine the set of matrix operations which will transform a symmetric matrix into a diagonal form. To follow through with the examples above, the question we are asking is, find me a <strong>P</strong> such that:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nP^T .\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\na & d & n & w \\\\\r\nd & b & h & e \\\\\r\nn & h & c & i \\\\\r\nw & e & i & d \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n.P\r\n=\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\np & 0 & 0 & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & q & 0 & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & 0 & r & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & 0 & 0 & s \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nor, more concisely,\r\n[latex]\r\nP^{-1}.A.P = D\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nWhy such an unsightly transformation?\r\nI\'ll probably write about this in a future post, but for now, remember that the eigenvector matrix diagonalises its \'parent\' matrix. In the previous identity, [latex]P[/latex] is the eigenvector matrix.\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nP = P_1.P_2.P_3 \\ldots P_n\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nSubstituting the above into the diagonalisation identity:\r\n[latex]\r\n(P_1.P_2.P_3 \\ldots P_n)^{-1}.A.(P_1.P_2.P_3 \\ldots P_n) = D\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nThe inverse of a product of matrices is the reversed-order product of the inverse of those same matrices, which is to say:\r\n[latex]\r\n(P_1.P_2.P_3 \\ldots P_n)^{-1} = P_n^{-1} \\ldots P_3^{-1}.P_2^{-1}.P_1^{-1}\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nWell, before we get into the mechanics of the method, let\'s clarify a thing or two about notation. First, the P<sup>T</sup> notation, this is read as \'P transpose\', or \'P tee\' (as I call it). The transpose of a matrix is simply a matrix whose rows are the columns of the original matrix, and whose columns are the rows of the original matrix. As an illustration:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\na & b & c & d \\\\\r\ne & f & g & h \\\\\r\ni & j & k & l \\\\\r\nm & n & o & p \\end{array} \\right)\\ ^T\r\n=\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\na & e & i & m \\\\\r\nb & f & j & n \\\\\r\nc & g & k & o \\\\\r\nd & h & l & p \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\n', 'Eigenvector algorithms for symmetric matrices: Jacobi rotations', 0, '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '331-revision-56', '', '', '2011-07-23 00:26:00', '2011-07-23 08:26:00', '', 331, 'http://avishek.net/blog/?p=389', 0, 'revision', '', 0); 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (390, 1, '2011-07-23 00:28:00', '2011-07-23 08:28:00', 'Let\'s start off by stating what the objective is. We are attempting to diagonalise a symmetric matrix.\r\nA symmetric matrix looks like this:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nA=\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\na & d & n & w \\\\\r\nd & b & h & e \\\\\r\nn & h & c & i \\\\\r\nw & e & i & d \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nNotice how the values are reflected across the diagonal a-b-c-d; this holds true for any symmetric matrix. Now, here\'s an example of a diagonal matrix.\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nD=\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\na & 0 & 0 & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & b & 0 & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & 0 & c & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & 0 & 0 & d \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nNotice how all the off-diagonal elements (elements not part of the diagonal) are zero; this holds true for any diagonal matrix.\r\nArmed with that information, we are now in a position to restate the first line: determine the set of matrix operations which will transform a symmetric matrix into a diagonal form. To follow through with the examples above, the question we are asking is, find me a <strong>P</strong> such that:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nP^T .\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\na & d & n & w \\\\\r\nd & b & h & e \\\\\r\nn & h & c & i \\\\\r\nw & e & i & d \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n.P\r\n=\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\np & 0 & 0 & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & q & 0 & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & 0 & r & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & 0 & 0 & s \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nor, more concisely,\r\n[latex]\r\nP^{-1}.A.P = D\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nWhy such an unsightly transformation?\r\nI\'ll probably write about this in a future post, but for now, remember that the eigenvector matrix diagonalises its \'parent\' matrix. In the previous identity, [latex]P[/latex] is the eigenvector matrix.\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nP = P_1.P_2.P_3 \\ldots P_n\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nSubstituting the above into the diagonalisation identity:\r\n[latex]\r\n(P_1.P_2.P_3 \\ldots P_n)^{-1}.A.(P_1.P_2.P_3 \\ldots P_n) = D\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nThe inverse of a product of matrices is the reversed-order product of the inverse of those same matrices, which is to say:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\n(P_1.P_2.P_3 \\ldots P_n)^{-1} = P_n^{-1} \\ldots P_3^{-1}.P_2^{-1}.P_1^{-1}\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nSubstituting this result gives:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nP_n^{-1} \\ldots P_3^{-1}.P_2^{-1}.P_1^{-1}\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nWell, before we get into the mechanics of the method, let\'s clarify a thing or two about notation. First, the P<sup>T</sup> notation, this is read as \'P transpose\', or \'P tee\' (as I call it). The transpose of a matrix is simply a matrix whose rows are the columns of the original matrix, and whose columns are the rows of the original matrix. As an illustration:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\na & b & c & d \\\\\r\ne & f & g & h \\\\\r\ni & j & k & l \\\\\r\nm & n & o & p \\end{array} \\right)\\ ^T\r\n=\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\na & e & i & m \\\\\r\nb & f & j & n \\\\\r\nc & g & k & o \\\\\r\nd & h & l & p \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\n', 'Eigenvector algorithms for symmetric matrices: Jacobi rotations', 0, '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '331-revision-57', '', '', '2011-07-23 00:28:00', '2011-07-23 08:28:00', '', 331, 'http://avishek.net/blog/?p=390', 0, 'revision', '', 0); 
