dots P_n) = D\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nThe inverse of a product of matrices is the reversed-order product of the inverse of those same matrices, which is to say:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\n(P_1.P_2.P_3 \\ldots P_n)^{-1} = P_n^{-1} \\ldots P_3^{-1}.P_2^{-1}.P_1^{-1}\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nSubstituting this result gives:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\n\\left( P_n^{-1} \\ldots P_3^{-1}.P_2^{-1}.P_1^{-1} \\right).A.\\left( P_1.P_2.P_3 \\ldots P_n \\right) = D\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nWell, before we get into the mechanics of the method, let\'s clarify a thing or two about notation. First, the P<sup>T</sup> notation, this is read as \'P transpose\', or \'P tee\' (as I call it). The transpose of a matrix is simply a matrix whose rows are the columns of the original matrix, and whose columns are the rows of the original matrix. As an illustration:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\na & b & c & d \\\\\r\ne & f & g & h \\\\\r\ni & j & k & l \\\\\r\nm & n & o & p \\end{array} \\right)\\ ^T\r\n=\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\na & e & i & m \\\\\r\nb & f & j & n \\\\\r\nc & g & k & o \\\\\r\nd & h & l & p \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\n', 'Eigenvector algorithms for symmetric matrices: Jacobi rotations', 0, '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '331-revision-61', '', '', '2011-07-23 00:32:02', '2011-07-23 08:32:02', '', 331, 'http://avishek.net/blog/?p=394', 0, 'revision', '', 0); 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (395, 1, '2011-07-23 00:36:43', '2011-07-23 08:36:43', 'Let\'s start off by stating what the objective is. We are attempting to diagonalise a symmetric matrix.\r\nA symmetric matrix looks like this:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nA=\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\na & d & n & w \\\\\r\nd & b & h & e \\\\\r\nn & h & c & i \\\\\r\nw & e & i & d \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nNotice how the values are reflected across the diagonal a-b-c-d; this holds true for any symmetric matrix. Now, here\'s an example of a diagonal matrix.\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nD=\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\na & 0 & 0 & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & b & 0 & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & 0 & c & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & 0 & 0 & d \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nNotice how all the off-diagonal elements (elements not part of the diagonal) are zero; this holds true for any diagonal matrix.\r\nArmed with that information, we are now in a position to restate the first line: determine the set of matrix operations which will transform a symmetric matrix into a diagonal form. To follow through with the examples above, the question we are asking is, find me a <strong>P</strong> such that:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nP^T .\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\na & d & n & w \\\\\r\nd & b & h & e \\\\\r\nn & h & c & i \\\\\r\nw & e & i & d \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n.P\r\n=\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\np & 0 & 0 & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & q & 0 & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & 0 & r & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & 0 & 0 & s \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nor, more concisely,\r\n[latex]\r\nP^{-1}.A.P = D\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nWhy such an unsightly transformation?\r\nI\'ll probably write about this in a future post, but for now, remember that the eigenvector matrix diagonalises its \'parent\' matrix. In the previous identity, [latex]P[/latex] is the eigenvector matrix.\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nP = P_1.P_2.P_3 \\ldots P_n\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nSubstituting the above into the diagonalisation identity:\r\n[latex]\r\n(P_1.P_2.P_3 \\ldots P_n)^{-1}.A.(P_1.P_2.P_3 \\ldots P_n) = D\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nThe inverse of a product of matrices is the reversed-order product of the inverse of those same matrices, which is to say:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\n(P_1.P_2.P_3 \\ldots P_n)^{-1} = P_n^{-1} \\ldots P_3^{-1}.P_2^{-1}.P_1^{-1}\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nSubstituting this result gives:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\n\\left( P_n^{-1} \\ldots P_3^{-1}.P_2^{-1}.P_1^{-1} \\right).A.\\left( P_1.P_2.P_3 \\ldots P_n \\right) = D\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nWell, let\'s use the associative property of matrix multiplication to shift around the brackets a bit.\r\n(The associative property of matrix multiplication, by the way, says that: [latex]\\left(AB\\right)C = A\\left(BC\\right)[/latex])\r\nWell, before we get into the mechanics of the method, let\'s clarify a thing or two about notation. First, the P<sup>T</sup> notation, this is read as \'P transpose\', or \'P tee\' (as I call it). The transpose of a matrix is simply a matrix whose rows are the columns of the original matrix, and whose columns are the rows of the original matrix. As an illustration:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\na & b & c & d \\\\\r\ne & f & g & h \\\\\r\ni & j & k & l \\\\\r\nm & n & o & p \\end{array} \\right)\\ ^T\r\n=\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\na & e & i & m \\\\\r\nb & f & j & n \\\\\r\nc & g & k & o \\\\\r\nd & h & l & p \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\n', 'Eigenvector algorithms for symmetric matrices: Jacobi rotations', 0, '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '331-revision-62', '', '', '2011-07-23 00:36:43', '2011-07-23 08:36:43', '', 331, 'http://avishek.net/blog/?p=395', 0, 'revision', '', 0); 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (396, 1, '2011-07-23 00:38:45', '2011-07-23 08:38:45', 'Let\'s start off by stating what the objective is. We are attempting to diagonalise a symmetric matrix.\r\nA symmetric matrix looks like this:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nA=\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\na & d & n & w \\\\\r\nd & b & h & e \\\\\r\nn & h & c & i \\\\\r\nw & e & i & d \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nNotice how the values are reflected across the diagonal a-b-c-d; this holds true for any symmetric matrix. Now, here\'s an example of a diagonal matrix.\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nD=\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\na & 0 & 0 & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & b & 0 & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & 0 & c & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & 0 & 0 & d \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nNotice how all the off-diagonal elements (elements not part of the diagonal) are zero; this holds true for any diagonal matrix.\r\nArmed with that information, we are now in a position to restate the first line: determine the set of matrix operations which will transform a symmetric matrix into a diagonal form. To follow through with the examples above, the question we are asking is, find me a <strong>P</strong> such that:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nP^T .\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\na & d & n & w \\\\\r\nd & b & h & e \\\\\r\nn & h & c & i \\\\\r\nw & e & i & d \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n.P\r\n=\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\np & 0 & 0 & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & q & 0 & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & 0 & r & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & 0 & 0 & s \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nor, more concisely,\r\n[latex]\r\nP^{-1}.A.P = D\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nWhy such an unsightly transformation?\r\nI\'ll probably write about this in a future post, but for now, remember that the eigenvector matrix diagonalises its \'parent\' matrix. In the previous identity, [latex]P[/latex] is the eigenvector matrix.\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nP = P_1.P_2.P_3 \\ldots P_n\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nSubstituting the above into the diagonalisation identity:\r\n[latex]\r\n(P_1.P_2.P_3 \\ldots P_n)^{-1}.A.(P_1.P_2.P_3 \\ldots P_n) = D\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nThe inverse of a product of matrices is the reversed-order product of the inverse of those same matrices, which is to say:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\n(P_1.P_2.P_3 \\ldots P_n)^{-1} = P_n^{-1} \\ldots P_3^{-1}.P_2^{-1}.P_1^{-1}\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nSubstituting this result gives:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\n\\left( P_n^{-1} \\ldots P_3^{-1}.P_2^{-1}.P_1^{-1} \\right).A.\\left( P_1.P_2.P_3 \\ldots P_n \\right) = D\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nWell, let\'s use the associative property of matrix multiplication to shift around the brackets a bit.\r\n<em>The associative property of matrix multiplication, by the way, says that: [latex]\\left(AB\\right)C = A\\left(BC\\right)[/latex]</em>\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\n\\left(P_n^{-1} \\ldots \\left(P_3^{-1}.\\left(P_2^{-1}.\\left(P_1^{-1}.A.P_1\\right).P_2\\right).P_3\\right)\\ldots P_n\\right) = D\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nWell, before we get into the mechanics of the method, let\'s clarify a thing or two about notation. First, the P<sup>T</sup> notation, this is read as \'P transpose\', or \'P tee\' (as I call it). The transpose of a matrix is simply a matrix whose rows are the columns of the original matrix, and whose columns are the rows of the original matrix. As an illustration:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\na & b & c & d \\\\\r\ne & f & g & h \\\\\r\ni & j & k & l \\\\\r\nm & n & o & p \\end{array} \\right)\\ ^T\r\n=\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\na & e & i & m \\\\\r\nb & f & j & n \\\\\r\nc & g & k & o \\\\\r\nd & h & l & p \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\n', 'Eigenvector algorithms for symmetric matrices: Jacobi rotations', 0, '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '331-revision-63', '', '', '2011-07-23 00:38:45', '2011-07-23 08:38:45', '', 331, 'http://avishek.net/blog/?p=396', 0, 'revision', '', 0); 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (397, 1, '2011-07-23 00:41:58', '2011-07-23 08:41:58', 'Let\'s start off by stating what the objective is. We are attempting to diagonalise a symmetric matrix.\r\nA symmetric matrix looks like this:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nA=\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\na & d & n & w \\\\\r\nd & b & h & e \\\\\r\nn & h & c & i \\\\\r\nw & e & i & d \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nNotice how the values are reflected across the diagonal a-b-c-d; this holds true for any symmetric matrix. Now, here\'s an example of a diagonal matrix.\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nD=\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\na & 0 & 0 & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & b & 0 & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & 0 & c & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & 0 & 0 & d \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nNotice how all the off-diagonal elements (elements not part of the diagonal) are zero; this holds true for any diagonal matrix.\r\nArmed with that information, we are now in a position to restate the first line: determine the set of matrix operations which will transform a symmetric matrix into a diagonal form. To follow through with the examples above, the question we are asking is, find me a <strong>P</strong> such that:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nP^T .\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\na & d & n & w \\\\\r\nd & b & h & e \\\\\r\nn & h & c & i \\\\\r\nw & e & i & d \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n.P\r\n=\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\np & 0 & 0 & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & q & 0 & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & 0 & r & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & 0 & 0 & s \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nor, more concisely,\r\n[latex]\r\nP^{-1}.A.P = D\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nWhy such an unsightly transformation?\r\nI\'ll probably write about this in a future post, but for now, remember that the eigenvector matrix diagonalises its \'parent\' matrix. In the previous identity, [latex]P[/latex] is the eigenvector matrix.\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nP = P_1.P_2.P_3 \\ldots P_n\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nSubstituting the above into the diagonalisation identity:\r\n[latex]\r\n(P_1.P_2.P_3 \\ldots P_n)^{-1}.A.(P_1.P_2.P_3 \\ldots P_n) = D\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nThe inverse of a product of matrices is the reversed-order product of the inverse of those same matrices, which is to say:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\n(P_1.P_2.P_3 \\ldots P_n)^{-1} = P_n^{-1} \\ldots P_3^{-1}.P_2^{-1}.P_1^{-1}\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nSubstituting this result gives:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\n\\left( P_n^{-1} \\ldots P_3^{-1}.P_2^{-1}.P_1^{-1} \\right).A.\\left( P_1.P_2.P_3 \\ldots P_n \\right) = D\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nWell, let\'s use the associative property of matrix multiplication to shift around the brackets a bit.\r\n<em>The associative property of matrix multiplication, by the way, says that: [latex]\\left(AB\\right)C = A\\left(BC\\right)[/latex]</em>\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\n\\left(P_n^{-1} \\ldots \\left(P_3^{-1}.\\left(P_2^{-1}.\\left(P_1^{-1}.A.P_1\\right).P_2\\right).P_3\\right)\\ldots P_n\\right) = D\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nThe above grouping can be expressed more concisely as:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nA_{j+1} = P_{j+1}^{-1}.A_j.P_{j+1}\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nWell, before we get into the mechanics of the method, let\'s clarify a thing or two about notation. First, the P<sup>T</sup> notation, this is read as \'P transpose\', or \'P tee\' (as I call it). The transpose of a matrix is simply a matrix whose rows are the columns of the original matrix, and whose columns are the rows of the original matrix. As an illustration:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\na & b & c & d \\\\\r\ne & f & g & h \\\\\r\ni & j & k & l \\\\\r\nm & n & o & p \\end{array} \\right)\\ ^T\r\n=\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\na & e & i & m \\\\\r\nb & f & j & n \\\\\r\nc & g & k & o \\\\\r\nd & h & l & p \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\n', 'Eigenvector algorithms for symmetric matrices: Jacobi rotations', 0, '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '331-revision-64', '', '', '2011-07-23 00:41:58', '2011-07-23 08:41:58', '', 331, 'http://avishek.net/blog/?p=397', 0, 'revision', '', 0); 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (398, 1, '2011-07-23 00:43:03', '2011-07-23 08:43:03', 'Let\'s start off by stating what the objective is. We are attempting to diagonalise a symmetric matrix.\r\nA symmetric matrix looks like this:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nA=\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\na & d & n & w \\\\\r\nd & b & h & e \\\\\r\nn & h & c & i \\\\\r\nw & e & i & d \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nNotice how the values are reflected across the diagonal a-b-c-d; this holds true for any symmetric matrix. Now, here\'s an example of a diagonal matrix.\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nD=\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\na & 0 & 0 & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & b & 0 & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & 0 & c & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & 0 & 0 & d \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nNotice how all the off-diagonal elements (elements not part of the diagonal) are zero; this holds true for any diagonal matrix.\r\nArmed with that information, we are now in a position to restate the first line: determine the set of matrix operations which will transform a symmetric matrix into a diagonal form. To follow through with the examples above, the question we are asking is, find me a <strong>P</strong> such that:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nP^{-1} .\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\na & d & n & w \\\\\r\nd & b & h & e \\\\\r\nn & h & c & i \\\\\r\nw & e & i & d \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n.P\r\n=\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\np & 0 & 0 & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & q & 0 & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & 0 & r & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & 0 & 0 & s \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nor, more concisely,\r\n[latex]\r\nP^{-1}.A.P = D\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nWhy such an unsightly transformation?\r\nI\'ll probably write about this in a future post, but for now, remember that the eigenvector matrix diagonalises its \'parent\' matrix. In the previous identity, [latex]P[/latex] is the eigenvector matrix.\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nP = P_1.P_2.P_3 \\ldots P_n\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nSubstituting the above into the diagonalisation identity:\r\n[latex]\r\n(P_1.P_2.P_3 \\ldots P_n)^{-1}.A.(P_1.P_2.P_3 \\ldots P_n) = D\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nThe inverse of a product of matrices is the reversed-order product of the inverse of those same matrices, which is to say:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\n(P_1.P_2.P_3 \\ldots P_n)^{-1} = P_n^{-1} \\ldots P_3^{-1}.P_2^{-1}.P_1^{-1}\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nSubstituting this result gives:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\n\\left( P_n^{-1} \\ldots P_3^{-1}.P_2^{-1}.P_1^{-1} \\right).A.\\left( P_1.P_2.P_3 \\ldots P_n \\right) = D\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nWell, let\'s use the associative property of matrix multiplication to shift around the brackets a bit.\r\n<em>The associative property of matrix multiplication, by the way, says that: [latex]\\left(AB\\right)C = A\\left(BC\\right)[/latex]</em>\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\n\\left(P_n^{-1} \\ldots \\left(P_3^{-1}.\\left(P_2^{-1}.\\left(P_1^{-1}.A.P_1\\right).P_2\\right).P_3\\right)\\ldots P_n\\right) = D\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nThe above grouping can be expressed more concisely as:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nA_{j+1} = P_{j+1}^{-1}.A_j.P_{j+1}\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nWell, before we get into the mechanics of the method, let\'s clarify a thing or two about notation. First, the P<sup>T</sup> notation, this is read as \'P transpose\', or \'P tee\' (as I call it). The transpose of a matrix is simply a matrix whose rows are the columns of the original matrix, and whose columns are the rows of the original matrix. As an illustration:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\na & b & c & d \\\\\r\ne & f & g & h \\\\\r\ni & j & k & l \\\\\r\nm & n & o & p \\end{array} \\right)\\ ^T\r\n=\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\na & e & i & m \\\\\r\nb & f & j & n \\\\\r\nc & g & k & o \\\\\r\nd & h & l & p \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\n', 'Eigenvector algorithms for symmetric matrices: Jacobi rotations', 0, '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '331-revision-65', '', '', '2011-07-23 00:43:03', '2011-07-23 08:43:03', '', 331, 'http://avishek.net/blog/?p=398', 0, 'revision', '', 0); 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (584, 1, '2011-09-04 07:23:26', '2011-09-04 15:23:26', 'Partly to play around with the Jenkins Remote API, and partly to kickstart a build radiator setup at my current consulting engagement, I wrote a quick radiator page which might serve as a foundation for further experiment by the team. I\'ve seen several build radiators built using multiple technologies - Java, Python, etc.; I specifically chose HTML/jQuery for this effort because a modern browser seems to be the only piece of software universally available on any machine one might care to set up.\r\nThe code is up at <a href="https://github.com/asengupta/jquery-jenkins-radiator">GitHub</a>, and here is the obligatory screenshot :-)\r\n\r\n<a href="http://avishek.net/blog/wp-content/uploads/2011/09/BuildRadiator.png"><img src="http://avishek.net/blog/wp-content/uploads/2011/09/BuildRadiator-300x168.png" alt="" title="BuildRadiator" width="300" height="168" class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-581" /></a>\r\n', 'A jQuery-based build radiator for Jenkins', 0, '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '580-revision-3', '', '', '2011-09-04 07:23:26', '2011-09-04 15:23:26', '', 580, 'http://avishek.net/blog/?p=584', 0, 'revision', '', 0); 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (399, 1, '2011-07-23 00:47:01', '2011-07-23 08:47:01', 'Let\'s start off by stating what the objective is. We are attempting to diagonalise a symmetric matrix.\r\nA symmetric matrix looks like this:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nA=\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\na & d & n & w \\\\\r\nd & b & h & e \\\\\r\nn & h & c & i \\\\\r\nw & e & i & d \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nNotice how the values are reflected across the diagonal a-b-c-d; this holds true for any symmetric matrix. Now, here\'s an example of a diagonal matrix.\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nD=\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\na & 0 & 0 & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & b & 0 & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & 0 & c & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & 0 & 0 & d \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nNotice how all the off-diagonal elements (elements not part of the diagonal) are zero; this holds true for any diagonal matrix.\r\nArmed with that information, we are now in a position to restate the first line: determine the set of matrix operations which will transform a symmetric matrix into a diagonal form. To follow through with the examples above, the question we are asking is, find me a <strong>P</strong> such that:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nP^{-1} .\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\na & d & n & w \\\\\r\nd & b & h & e \\\\\r\nn & h & c & i \\\\\r\nw & e & i & d \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n.P\r\n=\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\np & 0 & 0 & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & q & 0 & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & 0 & r & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & 0 & 0 & s \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nor, more concisely,\r\n[latex]\r\nP^{-1}.A.P = D\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nWhy such an unsightly transformation?\r\nI\'ll probably write about this in a future post, but for now, remember that the eigenvector matrix diagonalises its \'parent\' matrix. In the previous identity, [latex]P[/latex] is the eigenvector matrix.\r\nAnyway, we need to determine [latex]P[/latex]. There are several ways of doing this, and in this post we are describing one such, namely, Jacobi rotations.\r\nHow about we assume that this eigenvector matrix [latex]P[/latex] can be expressed as a product of n matrices [latex]P_1, P_2, \\ldots P_n[/latex]? Then, we can write:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nP = P_1.P_2.P_3 \\ldots P_n\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nSubstituting the above into the diagonalisation identity:\r\n[latex]\r\n(P_1.P_2.P_3 \\ldots P_n)^{-1}.A.(P_1.P_2.P_3 \\ldots P_n) = D\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nThe inverse of a product of matrices is the reversed-order product of the inverse of those same matrices, which is to say:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\n(P_1.P_2.P_3 \\ldots P_n)^{-1} = P_n^{-1} \\ldots P_3^{-1}.P_2^{-1}.P_1^{-1}\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nSubstituting this result gives:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\n\\left( P_n^{-1} \\ldots P_3^{-1}.P_2^{-1}.P_1^{-1} \\right).A.\\left( P_1.P_2.P_3 \\ldots P_n \\right) = D\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nWell, let\'s use the associative property of matrix multiplication to shift around the brackets a bit.\r\n<em>The associative property of matrix multiplication, by the way, says that: [latex]\\left(AB\\right)C = A\\left(BC\\right)[/latex]</em>\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\n\\left(P_n^{-1} \\ldots \\left(P_3^{-1}.\\left(P_2^{-1}.\\left(P_1^{-1}.A.P_1\\right).P_2\\right).P_3\\right)\\ldots P_n\\right) = D\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nThe above grouping can be expressed more concisely as:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nA_{j+1} = P_{j+1}^{-1}.A_j.P_{j+1}\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nLet\'s take a minute to spell out what this means.\r\nWell, before we get into the mechanics of the method, let\'s clarify a thing or two about notation. First, the P<sup>T</sup> notation, this is read as \'P transpose\', or \'P tee\' (as I call it). The transpose of a matrix is simply a matrix whose rows are the columns of the original matrix, and whose columns are the rows of the original matrix. As an illustration:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\na & b & c & d \\\\\r\ne & f & g & h \\\\\r\ni & j & k & l \\\\\r\nm & n & o & p \\end{array} \\right)\\ ^T\r\n=\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\na & e & i & m \\\\\r\nb & f & j & n \\\\\r\nc & g & k & o \\\\\r\nd & h & l & p \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\n', 'Eigenvector algorithms for symmetric matrices: Jacobi rotations', 0, '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '331-revision-66', '', '', '2011-07-23 00:47:01', '2011-07-23 08:47:01', '', 331, 'http://avishek.net/blog/?p=399', 0, 'revision', '', 0); 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (433, 1, '2011-07-24 12:39:00', '2011-07-24 20:39:00', '<h3>Symmetric Matrices / Diagonal Matrices</h3>\r\nA symmetric matrix looks like this:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nA=\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\na & d & n & w \\\\\r\nd & b & h & e \\\\\r\nn & h & c & i \\\\\r\nw & e & i & d \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nNotice how the values are reflected across the diagonal a-b-c-d; this holds true for any symmetric matrix. Now, here\'s an example of a diagonal matrix.\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nD=\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\na & 0 & 0 & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & b & 0 & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & 0 & c & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & 0 & 0 & d \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nNotice how all the off-diagonal elements (elements not part of the diagonal) are zero; this holds true for any diagonal matrix.\r\nLet\'s take a (short) digression and look at a widely-used way of viewing matrices - as linear transformations.\r\n\r\n<h3>Linear Transformations</h3>\r\n\r\n<img src="https://docs.google.com/drawings/pub?id=1UjD6Vj8mBPfUzNQ42og7Z8I_133IafcCblkmEKSyLLM&amp;w=510&amp;h=476"/>\r\nHere is a simple question: find me the matrix P which when multiplied with the vector [latex]\\overrightarrow{r, \\theta}[/latex] gives me the rotated vector [latex]\\overrightarrow{r,\\left(\\theta + \\alpha\\right)}[/latex].\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nP.\\left( \\begin{array}{c}\r\nr cos \\theta \\\\\r\nr sin \\theta \\end{array} \\right).P\r\n=\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{c}\r\nr cos \\left(\\theta+\\alpha\\right) \\\\\r\nr sin \\left(\\theta+\\alpha\\right) \\end{array} \\right)\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nThis is how I do it. Expand the trigonometric expressions for [latex]cos \\left(\\theta+\\alpha\\right)[/latex] and [latex]sin \\left(\\theta+\\alpha\\right)[/latex], so that you get:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nP.\\left( \\begin{array}{c}\r\nr cos \\theta \\\\\r\nr sin \\theta \\end{array} \\right)\r\n=\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{c}\r\nr cos \\theta.cos \\alpha - r sin \\theta.sin \\alpha \\\\\r\nr sin \\theta.cos \\alpha + r cos \\alpha.sin \\theta \\end{array} \\right)\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nA little inspection gives the answer:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nP =\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\ncos \\alpha & -sin \\alpha \\\\\r\nsin \\alpha & cos \\alpha \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nThe matrix P is a linear transformation; why it is linear and what its properties are I\'ll leave to the formal definitions in books. It suffices to say that you can look at a matrix as if it were a map or a function to which you could pass in a vector and get a new vector out of it.\r\nAs in the above example, all matrices have geometrical descriptions: the above one is a rotation vector, for instance. For the purposes of this series, I shall concentrate for the moment on the type of transformation given by a diagonal matrix.\r\n', 'Matrix Theory', 0, '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '331-revision-98', '', '', '2011-07-24 12:39:00', '2011-07-24 20:39:00', '', 331, 'http://avishek.net/blog/?p=433', 0, 'revision', '', 0); 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (400, 1, '2011-07-23 00:58:15', '2011-07-23 08:58:15', 'Let\'s start off by stating what the objective is. We are attempting to diagonalise a symmetric matrix.\r\nA symmetric matrix looks like this:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nA=\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\na & d & n & w \\\\\r\nd & b & h & e \\\\\r\nn & h & c & i \\\\\r\nw & e & i & d \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nNotice how the values are reflected across the diagonal a-b-c-d; this holds true for any symmetric matrix. Now, here\'s an example of a diagonal matrix.\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nD=\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\na & 0 & 0 & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & b & 0 & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & 0 & c & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & 0 & 0 & d \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nNotice how all the off-diagonal elements (elements not part of the diagonal) are zero; this holds true for any diagonal matrix.\r\nArmed with that information, we are now in a position to restate the first line: determine the set of matrix operations which will transform a symmetric matrix into a diagonal form. To follow through with the examples above, the question we are asking is, find me a <strong>P</strong> such that:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nP^{-1} .\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\na & d & n & w \\\\\r\nd & b & h & e \\\\\r\nn & h & c & i \\\\\r\nw & e & i & d \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n.P\r\n=\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\np & 0 & 0 & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & q & 0 & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & 0 & r & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & 0 & 0 & s \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nor, more concisely,\r\n[latex]\r\nP^{-1}.A.P = D\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nWhy such an unsightly transformation?\r\nI\'ll probably write about this in a future post, but for now, remember that the eigenvector matrix diagonalises its \'parent\' matrix. In the previous identity, [latex]P[/latex] is the eigenvector matrix.\r\nAnyway, we need to determine [latex]P[/latex]. There are several ways of doing this, and in this post we are describing one such, namely, Jacobi rotations.\r\nHow about we assume that this eigenvector matrix [latex]P[/latex] can be expressed as a product of n matrices [latex]P_1, P_2, \\ldots P_n[/latex]? Then, we can write:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nP = P_1.P_2.P_3 \\ldots P_n\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nSubstituting the above into the diagonalisation identity:\r\n[latex]\r\n(P_1.P_2.P_3 \\ldots P_n)^{-1}.A.(P_1.P_2.P_3 \\ldots P_n) = D\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nThe inverse of a product of matrices is the reversed-order product of the inverse of those same matrices, which is to say:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\n(P_1.P_2.P_3 \\ldots P_n)^{-1} = P_n^{-1} \\ldots P_3^{-1}.P_2^{-1}.P_1^{-1}\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nSubstituting this result gives:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\n\\left( P_n^{-1} \\ldots P_3^{-1}.P_2^{-1}.P_1^{-1} \\right).A.\\left( P_1.P_2.P_3 \\ldots P_n \\right) = D\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nWell, let\'s use the associative property of matrix multiplication to shift around the brackets a bit.\r\n<em>The associative property of matrix multiplication, by the way, says that: [latex]\\left(AB\\right)C = A\\left(BC\\right)[/latex]</em>\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\n\\left(P_n^{-1} \\ldots \\left(P_3^{-1}.\\left(P_2^{-1}.\\left(P_1^{-1}.A.P_1\\right).P_2\\right).P_3\\right)\\ldots P_n\\right) = D\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nThe above grouping can be expressed more concisely as:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nA_{j+1} = P_{j+1}^{-1}.A_j.P_{j+1}\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nLet\'s take a minute to spell out what this means.\r\nIf we (somehow) know all the matrices [latex]P_1, P_2, \\ldots P_n[/latex], then we can get to D, by repeatedly carrying out the above matrix operation.\r\nAlright, now the question arises as to what these matrices should be. Well, one clear sign that we are moving in the right direction is, if during the course of these recurring operations, [latex]A_{j}[/latex] becomes increasingly diagonal. In other words, more off-diagonal elements get zeroed while we are doing these multiplications.\r\nBut exactly what sort of matrix does this?\r\n\r\nLet\'s take a (short) digression and look at a fundamental operation in computer graphics/vector algebra.\r\n\r\nWell, before we get into the mechanics of the method, let\'s clarify a thing or two about notation. First, the P<sup>T</sup> notation, this is read as \'P transpose\', or \'P tee\' (as I call it). The transpose of a matrix is simply a matrix whose rows are the columns of the original matrix, and whose columns are the rows of the original matrix. As an illustration:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\na & b & c & d \\\\\r\ne & f & g & h \\\\\r\ni & j & k & l \\\\\r\nm & n & o & p \\end{array} \\right)\\ ^T\r\n=\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\na & e & i & m \\\\\r\nb & f & j & n \\\\\r\nc & g & k & o \\\\\r\nd & h & l & p \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\n', 'Eigenvector algorithms for symmetric matrices: Jacobi rotations', 0, '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '331-revision-67', '', '', '2011-07-23 00:58:15', '2011-07-23 08:58:15', '', 331, 'http://avishek.net/blog/?p=400', 0, 'revision', '', 0); 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (401, 1, '2011-07-23 01:03:24', '2011-07-23 09:03:24', 'Let\'s start off by stating what the objective is. We are attempting to diagonalise a symmetric matrix.\r\n\r\n<h3>Symmetric Matrices / Diagonal Matrices</h3>\r\nA symmetric matrix looks like this:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nA=\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\na & d & n & w \\\\\r\nd & b & h & e \\\\\r\nn & h & c & i \\\\\r\nw & e & i & d \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nNotice how the values are reflected across the diagonal a-b-c-d; this holds true for any symmetric matrix. Now, here\'s an example of a diagonal matrix.\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nD=\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\na & 0 & 0 & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & b & 0 & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & 0 & c & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & 0 & 0 & d \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nNotice how all the off-diagonal elements (elements not part of the diagonal) are zero; this holds true for any diagonal matrix.\r\n\r\n<h3>Problem Statement, restated</h3>\r\nArmed with that information, we are now in a position to restate the first line: determine the set of matrix operations which will transform a symmetric matrix into a diagonal form. To follow through with the examples above, the question we are asking is, find me a <strong>P</strong> such that:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nP^{-1} .\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\na & d & n & w \\\\\r\nd & b & h & e \\\\\r\nn & h & c & i \\\\\r\nw & e & i & d \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n.P\r\n=\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\np & 0 & 0 & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & q & 0 & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & 0 & r & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & 0 & 0 & s \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nor, more concisely,\r\n[latex]\r\nP^{-1}.A.P = D\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nWhy such an unsightly transformation?\r\nI\'ll probably write about this in a future post, but for now, remember that the eigenvector matrix diagonalises its \'parent\' matrix. In the previous identity, [latex]P[/latex] is the eigenvector matrix.\r\nAnyway, we need to determine [latex]P[/latex]. There are several ways of doing this, and in this post we are describing one such, namely, Jacobi rotations.\r\n\r\n<h3>The shape of the solution</h3>\r\nHow about we assume that this eigenvector matrix [latex]P[/latex] can be expressed as a product of n matrices [latex]P_1, P_2, \\ldots P_n[/latex]? Then, we can write:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nP = P_1.P_2.P_3 \\ldots P_n\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nSubstituting the above into the diagonalisation identity:\r\n[latex]\r\n(P_1.P_2.P_3 \\ldots P_n)^{-1}.A.(P_1.P_2.P_3 \\ldots P_n) = D\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nThe inverse of a product of matrices is the reversed-order product of the inverse of those same matrices, which is to say:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\n(P_1.P_2.P_3 \\ldots P_n)^{-1} = P_n^{-1} \\ldots P_3^{-1}.P_2^{-1}.P_1^{-1}\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nSubstituting this result gives:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\n\\left( P_n^{-1} \\ldots P_3^{-1}.P_2^{-1}.P_1^{-1} \\right).A.\\left( P_1.P_2.P_3 \\ldots P_n \\right) = D\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nWell, let\'s use the associative property of matrix multiplication to shift around the brackets a bit.\r\n<em>The associative property of matrix multiplication, by the way, says that: [latex]\\left(AB\\right)C = A\\left(BC\\right)[/latex]</em>\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\n\\left(P_n^{-1} \\ldots \\left(P_3^{-1}.\\left(P_2^{-1}.\\left(P_1^{-1}.A.P_1\\right).P_2\\right).P_3\\right)\\ldots P_n\\right) = D\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nThe above grouping can be expressed more concisely as:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nA_{j+1} = P_{j+1}^{-1}.A_j.P_{j+1}\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nLet\'s take a minute to spell out what this means.\r\nIf we (somehow) know all the matrices [latex]P_1, P_2, \\ldots P_n[/latex], then we can get to D, by repeatedly carrying out the above matrix operation.\r\nAlright, now the question arises as to what these matrices should be. Well, one clear sign that we are moving in the right direction is, if during the course of these recurring operations, [latex]A_{j}[/latex] becomes increasingly diagonal. In other words, more off-diagonal elements get zeroed while we are doing these multiplications.\r\nBut exactly what sort of matrix does this?\r\n\r\nLet\'s take a (short) digression and look at a fundamental operation in computer graphics/vector algebra.\r\n\r\n<h3>Vector Rotations</h3>\r\nWell, before we get into the mechanics of the method, let\'s clarify a thing or two about notation. First, the P<sup>T</sup> notation, this is read as \'P transpose\', or \'P tee\' (as I call it). The transpose of a matrix is simply a matrix whose rows are the columns of the original matrix, and whose columns are the rows of the original matrix. As an illustration:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\na & b & c & d \\\\\r\ne & f & g & h \\\\\r\ni & j & k & l \\\\\r\nm & n & o & p \\end{array} \\right)\\ ^T\r\n=\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\na & e & i & m \\\\\r\nb & f & j & n \\\\\r\nc & g & k & o \\\\\r\nd & h & l & p \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\n', 'Eigenvector algorithms for symmetric matrices: Jacobi rotations', 0, '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '331-revision-68', '', '', '2011-07-23 01:03:24', '2011-07-23 09:03:24', '', 331, 'http://avishek.net/blog/?p=401', 0, 'revision', '', 0); 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (402, 1, '2011-07-23 02:13:41', '2011-07-23 10:13:41', 'Let\'s start off by stating what the objective is. We are attempting to diagonalise a symmetric matrix.\r\n\r\n<h3>Symmetric Matrices / Diagonal Matrices</h3>\r\nA symmetric matrix looks like this:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nA=\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\na & d & n & w \\\\\r\nd & b & h & e \\\\\r\nn & h & c & i \\\\\r\nw & e & i & d \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nNotice how the values are reflected across the diagonal a-b-c-d; this holds true for any symmetric matrix. Now, here\'s an example of a diagonal matrix.\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nD=\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\na & 0 & 0 & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & b & 0 & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & 0 & c & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & 0 & 0 & d \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nNotice how all the off-diagonal elements (elements not part of the diagonal) are zero; this holds true for any diagonal matrix.\r\n\r\n<h3>Problem Statement, restated</h3>\r\nArmed with that information, we are now in a position to restate the first line: determine the set of matrix operations which will transform a symmetric matrix into a diagonal form. To follow through with the examples above, the question we are asking is, find me a <strong>P</strong> such that:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nP^{-1} .\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\na & d & n & w \\\\\r\nd & b & h & e \\\\\r\nn & h & c & i \\\\\r\nw & e & i & d \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n.P\r\n=\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\np & 0 & 0 & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & q & 0 & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & 0 & r & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & 0 & 0 & s \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nor, more concisely,\r\n[latex]\r\nP^{-1}.A.P = D\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nWhy such an unsightly transformation?\r\nI\'ll probably write about this in a future post, but for now, remember that the eigenvector matrix diagonalises its \'parent\' matrix. In the previous identity, [latex]P[/latex] is the eigenvector matrix.\r\nAnyway, we need to determine [latex]P[/latex]. There are several ways of doing this, and in this post we are describing one such, namely, Jacobi rotations.\r\n\r\n<h3>The shape of the solution</h3>\r\nHow about we assume that this eigenvector matrix [latex]P[/latex] can be expressed as a product of n matrices [latex]P_1, P_2, \\ldots P_n[/latex]? Then, we can write:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nP = P_1.P_2.P_3 \\ldots P_n\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nSubstituting the above into the diagonalisation identity:\r\n[latex]\r\n(P_1.P_2.P_3 \\ldots P_n)^{-1}.A.(P_1.P_2.P_3 \\ldots P_n) = D\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nThe inverse of a product of matrices is the reversed-order product of the inverse of those same matrices, which is to say:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\n(P_1.P_2.P_3 \\ldots P_n)^{-1} = P_n^{-1} \\ldots P_3^{-1}.P_2^{-1}.P_1^{-1}\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nSubstituting this result gives:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\n\\left( P_n^{-1} \\ldots P_3^{-1}.P_2^{-1}.P_1^{-1} \\right).A.\\left( P_1.P_2.P_3 \\ldots P_n \\right) = D\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nWell, let\'s use the associative property of matrix multiplication to shift around the brackets a bit.\r\n<em>The associative property of matrix multiplication, by the way, says that: [latex]\\left(AB\\right)C = A\\left(BC\\right)[/latex]</em>\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\n\\left(P_n^{-1} \\ldots \\left(P_3^{-1}.\\left(P_2^{-1}.\\left(P_1^{-1}.A.P_1\\right).P_2\\right).P_3\\right)\\ldots P_n\\right) = D\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nThe above grouping can be expressed more concisely as:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nA_{j+1} = P_{j+1}^{-1}.A_j.P_{j+1}\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nLet\'s take a minute to spell out what this means.\r\nIf we (somehow) know all the matrices [latex]P_1, P_2, \\ldots P_n[/latex], then we can get to D, by repeatedly carrying out the above matrix operation.\r\nAlright, now the question arises as to what these matrices should be. Well, one clear sign that we are moving in the right direction is, if during the course of these recurring operations, [latex]A_{j}[/latex] becomes increasingly diagonal. In other words, more off-diagonal elements get zeroed while we are doing these multiplications.\r\nBut exactly what sort of matrix does this?\r\n\r\nLet\'s take a (short) digression and look at a fundamental operation in computer graphics/vector algebra.\r\n\r\n<h3>Vector Rotations</h3>\r\n\r\n<img src="https://docs.google.com/drawings/pub?id=1UjD6Vj8mBPfUzNQ42og7Z8I_133IafcCblkmEKSyLLM&amp;w=510&amp;h=476"/>\r\nHere is a simple question: find me the matrix which when multiplied with the vector [latex]r cos \\theta[/latex] gives me the rotated vector [latex]r cos \\left(\\theta + \\alpha\\right)[/latex].\r\n\r\nWell, before we get into the mechanics of the method, let\'s clarify a thing or two about notation. First, the P<sup>T</sup> notation, this is read as \'P transpose\', or \'P tee\' (as I call it). The transpose of a matrix is simply a matrix whose rows are the columns of the original matrix, and whose columns are the rows of the original matrix. As an illustration:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\na & b & c & d \\\\\r\ne & f & g & h \\\\\r\ni & j & k & l \\\\\r\nm & n & o & p \\end{array} \\right)\\ ^T\r\n=\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\na & e & i & m \\\\\r\nb & f & j & n \\\\\r\nc & g & k & o \\\\\r\nd & h & l & p \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\n', 'Eigenvector algorithms for symmetric matrices: Jacobi rotations', 0, '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '331-revision-69', '', '', '2011-07-23 02:13:41', '2011-07-23 10:13:41', '', 331, 'http://avishek.net/blog/?p=402', 0, 'revision', '', 0); 
