cations.\r\nBut exactly what sort of matrix does this?\r\n\r\nLet\'s take a (short) digression and look at a fundamental operation in computer graphics/vector algebra.\r\n\r\n<h3>Vector Rotations</h3>\r\n\r\n<img src="https://docs.google.com/drawings/pub?id=1UjD6Vj8mBPfUzNQ42og7Z8I_133IafcCblkmEKSyLLM&amp;w=510&amp;h=476"/>\r\nHere is a simple question: find me the matrix P which when multiplied with the vector [latex]\\overrightarrow{r, \\theta}[/latex] gives me the rotated vector [latex]\\overrightarrow{r,\\left(\\theta + \\alpha\\right)}[/latex].\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nP.\\left( \\begin{array}{c}\r\nr cos \\theta \\\\\r\nr sin \\theta \\end{array} \\right).P\r\n=\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{c}\r\nr cos \\left(\\theta+\\alpha\\right) \\\\\r\nr sin \\left(\\theta+\\alpha\\right) \\end{array} \\right)\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nThis is how I do it. Expand the trigonometric expressions for [latex]cos \\left(\\theta+\\alpha\\right)[/latex] and [latex]sin \\left(\\theta+\\alpha\\right)[/latex], so that you get:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nP.\\left( \\begin{array}{c}\r\nr cos \\theta \\\\\r\nr sin \\theta \\end{array} \\right)\r\n=\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{c}\r\nr cos \\theta.cos \\alpha - sin \\theta.sin \\alpha \\\\\r\nr sin \\theta.cos \\alpha + cos \\alpha.sin \\theta \\end{array} \\right)\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nA little inspection gives the answer:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nP =\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\ncos \\alpha & -sin \\alpha \\\\\r\nsin \\alpha & cos \\alpha \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nLet\'s take a moment to examine one or two properties of this rotation matrix. The most important property of this matrix is that it is orthogonal, that is, the norm of its rows and columns is one. Since it is orthogonal, its transpose is equal to its inverse, that is:\r\n[latex]\r\nP^{-1}=P^T=\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\ncos \\alpha & sin \\alpha \\\\\r\n-sin \\alpha & cos \\alpha \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\n<h3>Where it all comes together</h3>\r\nHow do we exploit this identity in answering our original question? Well, the basic idea is that we want a rotation to be applied to the original matrix, such that a given element, say [latex]A_{mn}[/latex] gets zeroed.\r\nLet\'s return to our original recurrence relation:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nA_{j+1} = P_{j+1}^{-1}.A_j.P_{j+1}\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nWe want to substitute P for our rotation matrix, so that (because P is orthogonal) we can write:\r\n[latex]\r\nA_{j+1} = P_{j+1}^T.A_j.P_{j+1}\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nTo be able to substitute P for our rotation matrix, we need to generalise the matrix somewhat; it\'s still 2x2 from the previous section. For that, we need to decide which element we want to zero, in our case this is [latex]A_{mn}[/latex].\r\nThe generalised rotation matrix is then:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\n\\left( \\begin{matrix}\r\n1 &  0  & \\ldots & 0\\\\\r\n0  &  \\ddots & \\vdots & \\ddots\\\\\r\n\\vdots & \\vdots & \\ddots & \\vdots\\\\\r\n0  &   0       &\\ldots & a_{nn}\r\n\\end{matrix} \\right)\\\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nAlright, so we know what P to apply...wait, not quite. There is still the question of what value of [latex]\\alpha[/latex] should be used for each transformation. ', 'Eigenvector algorithms for symmetric matrices: Jacobi rotations', 0, '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '331-revision-86', '', '', '2011-07-23 04:38:16', '2011-07-23 12:38:16', '', 331, 'http://avishek.net/blog/?p=419', 0, 'revision', '', 0); 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (420, 1, '2011-07-23 04:39:38', '2011-07-23 12:39:38', 'Let\'s start off by stating what the objective is. We are attempting to diagonalise a symmetric matrix.\r\n\r\n<h3>Symmetric Matrices / Diagonal Matrices</h3>\r\nA symmetric matrix looks like this:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nA=\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\na & d & n & w \\\\\r\nd & b & h & e \\\\\r\nn & h & c & i \\\\\r\nw & e & i & d \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nNotice how the values are reflected across the diagonal a-b-c-d; this holds true for any symmetric matrix. Now, here\'s an example of a diagonal matrix.\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nD=\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\na & 0 & 0 & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & b & 0 & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & 0 & c & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & 0 & 0 & d \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nNotice how all the off-diagonal elements (elements not part of the diagonal) are zero; this holds true for any diagonal matrix.\r\n\r\n<h3>Problem Statement, restated</h3>\r\nArmed with that information, we are now in a position to restate the first line: determine the set of matrix operations which will transform a symmetric matrix into a diagonal form. To follow through with the examples above, the question we are asking is, find me a <strong>P</strong> such that:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nP^{-1} .\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\na & d & n & w \\\\\r\nd & b & h & e \\\\\r\nn & h & c & i \\\\\r\nw & e & i & d \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n.P\r\n=\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\np & 0 & 0 & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & q & 0 & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & 0 & r & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & 0 & 0 & s \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nor, more concisely,\r\n[latex]\r\nP^{-1}.A.P = D\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nWhy such an unsightly transformation?\r\nI\'ll probably write about this in a future post, but for now, remember that the eigenvector matrix diagonalises its \'parent\' matrix. In the previous identity, [latex]P[/latex] is the eigenvector matrix.\r\nAnyway, we need to determine [latex]P[/latex]. There are several ways of doing this, and in this post we are describing one such, namely, Jacobi rotations.\r\n\r\n<h3>The shape of the solution</h3>\r\nHow about we assume that this eigenvector matrix [latex]P[/latex] can be expressed as a product of n matrices [latex]P_1, P_2, \\ldots P_n[/latex]? Then, we can write:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nP = P_1.P_2.P_3 \\ldots P_n\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nSubstituting the above into the diagonalisation identity:\r\n[latex]\r\n(P_1.P_2.P_3 \\ldots P_n)^{-1}.A.(P_1.P_2.P_3 \\ldots P_n) = D\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nThe inverse of a product of matrices is the reversed-order product of the inverse of those same matrices, which is to say:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\n(P_1.P_2.P_3 \\ldots P_n)^{-1} = P_n^{-1} \\ldots P_3^{-1}.P_2^{-1}.P_1^{-1}\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nSubstituting this result gives:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\n\\left( P_n^{-1} \\ldots P_3^{-1}.P_2^{-1}.P_1^{-1} \\right).A.\\left( P_1.P_2.P_3 \\ldots P_n \\right) = D\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nWell, let\'s use the associative property of matrix multiplication to shift around the brackets a bit.\r\n<em>The associative property of matrix multiplication, by the way, says that: [latex]\\left(AB\\right)C = A\\left(BC\\right)[/latex]</em>\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\n\\left(P_n^{-1} \\ldots \\left(P_3^{-1}.\\left(P_2^{-1}.\\left(P_1^{-1}.A.P_1\\right).P_2\\right).P_3\\right)\\ldots P_n\\right) = D\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nThe above grouping can be expressed more concisely as:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nA_{j+1} = P_{j+1}^{-1}.A_j.P_{j+1}\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nLet\'s take a minute to spell out what this means.\r\nIf we (somehow) know all the matrices [latex]P_1, P_2, \\ldots P_n[/latex], then we can get to D, by repeatedly carrying out the above matrix operation.\r\nAlright, now the question arises as to what these matrices should be. Well, one clear sign that we are moving in the right direction is, if during the course of these recurring operations, [latex]A_{j}[/latex] becomes increasingly diagonal. In other words, more off-diagonal elements get zeroed while we are doing these multiplications.\r\nBut exactly what sort of matrix does this?\r\n\r\nLet\'s take a (short) digression and look at a fundamental operation in computer graphics/vector algebra.\r\n\r\n<h3>Vector Rotations</h3>\r\n\r\n<img src="https://docs.google.com/drawings/pub?id=1UjD6Vj8mBPfUzNQ42og7Z8I_133IafcCblkmEKSyLLM&amp;w=510&amp;h=476"/>\r\nHere is a simple question: find me the matrix P which when multiplied with the vector [latex]\\overrightarrow{r, \\theta}[/latex] gives me the rotated vector [latex]\\overrightarrow{r,\\left(\\theta + \\alpha\\right)}[/latex].\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nP.\\left( \\begin{array}{c}\r\nr cos \\theta \\\\\r\nr sin \\theta \\end{array} \\right).P\r\n=\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{c}\r\nr cos \\left(\\theta+\\alpha\\right) \\\\\r\nr sin \\left(\\theta+\\alpha\\right) \\end{array} \\right)\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nThis is how I do it. Expand the trigonometric expressions for [latex]cos \\left(\\theta+\\alpha\\right)[/latex] and [latex]sin \\left(\\theta+\\alpha\\right)[/latex], so that you get:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nP.\\left( \\begin{array}{c}\r\nr cos \\theta \\\\\r\nr sin \\theta \\end{array} \\right)\r\n=\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{c}\r\nr cos \\theta.cos \\alpha - sin \\theta.sin \\alpha \\\\\r\nr sin \\theta.cos \\alpha + cos \\alpha.sin \\theta \\end{array} \\right)\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nA little inspection gives the answer:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nP =\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\ncos \\alpha & -sin \\alpha \\\\\r\nsin \\alpha & cos \\alpha \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nLet\'s take a moment to examine one or two properties of this rotation matrix. The most important property of this matrix is that it is orthogonal, that is, the norm of its rows and columns is one. Since it is orthogonal, its transpose is equal to its inverse, that is:\r\n[latex]\r\nP^{-1}=P^T=\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\ncos \\alpha & sin \\alpha \\\\\r\n-sin \\alpha & cos \\alpha \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\n<h3>Where it all comes together</h3>\r\nHow do we exploit this identity in answering our original question? Well, the basic idea is that we want a rotation to be applied to the original matrix, such that a given element, say [latex]A_{mn}[/latex] gets zeroed.\r\nLet\'s return to our original recurrence relation:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nA_{j+1} = P_{j+1}^{-1}.A_j.P_{j+1}\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nWe want to substitute P for our rotation matrix, so that (because P is orthogonal) we can write:\r\n[latex]\r\nA_{j+1} = P_{j+1}^T.A_j.P_{j+1}\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nTo be able to substitute P for our rotation matrix, we need to generalise the matrix somewhat; it\'s still 2x2 from the previous section. For that, we need to decide which element we want to zero, in our case this is [latex]A_{mn}[/latex].\r\nThe generalised rotation matrix is then:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\n\\left( \\begin{matrix}\r\n1 &  0  & \\ldots & 0\\\\\r\n0  &  \\ddots & \\vdots & \\iddots\\\\\r\n\\vdots & \\vdots & \\ddots & \\vdots\\\\\r\n0  &   0       &\\ldots & a_{nn}\r\n\\end{matrix} \\right)\\\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nAlright, so we know what P to apply...wait, not quite. There is still the question of what value of [latex]\\alpha[/latex] should be used for each transformation. ', 'Eigenvector algorithms for symmetric matrices: Jacobi rotations', 0, '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '331-revision-87', '', '', '2011-07-23 04:39:38', '2011-07-23 12:39:38', '', 331, 'http://avishek.net/blog/?p=420', 0, 'revision', '', 0); 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (422, 1, '2011-07-23 04:51:29', '2011-07-23 12:51:29', 'Let\'s start off by stating what the objective is. We are attempting to diagonalise a symmetric matrix.\r\n\r\n<h3>Symmetric Matrices / Diagonal Matrices</h3>\r\nA symmetric matrix looks like this:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nA=\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\na & d & n & w \\\\\r\nd & b & h & e \\\\\r\nn & h & c & i \\\\\r\nw & e & i & d \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nNotice how the values are reflected across the diagonal a-b-c-d; this holds true for any symmetric matrix. Now, here\'s an example of a diagonal matrix.\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nD=\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\na & 0 & 0 & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & b & 0 & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & 0 & c & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & 0 & 0 & d \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nNotice how all the off-diagonal elements (elements not part of the diagonal) are zero; this holds true for any diagonal matrix.\r\n\r\n<h3>Problem Statement, restated</h3>\r\nArmed with that information, we are now in a position to restate the first line: determine the set of matrix operations which will transform a symmetric matrix into a diagonal form. To follow through with the examples above, the question we are asking is, find me a <strong>P</strong> such that:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nP^{-1} .\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\na & d & n & w \\\\\r\nd & b & h & e \\\\\r\nn & h & c & i \\\\\r\nw & e & i & d \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n.P\r\n=\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\np & 0 & 0 & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & q & 0 & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & 0 & r & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & 0 & 0 & s \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nor, more concisely,\r\n[latex]\r\nP^{-1}.A.P = D\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nWhy such an unsightly transformation?\r\nI\'ll probably write about this in a future post, but for now, remember that the eigenvector matrix diagonalises its \'parent\' matrix. In the previous identity, [latex]P[/latex] is the eigenvector matrix.\r\nAnyway, we need to determine [latex]P[/latex]. There are several ways of doing this, and in this post we are describing one such, namely, Jacobi rotations.\r\n\r\n<h3>The shape of the solution</h3>\r\nHow about we assume that this eigenvector matrix [latex]P[/latex] can be expressed as a product of n matrices [latex]P_1, P_2, \\ldots P_n[/latex]? Then, we can write:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nP = P_1.P_2.P_3 \\ldots P_n\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nSubstituting the above into the diagonalisation identity:\r\n[latex]\r\n(P_1.P_2.P_3 \\ldots P_n)^{-1}.A.(P_1.P_2.P_3 \\ldots P_n) = D\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nThe inverse of a product of matrices is the reversed-order product of the inverse of those same matrices, which is to say:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\n(P_1.P_2.P_3 \\ldots P_n)^{-1} = P_n^{-1} \\ldots P_3^{-1}.P_2^{-1}.P_1^{-1}\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nSubstituting this result gives:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\n\\left( P_n^{-1} \\ldots P_3^{-1}.P_2^{-1}.P_1^{-1} \\right).A.\\left( P_1.P_2.P_3 \\ldots P_n \\right) = D\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nWell, let\'s use the associative property of matrix multiplication to shift around the brackets a bit.\r\n<em>The associative property of matrix multiplication, by the way, says that: [latex]\\left(AB\\right)C = A\\left(BC\\right)[/latex]</em>\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\n\\left(P_n^{-1} \\ldots \\left(P_3^{-1}.\\left(P_2^{-1}.\\left(P_1^{-1}.A.P_1\\right).P_2\\right).P_3\\right)\\ldots P_n\\right) = D\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nThe above grouping can be expressed more concisely as:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nA_{j+1} = P_{j+1}^{-1}.A_j.P_{j+1}\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nLet\'s take a minute to spell out what this means.\r\nIf we (somehow) know all the matrices [latex]P_1, P_2, \\ldots P_n[/latex], then we can get to D, by repeatedly carrying out the above matrix operation.\r\nAlright, now the question arises as to what these matrices should be. Well, one clear sign that we are moving in the right direction is, if during the course of these recurring operations, [latex]A_{j}[/latex] becomes increasingly diagonal. In other words, more off-diagonal elements get zeroed while we are doing these multiplications.\r\nBut exactly what sort of matrix does this?\r\n\r\nLet\'s take a (short) digression and look at a fundamental operation in computer graphics/vector algebra.\r\n\r\n<h3>Vector Rotations</h3>\r\n\r\n<img src="https://docs.google.com/drawings/pub?id=1UjD6Vj8mBPfUzNQ42og7Z8I_133IafcCblkmEKSyLLM&amp;w=510&amp;h=476"/>\r\nHere is a simple question: find me the matrix P which when multiplied with the vector [latex]\\overrightarrow{r, \\theta}[/latex] gives me the rotated vector [latex]\\overrightarrow{r,\\left(\\theta + \\alpha\\right)}[/latex].\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nP.\\left( \\begin{array}{c}\r\nr cos \\theta \\\\\r\nr sin \\theta \\end{array} \\right).P\r\n=\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{c}\r\nr cos \\left(\\theta+\\alpha\\right) \\\\\r\nr sin \\left(\\theta+\\alpha\\right) \\end{array} \\right)\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nThis is how I do it. Expand the trigonometric expressions for [latex]cos \\left(\\theta+\\alpha\\right)[/latex] and [latex]sin \\left(\\theta+\\alpha\\right)[/latex], so that you get:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nP.\\left( \\begin{array}{c}\r\nr cos \\theta \\\\\r\nr sin \\theta \\end{array} \\right)\r\n=\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{c}\r\nr cos \\theta.cos \\alpha - sin \\theta.sin \\alpha \\\\\r\nr sin \\theta.cos \\alpha + cos \\alpha.sin \\theta \\end{array} \\right)\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nA little inspection gives the answer:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nP =\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\ncos \\alpha & -sin \\alpha \\\\\r\nsin \\alpha & cos \\alpha \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nLet\'s take a moment to examine one or two properties of this rotation matrix. The most important property of this matrix is that it is orthogonal, that is, the norm of its rows and columns is one. Since it is orthogonal, its transpose is equal to its inverse, that is:\r\n[latex]\r\nP^{-1}=P^T=\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\ncos \\alpha & sin \\alpha \\\\\r\n-sin \\alpha & cos \\alpha \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\n<h3>Where it all comes together</h3>\r\nHow do we exploit this identity in answering our original question? Well, the basic idea is that we want a rotation to be applied to the original matrix, such that a given element, say [latex]A_{mn}[/latex] gets zeroed.\r\nLet\'s return to our original recurrence relation:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nA_{j+1} = P_{j+1}^{-1}.A_j.P_{j+1}\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nWe want to substitute P for our rotation matrix, so that (because P is orthogonal) we can write:\r\n[latex]\r\nA_{j+1} = P_{j+1}^T.A_j.P_{j+1}\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nTo be able to substitute P for our rotation matrix, we need to generalise the matrix somewhat; it\'s still 2x2 from the previous section. For that, we need to decide which element we want to zero, in our case this is [latex]A_{mn}[/latex].\r\nThe generalised rotation matrix is then:\r\n\r\n<img alt="" src="http://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/JacobiRotationMatrix/NumberedEquation2.gif" title="JacobiRotation" class="alignnone" width="278" height="138" />\r\n\r\nAlright, so we know what P to apply...wait, not quite. There is still the question of what value of [latex]\\alpha[/latex] should be used for each transformation. Also, the effect of the rotation matrix on the matrix A<sub>j</sub> still needs calculation. This and more I shall cover in the next post.', 'Eigenvector algorithms for symmetric matrices: Jacobi rotations, Part 1', 0, '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '331-revision-89', '', '', '2011-07-23 04:51:29', '2011-07-23 12:51:29', '', 331, 'http://avishek.net/blog/?p=422', 0, 'revision', '', 0); 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (423, 1, '2011-07-23 04:51:50', '2011-07-23 12:51:50', 'Let\'s start off by stating what the objective is. We are attempting to diagonalise a symmetric matrix.\r\n\r\n<h3>Symmetric Matrices / Diagonal Matrices</h3>\r\nA symmetric matrix looks like this:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nA=\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\na & d & n & w \\\\\r\nd & b & h & e \\\\\r\nn & h & c & i \\\\\r\nw & e & i & d \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nNotice how the values are reflected across the diagonal a-b-c-d; this holds true for any symmetric matrix. Now, here\'s an example of a diagonal matrix.\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nD=\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\na & 0 & 0 & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & b & 0 & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & 0 & c & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & 0 & 0 & d \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nNotice how all the off-diagonal elements (elements not part of the diagonal) are zero; this holds true for any diagonal matrix.\r\n\r\n<h3>Problem Statement, restated</h3>\r\nArmed with that information, we are now in a position to restate the first line: determine the set of matrix operations which will transform a symmetric matrix into a diagonal form. To follow through with the examples above, the question we are asking is, find me a <strong>P</strong> such that:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nP^{-1} .\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\na & d & n & w \\\\\r\nd & b & h & e \\\\\r\nn & h & c & i \\\\\r\nw & e & i & d \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n.P\r\n=\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\np & 0 & 0 & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & q & 0 & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & 0 & r & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & 0 & 0 & s \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nor, more concisely,\r\n[latex]\r\nP^{-1}.A.P = D\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nWhy such an unsightly transformation?\r\nI\'ll probably write about this in a future post, but for now, remember that the eigenvector matrix diagonalises its \'parent\' matrix. In the previous identity, [latex]P[/latex] is the eigenvector matrix.\r\nAnyway, we need to determine [latex]P[/latex]. There are several ways of doing this, and in this post we are describing one such, namely, Jacobi rotations.\r\n\r\n<h3>The shape of the solution</h3>\r\nHow about we assume that this eigenvector matrix [latex]P[/latex] can be expressed as a product of n matrices [latex]P_1, P_2, \\ldots P_n[/latex]? Then, we can write:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nP = P_1.P_2.P_3 \\ldots P_n\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nSubstituting the above into the diagonalisation identity:\r\n[latex]\r\n(P_1.P_2.P_3 \\ldots P_n)^{-1}.A.(P_1.P_2.P_3 \\ldots P_n) = D\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nThe inverse of a product of matrices is the reversed-order product of the inverse of those same matrices, which is to say:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\n(P_1.P_2.P_3 \\ldots P_n)^{-1} = P_n^{-1} \\ldots P_3^{-1}.P_2^{-1}.P_1^{-1}\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nSubstituting this result gives:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\n\\left( P_n^{-1} \\ldots P_3^{-1}.P_2^{-1}.P_1^{-1} \\right).A.\\left( P_1.P_2.P_3 \\ldots P_n \\right) = D\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nWell, let\'s use the associative property of matrix multiplication to shift around the brackets a bit.\r\n<em>The associative property of matrix multiplication, by the way, says that: [latex]\\left(AB\\right)C = A\\left(BC\\right)[/latex]</em>\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\n\\left(P_n^{-1} \\ldots \\left(P_3^{-1}.\\left(P_2^{-1}.\\left(P_1^{-1}.A.P_1\\right).P_2\\right).P_3\\right)\\ldots P_n\\right) = D\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nThe above grouping can be expressed more concisely as:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nA_{j+1} = P_{j+1}^{-1}.A_j.P_{j+1}\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nLet\'s take a minute to spell out what this means.\r\nIf we (somehow) know all the matrices [latex]P_1, P_2, \\ldots P_n[/latex], then we can get to D, by repeatedly carrying out the above matrix operation.\r\nAlright, now the question arises as to what these matrices should be. Well, one clear sign that we are moving in the right direction is, if during the course of these recurring operations, [latex]A_{j}[/latex] becomes increasingly diagonal. In other words, more off-diagonal elements get zeroed while we are doing these multiplications.\r\nBut exactly what sort of matrix does this?\r\n\r\nLet\'s take a (short) digression and look at a fundamental operation in computer graphics/vector algebra.\r\n\r\n<h3>Vector Rotations</h3>\r\n\r\n<img src="https://docs.google.com/drawings/pub?id=1UjD6Vj8mBPfUzNQ42og7Z8I_133IafcCblkmEKSyLLM&amp;w=510&amp;h=476"/>\r\nHere is a simple question: find me the matrix P which when multiplied with the vector [latex]\\overrightarrow{r, \\theta}[/latex] gives me the rotated vector [latex]\\overrightarrow{r,\\left(\\theta + \\alpha\\right)}[/latex].\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nP.\\left( \\begin{array}{c}\r\nr cos \\theta \\\\\r\nr sin \\theta \\end{array} \\right).P\r\n=\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{c}\r\nr cos \\left(\\theta+\\alpha\\right) \\\\\r\nr sin \\left(\\theta+\\alpha\\right) \\end{array} \\right)\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nThis is how I do it. Expand the trigonometric expressions for [latex]cos \\left(\\theta+\\alpha\\right)[/latex] and [latex]sin \\left(\\theta+\\alpha\\right)[/latex], so that you get:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nP.\\left( \\begin{array}{c}\r\nr cos \\theta \\\\\r\nr sin \\theta \\end{array} \\right)\r\n=\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{c}\r\nr cos \\theta.cos \\alpha - sin \\theta.sin \\alpha \\\\\r\nr sin \\theta.cos \\alpha + cos \\alpha.sin \\theta \\end{array} \\right)\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nA little inspection gives the answer:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nP =\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\ncos \\alpha & -sin \\alpha \\\\\r\nsin \\alpha & cos \\alpha \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nLet\'s take a moment to examine one or two properties of this rotation matrix. The most important property of this matrix is that it is orthogonal, that is, the norm of its rows and columns is one. Since it is orthogonal, its transpose is equal to its inverse, that is:\r\n[latex]\r\nP^{-1}=P^T=\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\ncos \\alpha & sin \\alpha \\\\\r\n-sin \\alpha & cos \\alpha \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\n<h3>Where it all comes together</h3>\r\nHow do we exploit this identity in answering our original question? Well, the basic idea is that we want a rotation to be applied to the original matrix, such that a given element, say [latex]A_{mn}[/latex] gets zeroed.\r\nLet\'s return to our original recurrence relation:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nA_{j+1} = P_{j+1}^{-1}.A_j.P_{j+1}\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nWe want to substitute P for our rotation matrix, so that (because P is orthogonal) we can write:\r\n[latex]\r\nA_{j+1} = P_{j+1}^T.A_j.P_{j+1}\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nTo be able to substitute P for our rotation matrix, we need to generalise the matrix somewhat; it\'s still 2x2 from the previous section. For that, we need to decide which element we want to zero, in our case this is [latex]A_{mn}[/latex].\r\nThe generalised rotation matrix is then:\r\n\r\n<img alt="" src="http://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/JacobiRotationMatrix/NumberedEquation2.gif" title="JacobiRotation" class="alignnone" width="278" height="138" />\r\n\r\nAlright, so we know what P to apply...wait, not quite. There is still the question of what value of [latex]\\alpha[/latex] should be used for each transformation. Also, the effect of the rotation matrix on the matrix A<sub>j</sub> still needs calculation. This and more I shall cover in the next post.', 'Eigenvector algorithms for symmetric matrices: Jacobi rotations, Part 1', 0, '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '331-revision-90', '', '', '2011-07-23 04:51:50', '2011-07-23 12:51:50', '', 331, 'http://avishek.net/blog/?p=423', 0, 'revision', '', 0); 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (432, 1, '2011-07-24 12:37:55', '2011-07-24 20:37:55', '<h3>Symmetric Matrices / Diagonal Matrices</h3>\r\nA symmetric matrix looks like this:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nA=\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\na & d & n & w \\\\\r\nd & b & h & e \\\\\r\nn & h & c & i \\\\\r\nw & e & i & d \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nNotice how the values are reflected across the diagonal a-b-c-d; this holds true for any symmetric matrix. Now, here\'s an example of a diagonal matrix.\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nD=\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\na & 0 & 0 & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & b & 0 & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & 0 & c & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & 0 & 0 & d \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nNotice how all the off-diagonal elements (elements not part of the diagonal) are zero; this holds true for any diagonal matrix.\r\nLet\'s take a (short) digression and look at a widely-used way of viewing matrices - as linear transformations.\r\n\r\n<h3>Linear Transformations</h3>\r\n\r\n<img src="https://docs.google.com/drawings/pub?id=1UjD6Vj8mBPfUzNQ42og7Z8I_133IafcCblkmEKSyLLM&amp;w=510&amp;h=476"/>\r\nHere is a simple question: find me the matrix P which when multiplied with the vector [latex]\\overrightarrow{r, \\theta}[/latex] gives me the rotated vector [latex]\\overrightarrow{r,\\left(\\theta + \\alpha\\right)}[/latex].\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nP.\\left( \\begin{array}{c}\r\nr cos \\theta \\\\\r\nr sin \\theta \\end{array} \\right).P\r\n=\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{c}\r\nr cos \\left(\\theta+\\alpha\\right) \\\\\r\nr sin \\left(\\theta+\\alpha\\right) \\end{array} \\right)\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nThis is how I do it. Expand the trigonometric expressions for [latex]cos \\left(\\theta+\\alpha\\right)[/latex] and [latex]sin \\left(\\theta+\\alpha\\right)[/latex], so that you get:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nP.\\left( \\begin{array}{c}\r\nr cos \\theta \\\\\r\nr sin \\theta \\end{array} \\right)\r\n=\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{c}\r\nr cos \\theta.cos \\alpha - r sin \\theta.sin \\alpha \\\\\r\nr sin \\theta.cos \\alpha + r cos \\alpha.sin \\theta \\end{array} \\right)\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nA little inspection gives the answer:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nP =\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\ncos \\alpha & -sin \\alpha \\\\\r\nsin \\alpha & cos \\alpha \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nThe matrix P is a linear transformation; why it is linear and what its properties are I\'ll leave to the formal definitions in books. It suffices to say that you can look at a matrix as if it were a map or a function to which you could pass in a vector and get a new vector out of it.\r\nAs in the above example, all matrices have geometrical descriptions: the above one is a rotation vector, for instance. For the purposes of this series, I shall concentrate for the moment on the type of transformation given by a diagonal matrix.\r\n\r\nLet\'s take a moment to examine one or two properties of this rotation matrix. The most important property of this matrix is that it is orthogonal, that is, the norm of its rows and columns is one. Since it is orthogonal, its transpose is equal to its inverse, that is:\r\n[latex]\r\nP^{-1}=P^T=\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\ncos \\alpha & sin \\alpha \\\\\r\n-sin \\alpha & cos \\alpha \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n[/latex]\r\n', 'Matrix Theory', 0, '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '331-revision-97', '', '', '2011-07-24 12:37:55', '2011-07-24 20:37:55', '', 331, 'http://avishek.net/blog/?p=432', 0, 'revision', '', 0); 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (431, 1, '2011-07-24 11:10:48', '2011-07-24 19:10:48', '<h3>Symmetric Matrices / Diagonal Matrices</h3>\r\nA symmetric matrix looks like this:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nA=\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\na & d & n & w \\\\\r\nd & b & h & e \\\\\r\nn & h & c & i \\\\\r\nw & e & i & d \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nNotice how the values are reflected across the diagonal a-b-c-d; this holds true for any symmetric matrix. Now, here\'s an example of a diagonal matrix.\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nD=\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\na & 0 & 0 & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & b & 0 & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & 0 & c & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & 0 & 0 & d \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nNotice how all the off-diagonal elements (elements not part of the diagonal) are zero; this holds true for any diagonal matrix.\r\n\r\n', 'Matrix Theory', 0, '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '331-revision-96', '', '', '2011-07-24 11:10:48', '2011-07-24 19:10:48', '', 331, 'http://avishek.net/blog/?p=431', 0, 'revision', '', 0); 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (428, 1, '2011-07-24 10:19:40', '2011-07-24 18:19:40', '<h3>Symmetric Matrices / Diagonal Matrices</h3>\r\nA symmetric matrix looks like this:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nA=\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\na & d & n & w \\\\\r\nd & b & h & e \\\\\r\nn & h & c & i \\\\\r\nw & e & i & d \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nNotice how the values are reflected across the diagonal a-b-c-d; this holds true for any symmetric matrix. Now, here\'s an example of a diagonal matrix.\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nD=\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\na & 0 & 0 & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & b & 0 & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & 0 & c & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & 0 & 0 & d \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nNotice how all the off-diagonal elements (elements not part of the diagonal) are zero; this holds true for any diagonal matrix.\r\n\r\n<h3>Problem Statement, restated</h3>\r\nArmed with that information, we are now in a position to restate the first line: determine the set of matrix operations which will transform a symmetric matrix into a diagonal form. To follow through with the examples above, the question we are asking is, find me a <strong>P</strong> such that:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nP^{-1} .\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\na & d & n & w \\\\\r\nd & b & h & e \\\\\r\nn & h & c & i \\\\\r\nw & e & i & d \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n.P\r\n=\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\np & 0 & 0 & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & q & 0 & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & 0 & r & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & 0 & 0 & s \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nor, more concisely,\r\n[latex]\r\nP^{-1}.A.P = D\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nWhy such an unsightly transformation?\r\nI\'ll probably write about this in a future post, but for now, remember that the eigenvector matrix diagonalises its \'parent\' matrix. In the previous identity, [latex]P[/latex] is the eigenvector matrix.\r\nAnyway, we need to determine [latex]P[/latex]. There are several ways of doing this, and in this post we are describing one such, namely, Jacobi rotations.\r\n\r\n<h3>The shape of the solution</h3>\r\nHow about we assume that this eigenvector matrix [latex]P[/latex] can be expressed as a product of n matrices [latex]P_1, P_2, \\ldots P_n[/latex]? Then, we can write:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nP = P_1.P_2.P_3 \\ldots P_n\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nSubstituting the above into the diagonalisation identity:\r\n[latex]\r\n(P_1.P_2.P_3 \\ldots P_n)^{-1}.A.(P_1.P_2.P_3 \\ldots P_n) = D\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nThe inverse of a product of matrices is the reversed-order product of the inverse of those same matrices, which is to say:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\n(P_1.P_2.P_3 \\ldots P_n)^{-1} = P_n^{-1} \\ldots P_3^{-1}.P_2^{-1}.P_1^{-1}\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nSubstituting this result gives:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\n\\left( P_n^{-1} \\ldots P_3^{-1}.P_2^{-1}.P_1^{-1} \\right).A.\\left( P_1.P_2.P_3 \\ldots P_n \\right) = D\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nWell, let\'s use the associative property of matrix multiplication to shift around the brackets a bit.\r\n<em>The associative property of matrix multiplication, by the way, says that: [latex]\\left(AB\\right)C = A\\left(BC\\right)[/latex]</em>\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\n\\left(P_n^{-1} \\ldots \\left(P_3^{-1}.\\left(P_2^{-1}.\\left(P_1^{-1}.A.P_1\\right).P_2\\right).P_3\\right)\\ldots P_n\\right) = D\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nThe above grouping can be expressed more concisely as:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nA_{j+1} = P_{j+1}^{-1}.A_j.P_{j+1}\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nLet\'s take a minute to spell out what this means.\r\nIf we (somehow) know all the matrices [latex]P_1, P_2, \\ldots P_n[/latex], then we can get to D, by repeatedly carrying out the above matrix operation.\r\nAlright, now the question arises as to what these matrices should be. Well, one clear sign that we are moving in the right direction is, if during the course of these recurring operations, [latex]A_{j}[/latex] becomes increasingly diagonal. In other words, more off-diagonal elements get zeroed while we are doing these multiplications.\r\nBut exactly what sort of matrix does this?\r\n\r\nLet\'s take a (short) digression and look at a fundamental operation in computer graphics/vector algebra.\r\n\r\n<h3>Vector Rotations</h3>\r\n\r\n<img src="https://docs.google.com/drawings/pub?id=1UjD6Vj8mBPfUzNQ42og7Z8I_133IafcCblkmEKSyLLM&amp;w=510&amp;h=476"/>\r\nHere is a simple question: find me the matrix P which when multiplied with the vector [latex]\\overrightarrow{r, \\theta}[/latex] gives me the rotated vector [latex]\\overrightarrow{r,\\left(\\theta + \\alpha\\right)}[/latex].\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nP.\\left( \\begin{array}{c}\r\nr cos \\theta \\\\\r\nr sin \\theta \\end{array} \\right).P\r\n=\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{c}\r\nr cos \\left(\\theta+\\alpha\\right) \\\\\r\nr sin \\left(\\theta+\\alpha\\right) \\end{array} \\right)\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nThis is how I do it. Expand the trigonometric expressions for [latex]cos \\left(\\theta+\\alpha\\right)[/latex] and [latex]sin \\left(\\theta+\\alpha\\right)[/latex], so that you get:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nP.\\left( \\begin{array}{c}\r\nr cos \\theta \\\\\r\nr sin \\theta \\end{array} \\right)\r\n=\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{c}\r\nr cos \\theta.cos \\alpha - r sin \\theta.sin \\alpha \\\\\r\nr sin \\theta.cos \\alpha + r cos \\alpha.sin \\theta \\end{array} \\right)\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nA little inspection gives the answer:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nP =\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\ncos \\alpha & -sin \\alpha \\\\\r\nsin \\alpha & cos \\alpha \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nLet\'s take a moment to examine one or two properties of this rotation matrix. The most important property of this matrix is that it is orthogonal, that is, the norm of its rows and columns is one. Since it is orthogonal, its transpose is equal to its inverse, that is:\r\n[latex]\r\nP^{-1}=P^T=\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\ncos \\alpha & sin \\alpha \\\\\r\n-sin \\alpha & cos \\alpha \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\n<h3>Rotation and its inverse/transpose as a similarity transformation</h3>\r\nHow do we exploit this identity in answering our original question? Well, the basic idea is that we want a rotation to be applied to the original matrix, such that a given element, say [latex]A_{mn}[/latex] gets zeroed. However, you can\'t just rotate a matrix arbitrarily, just for the sake of setting some element in it to zero; the resulting matrix would not be anything like the original matrix! Yes, we do need to set an element to zero, but under the constraint that the entire operation results in the same matrix.\r\nMore concretely, let\'s assume that A is the original matrix, and that it is transformed by P into a new matrix A\'. Ignore the nature of P for a minute. Then A\' and A are <em>similar matrices</em> if:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nA\' = P^{-1}.A.P\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nI\'ll write more about similar matrices soon. Let\'s return to our original recurrence relation:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nA_{j+1} = P_{j+1}^{-1}.A_j.P_{j+1}\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nWe want to substitute P for our rotation matrix, so that (because P is orthogonal) we can write:\r\n[latex]\r\nA_{j+1} = P_{j+1}^T.A_j.P_{j+1}\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nTo be able to substitute P for our rotation matrix, we need to generalise the matrix somewhat; it\'s still 2x2 from the previous section. For that, we need to decide which element we want to zero, in our case this is [latex]A_{mn}[/latex].\r\nThe generalised rotation matrix is then:\r\n\r\n<img alt="" src="http://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/JacobiRotationMatrix/NumberedEquation2.gif" title="JacobiRotation" class="alignnone" width="278" height="138" />\r\n\r\nAlright, so we know what P to apply...wait, not quite. There is still the question of what value of [latex]\\alpha[/latex] should be used for each transformation. Also, the effect of the rotation matrix on the matrix A<sub>j</sub> still needs calculation. This and more I shall cover in the next post.\r\n', 'Matrix Theory', 0, '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '331-revision-95', '', '', '2011-07-24 10:19:40', '2011-07-24 18:19:40', '', 331, 'http://avishek.net/blog/?p=428', 0, 'revision', '', 0); 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (424, 1, '2011-07-23 13:56:25', '2011-07-23 21:56:25', 'Let\'s start off by stating what the objective is. We are attempting to diagonalise a symmetric matrix.\r\n\r\n<h3>Symmetric Matrices / Diagonal Matrices</h3>\r\nA symmetric matrix looks like this:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nA=\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\na & d & n & w \\\\\r\nd & b & h & e \\\\\r\nn & h & c & i \\\\\r\nw & e & i & d \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nNotice how the values are reflected across the diagonal a-b-c-d; this holds true for any symmetric matrix. Now, here\'s an example of a diagonal matrix.\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nD=\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\na & 0 & 0 & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & b & 0 & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & 0 & c & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & 0 & 0 & d \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nNotice how all the off-diagonal elements (elements not part of the diagonal) are zero; this holds true for any diagonal matrix.\r\n\r\n<h3>Problem Statement, restated</h3>\r\nArmed with that information, we are now in a position to restate the first line: determine the set of matrix operations which will transform a symmetric matrix into a diagonal form. To follow through with the examples above, the question we are asking is, find me a <strong>P</strong> such that:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nP^{-1} .\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\na & d & n & w \\\\\r\nd & b & h & e \\\\\r\nn & h & c & i \\\\\r\nw & e & i & d \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n.P\r\n=\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\np & 0 & 0 & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & q & 0 & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & 0 & r & 0 \\\\\r\n0 & 0 & 0 & s \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nor, more concisely,\r\n[latex]\r\nP^{-1}.A.P = D\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nWhy such an unsightly transformation?\r\nI\'ll probably write about this in a future post, but for now, remember that the eigenvector matrix diagonalises its \'parent\' matrix. In the previous identity, [latex]P[/latex] is the eigenvector matrix.\r\nAnyway, we need to determine [latex]P[/latex]. There are several ways of doing this, and in this post we are describing one such, namely, Jacobi rotations.\r\n\r\n<h3>The shape of the solution</h3>\r\nHow about we assume that this eigenvector matrix [latex]P[/latex] can be expressed as a product of n matrices [latex]P_1, P_2, \\ldots P_n[/latex]? Then, we can write:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nP = P_1.P_2.P_3 \\ldots P_n\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nSubstituting the above into the diagonalisation identity:\r\n[latex]\r\n(P_1.P_2.P_3 \\ldots P_n)^{-1}.A.(P_1.P_2.P_3 \\ldots P_n) = D\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nThe inverse of a product of matrices is the reversed-order product of the inverse of those same matrices, which is to say:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\n(P_1.P_2.P_3 \\ldots P_n)^{-1} = P_n^{-1} \\ldots P_3^{-1}.P_2^{-1}.P_1^{-1}\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nSubstituting this result gives:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\n\\left( P_n^{-1} \\ldots P_3^{-1}.P_2^{-1}.P_1^{-1} \\right).A.\\left( P_1.P_2.P_3 \\ldots P_n \\right) = D\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nWell, let\'s use the associative property of matrix multiplication to shift around the brackets a bit.\r\n<em>The associative property of matrix multiplication, by the way, says that: [latex]\\left(AB\\right)C = A\\left(BC\\right)[/latex]</em>\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\n\\left(P_n^{-1} \\ldots \\left(P_3^{-1}.\\left(P_2^{-1}.\\left(P_1^{-1}.A.P_1\\right).P_2\\right).P_3\\right)\\ldots P_n\\right) = D\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nThe above grouping can be expressed more concisely as:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nA_{j+1} = P_{j+1}^{-1}.A_j.P_{j+1}\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nLet\'s take a minute to spell out what this means.\r\nIf we (somehow) know all the matrices [latex]P_1, P_2, \\ldots P_n[/latex], then we can get to D, by repeatedly carrying out the above matrix operation.\r\nAlright, now the question arises as to what these matrices should be. Well, one clear sign that we are moving in the right direction is, if during the course of these recurring operations, [latex]A_{j}[/latex] becomes increasingly diagonal. In other words, more off-diagonal elements get zeroed while we are doing these multiplications.\r\nBut exactly what sort of matrix does this?\r\n\r\nLet\'s take a (short) digression and look at a fundamental operation in computer graphics/vector algebra.\r\n\r\n<h3>Vector Rotations</h3>\r\n\r\n<img src="https://docs.google.com/drawings/pub?id=1UjD6Vj8mBPfUzNQ42og7Z8I_133IafcCblkmEKSyLLM&amp;w=510&amp;h=476"/>\r\nHere is a simple question: find me the matrix P which when multiplied with the vector [latex]\\overrightarrow{r, \\theta}[/latex] gives me the rotated vector [latex]\\overrightarrow{r,\\left(\\theta + \\alpha\\right)}[/latex].\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nP.\\left( \\begin{array}{c}\r\nr cos \\theta \\\\\r\nr sin \\theta \\end{array} \\right).P\r\n=\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{c}\r\nr cos \\left(\\theta+\\alpha\\right) \\\\\r\nr sin \\left(\\theta+\\alpha\\right) \\end{array} \\right)\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nThis is how I do it. Expand the trigonometric expressions for [latex]cos \\left(\\theta+\\alpha\\right)[/latex] and [latex]sin \\left(\\theta+\\alpha\\right)[/latex], so that you get:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nP.\\left( \\begin{array}{c}\r\nr cos \\theta \\\\\r\nr sin \\theta \\end{array} \\right)\r\n=\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{c}\r\nr cos \\theta.cos \\alpha - r sin \\theta.sin \\alpha \\\\\r\nr sin \\theta.cos \\alpha + r cos \\alpha.sin \\theta \\end{array} \\right)\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nA little inspection gives the answer:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nP =\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\ncos \\alpha & -sin \\alpha \\\\\r\nsin \\alpha & cos \\alpha \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nLet\'s take a moment to examine one or two properties of this rotation matrix. The most important property of this matrix is that it is orthogonal, that is, the norm of its rows and columns is one. Since it is orthogonal, its transpose is equal to its inverse, that is:\r\n[latex]\r\nP^{-1}=P^T=\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\ncos \\alpha & sin \\alpha \\\\\r\n-sin \\alpha & cos \\alpha \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\n<h3>Where it all comes together</h3>\r\nHow do we exploit this identity in answering our original question? Well, the basic idea is that we want a rotation to be applied to the original matrix, such that a given element, say [latex]A_{mn}[/latex] gets zeroed.\r\nLet\'s return to our original recurrence relation:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nA_{j+1} = P_{j+1}^{-1}.A_j.P_{j+1}\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nWe want to substitute P for our rotation matrix, so that (because P is orthogonal) we can write:\r\n[latex]\r\nA_{j+1} = P_{j+1}^T.A_j.P_{j+1}\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nTo be able to substitute P for our rotation matrix, we need to generalise the matrix somewhat; it\'s still 2x2 from the previous section. For that, we need to decide which element we want to zero, in our case this is [latex]A_{mn}[/latex].\r\nThe generalised rotation matrix is then:\r\n\r\n<img alt="" src="http://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/JacobiRotationMatrix/NumberedEquation2.gif" title="JacobiRotation" class="alignnone" width="278" height="138" />\r\n\r\nAlright, so we know what P to apply...wait, not quite. There is still the question of what value of [latex]\\alpha[/latex] should be used for each transformation. Also, the effect of the rotation matrix on the matrix A<sub>j</sub> still needs calculation. This and more I shall cover in the next post.', 'Eigenvector algorithms for symmetric matrices: Jacobi rotations, Part 1', 0, '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '331-revision-91', '', '', '2011-07-23 13:56:25', '2011-07-23 21:56:25', '', 331, 'http://avishek.net/blog/?p=424', 0, 'revision', '', 0); 
