INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (469, 1, '2011-07-25 04:55:04', '2011-07-25 12:55:04', '<h3>Basis Change</h3>\r\nUnderstand that there is nothing extremely special about the standard basis vectors [1,0] and [0,1]. All 2D vectors may be represented as linear combinations of these vectors. Thus, the vector [7,24] may be written as:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\n7 \\\\\r\n24 \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n=\r\n7.\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\n1 \\\\\r\n0 \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n+\r\n24.\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\n0 \\\\\r\n1 \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nYou may take linear combinations of any other reasonable (linearly independent) set of vectors, and still be able to express the same [7,24] as linear combinations of those. The diagram below shows an example. The vector [1,1] in standard basis can also be represented by an alternate basis [1,1], [-1,1]. Since, in the new basis, the vector lies along the B1 basis vector [1,1] itself, it can simply be expressed as:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\n1 \\\\\r\n1 \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n=\r\n1.\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\n1 \\\\\r\n1 \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n+\r\n0.\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\n-1 \\\\\r\n1 \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\n<img src="https://docs.google.com/drawings/pub?id=1YdBGg2uk1cJYdSnv6O-RITjaJdDOWFQ28WiMQCIaPlE&amp;w=670&amp;h=407"/>\r\n\r\nIn the above example, the new basis vectors are orthogonal; they need not be. Let\'s deduce the relation between the point as expressed between two bases. This leads us to the basis matrix, which is simply the matrix composed of the basis vectors of basis B. If a vector expressed in basis B is multiplied with the basis matrix of B, the result is the vector in the standard basis.\r\nWe can use the previous example to illustrate this point. In the basis B = {[1,1], [-1,1]}, the vector V<sub>B</sub> is [1,0]. If we multiply the two, we get:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nB.V_B =\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\n1 & -1\\\\\r\n1 & 1\\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n.\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\n1 \\\\\r\n0 \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n=\r\n\\left( \\begin{array}{cccc}\r\n1 \\\\\r\n1 \\end{array} \\right)\\\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nThen, for a basis matrix B, a vector V<sub>B</sub> is related to that same vector V<sub>S</sub> in standard basis as:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nB.V_B = V_S \\\\\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nSimply multiplying the basis matrix of B with a vector expressed in basis B gives us the vector in standard basis.\r\n\r\n<h3>Similarity transformations</h3>\r\nLet\'s explore basis changes further. We already know how to relate vectors expressed in two different bases. Now we\'ll explore how linear transformations can be expressed in different bases.\r\nRoughly, linear transformations map vectors in n-space to other vectors in n-space; I wrote about this <a href="http://avishek.net/blog/?p=331">here</a>.\r\nLet a transformation T<sub>S</sub>, applied to a vector x<sub>S</sub>, produce a vector y<sub>S</sub> in standard basis S. That is:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nT_S.x_S = y_S\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nFurthermore, let x<sub>S</sub> be represented in some other basis B by x<sub>B</sub>, and let them be related by the basis matrix C<sub>B</sub>(basis matrix of B) as:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nC_B.x_B = x_S\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nSimilarly, let y<sub>S</sub> be represented in some other basis B by y<sub>B</sub>, and let them be related by the same basis matrix C<sub>B</sub> as:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nC_B.y_B = y_S\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nThe question we ask is a simple one: what is the transformation T<sub>B</sub> that maps x<sub>B</sub> to y<sub>B</sub>? Essentially, if we know a transformation matrix in one basis, what would that same transformation look like in a different basis?\r\nThe algebra is pretty simple. We have:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nC_B.x_B = x_S \\\\\r\nC_B.y_B = y_S \\\\\r\n\r\nT_S.x_S = y_S\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nSubstituting the expressions for x<sub>S</sub> and y<sub>S</sub> in the above, we get:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nT_S.C_B.x_B = C_B.y_B \\\\\r\n{C_B}^{-1}.T_S.C_B.x_B = y_B \\\\\r\n\\left({C_B}^{-1}.T_S.C_B\\right).x_B = y_B \\\\\r\n\\\\\r\nT_B = {C_B}^{-1}.T_S.C_B\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\nNow, notice that we have not constrained T<sub>S</sub> to be anything special, apart from the dimensionality requirements for matrix multiplication. This implies that this identity may be applied to any matrix. T<sub>B</sub> and T<sub>S</sub> are said to be similar to each other, because they are essentially the same matrix, only expressed in terms of different bases.\r\n\r\nWhy did I go to the trouble of introducing these concepts? In the next post, I shall talk about how we tie all these up together to make the calculation of eigenvectors/eigenvalues easier. Hopefully, that will also shed some light on the nature of these beasts.', 'Matrix Theory: Basis change and Similarity transformations', 0, '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '448-revision-20', '', '', '2011-07-25 04:55:04', '2011-07-25 12:55:04', '', 448, 'http://avishek.net/blog/?p=469', 0, 'revision', '', 0); 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (470, 1, '2011-07-13 06:07:51', '2011-07-13 14:07:51', '<strong>This was an old proof that was up on my old blog, but since I\'m no longer posting to that, I\'m reposting it here for posterity.</strong>\r\n\r\nI present a simple mathematical device to prove that tests improve our understanding of code. It does not really matter if this is code written by the test author himself or is legacy. To do this, some simplification of the situation is necessary.\r\n\r\nWe assume X is the unit of code under consideration. X may be a function, a class or a compiled binary. The only restriction on X is that it can accept inputs and produce measurable outputs.\r\n\r\nWithout loss of generality, we may assume that the X\'s output consists of n bits. If complicated structures like objects are present in the result, they may simply be decomposed into bits and laid out in a convenient order to fit this model. This assumption exists to simplify quantizing the output space only.\r\n\r\nWe also assume that unique inputs yield unique outputs, but this assumption does not affect the fundamental conclusion.\r\n\r\nLet us define the probabilities:\r\n\r\n<strong>P(A) = Probability that X uses the correct algorithm = p\r\nP(B) = Probability of test T1 passing (getting the correct output) for a given input I1 = 1/(2^n)\r\nP(B|A) = Probability of test T1 passing (getting the correct output) for a given input I1, given X uses the correct algorithm = 1\r\n</strong>\r\n\r\nTherefore, using Bayes\' Theorem:\r\n\r\n*P(A|B)* = Probability that X uses the correct algorithm given test passes for a given input I1\r\n            = P(B|A).P(A)/P(B)\r\n            = *p.(2^n)*\r\n\r\nP(1)=p*(2^n)\r\n\r\n*Note that after writing one test, the probability of X using the correct algorithm has increased (n>=1) by a factor of 2^n.*\r\n\r\nLet us now write another test with input I2. Note that I assume that T1 passing does not affect any probabilities other than the updated probability of X using the correct algorithm, i.e., the tests are statistically independent (I believe that\'s the term used :-).\r\n\r\nP(A) = Probability that X uses the correct algorithm = p*(2^n)\r\nP(B) = Probability of test T2 passing (getting the correct output) for a given input I2 = 1/(2^n)\r\nP(B|A) = Probability of test T2 passing (getting the correct output) for a given input I2, given X uses the correct algorithm = 1\r\n\r\nTherefore, using Bayes\' Theorem:\r\n\r\nP(A|B) = Probability that X uses the correct algorithm given test passes for a given input I2\r\n            = P(B|A).P(A)/P(B)\r\n            = p.(2^n).(2^n)\r\n\r\nP(2)=p.(2^n).(2^n)\r\nAfter having written t tests, we may write:\r\n\r\n<div class="result">P(t)=p.[2^(n.t)]</div><div class="newline">&nbsp;</div>\r\n\r\n*<i>t</i> tests, therefore, increase the probability (or our knowledge, in very rough terms) of X being implemented correctly, by a factor of 2^nt.*\r\nProbability is inversely correlated with entropy; thus, we have also reduced the entropy of the system.\r\nIt might be useful to state that I use the term \'test\' in a broad sense. The test may range from an automated unit test to human verification.\r\n\r\nIt turns out that it should be possible to determine p. Note that t is the number of *statistically independent tests* that we can write. This implies that t has a fixed upper bound. Thus:\r\n\r\nT = total number of statistically independent tests for X\r\np.[2^(n.T)] <= 1, or,\r\n<div class="result"><strong>p <= 1/[2^(n.T)]</strong></div><div class="newline">&nbsp;</div>\r\n', 'Tests increase our Knowledge of a System: A Probabilistic Proof', 0, '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '181-revision-7', '', '', '2011-07-13 06:07:51', '2011-07-13 14:07:51', '', 181, 'http://avishek.net/blog/?p=470', 0, 'revision', '', 0); 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (471, 1, '2011-07-25 08:01:43', '2011-07-25 16:01:43', '<strong>This was an old proof that was up on my old blog, but since I\'m no longer posting to that, I\'m reposting it here for posterity. Also, rewriting the equations in LaTeX, now that I have installed a plugin for that.</strong>\r\n\r\nI present a simple mathematical device to prove that tests improve our understanding of code. It does not really matter if this is code written by the test author himself or is legacy. To do this, some simplification of the situation is necessary.\r\n\r\nWe assume X is the unit of code under consideration. X may be a function, a class or a compiled binary. The only restriction on X is that it can accept inputs and produce measurable outputs.\r\n\r\nWithout loss of generality, we may assume that the X\'s output consists of n bits. If complicated structures like objects are present in the result, they may simply be decomposed into bits and laid out in a convenient order to fit this model. This assumption exists to simplify quantizing the output space only.\r\n\r\nWe also assume that unique inputs yield unique outputs, but this assumption does not affect the fundamental conclusion.\r\n\r\nLet us define the probabilities:\r\n\r\n<strong>P(A) = Probability that X uses the correct algorithm = p\r\nP(B) = Probability of test T1 passing (getting the correct output) for a given input I1 = [latex]1/(2^n)[/latex]\r\nP(B|A) = Probability of test T1 passing (getting the correct output) for a given input I1, given X uses the correct algorithm = 1\r\n</strong>\r\n\r\nTherefore, using Bayes\' Theorem:\r\n\r\n*P(A|B)* = Probability that X uses the correct algorithm given test passes for a given input I1\r\n            = P(B|A).P(A)/P(B)\r\n            = *[latex]p.(2^n)[/latex]*\r\n\r\n[latex]P(1)=p*(2^n)[/latex]\r\n\r\n*Note that after writing one test, the probability of X using the correct algorithm has increased (n>=1) by a factor of 2^n.*\r\n\r\nLet us now write another test with input I2. Note that I assume that T1 passing does not affect any probabilities other than the updated probability of X using the correct algorithm, i.e., the tests are statistically independent (I believe that\'s the term used :-).\r\n\r\nP(A) = Probability that X uses the correct algorithm = [latex]p*(2^n)[/latex]\r\nP(B) = Probability of test T2 passing (getting the correct output) for a given input I2 = [latex]1/(2^n)[/latex]\r\nP(B|A) = Probability of test T2 passing (getting the correct output) for a given input I2, given X uses the correct algorithm = 1\r\n\r\nTherefore, using Bayes\' Theorem:\r\n\r\nP(A|B) = Probability that X uses the correct algorithm given test passes for a given input I2\r\n            = P(B|A).P(A)/P(B)\r\n            = [latex]p.(2^n).(2^n)[/latex]\r\n\r\n[latex]P(2)=p.(2^n).(2^n)[/latex]\r\nAfter having written t tests, we may write:\r\n\r\n[latex]P(t)=p.[2^{nt}][/latex]\r\n\r\n*<i>t</i> tests, therefore, increase the probability (or our knowledge, in very rough terms) of X being implemented correctly, by a factor of 2^nt.*\r\nProbability is inversely correlated with entropy; thus, we have also reduced the entropy of the system.\r\nIt might be useful to state that I use the term \'test\' in a broad sense. The test may range from an automated unit test to human verification.\r\n\r\nIt turns out that it should be possible to determine p. Note that t is the number of *statistically independent tests* that we can write. This implies that t has a fixed upper bound. Thus:\r\n\r\nT = total number of statistically independent tests for X\r\np.[2^(n.T)] <= 1, or,\r\n<div class="result"><strong>p <= 1/[2^(n.T)]</strong></div><div class="newline">&nbsp;</div>\r\n', 'Tests increase our Knowledge of a System: A Probabilistic Proof', 0, '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '181-revision-8', '', '', '2011-07-25 08:01:43', '2011-07-25 16:01:43', '', 181, 'http://avishek.net/blog/?p=471', 0, 'revision', '', 0); 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (472, 1, '2011-07-25 08:02:28', '2011-07-25 16:02:28', '<strong>This was an old proof that was up on my old blog, but since I\'m no longer posting to that, I\'m reposting it here for posterity. Also, rewriting the equations in LaTeX, now that I have installed a plugin for that.</strong>\r\n\r\nI present a simple mathematical device to prove that tests improve our understanding of code. It does not really matter if this is code written by the test author himself or is legacy. To do this, some simplification of the situation is necessary.\r\n\r\nWe assume X is the unit of code under consideration. X may be a function, a class or a compiled binary. The only restriction on X is that it can accept inputs and produce measurable outputs.\r\n\r\nWithout loss of generality, we may assume that the X\'s output consists of n bits. If complicated structures like objects are present in the result, they may simply be decomposed into bits and laid out in a convenient order to fit this model. This assumption exists to simplify quantizing the output space only.\r\n\r\nWe also assume that unique inputs yield unique outputs, but this assumption does not affect the fundamental conclusion.\r\n\r\nLet us define the probabilities:\r\n\r\n<strong>P(A) = Probability that X uses the correct algorithm = p\r\nP(B) = Probability of test T1 passing (getting the correct output) for a given input I1 = [latex]1/(2^n)[/latex]\r\nP(B|A) = Probability of test T1 passing (getting the correct output) for a given input I1, given X uses the correct algorithm = 1\r\n</strong>\r\n\r\nTherefore, using Bayes\' Theorem:\r\n\r\n[latex]\r\nP(A|B) = Probability that X uses the correct algorithm given test passes for a given input I1\r\n            = P(B|A).P(A)/P(B)\r\n            = p.(2^n)\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\n[latex]P(1)=p*(2^n)[/latex]\r\n\r\n*Note that after writing one test, the probability of X using the correct algorithm has increased (n>=1) by a factor of 2^n.*\r\n\r\nLet us now write another test with input I2. Note that I assume that T1 passing does not affect any probabilities other than the updated probability of X using the correct algorithm, i.e., the tests are statistically independent (I believe that\'s the term used :-).\r\n\r\nP(A) = Probability that X uses the correct algorithm = [latex]p*(2^n)[/latex]\r\nP(B) = Probability of test T2 passing (getting the correct output) for a given input I2 = [latex]1/(2^n)[/latex]\r\nP(B|A) = Probability of test T2 passing (getting the correct output) for a given input I2, given X uses the correct algorithm = 1\r\n\r\nTherefore, using Bayes\' Theorem:\r\n\r\nP(A|B) = Probability that X uses the correct algorithm given test passes for a given input I2\r\n            = P(B|A).P(A)/P(B)\r\n            = [latex]p.(2^n).(2^n)[/latex]\r\n\r\n[latex]P(2)=p.(2^n).(2^n)[/latex]\r\nAfter having written t tests, we may write:\r\n\r\n[latex]P(t)=p.[2^{nt}][/latex]\r\n\r\n*<i>t</i> tests, therefore, increase the probability (or our knowledge, in very rough terms) of X being implemented correctly, by a factor of 2^nt.*\r\nProbability is inversely correlated with entropy; thus, we have also reduced the entropy of the system.\r\nIt might be useful to state that I use the term \'test\' in a broad sense. The test may range from an automated unit test to human verification.\r\n\r\nIt turns out that it should be possible to determine p. Note that t is the number of *statistically independent tests* that we can write. This implies that t has a fixed upper bound. Thus:\r\n\r\nT = total number of statistically independent tests for X\r\np.[2^(n.T)] <= 1, or,\r\n<div class="result"><strong>p <= 1/[2^(n.T)]</strong></div><div class="newline">&nbsp;</div>\r\n', 'Tests increase our Knowledge of a System: A Probabilistic Proof', 0, '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '181-revision-9', '', '', '2011-07-25 08:02:28', '2011-07-25 16:02:28', '', 181, 'http://avishek.net/blog/?p=472', 0, 'revision', '', 0); 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (473, 1, '2011-07-25 08:05:48', '2011-07-25 16:05:48', '<strong>This was an old proof that was up on my old blog, but since I\'m no longer posting to that, I\'m reposting it here for posterity. Also, rewriting the equations in LaTeX, now that I have installed a plugin for that.</strong>\r\n\r\nI present a simple mathematical device to prove that tests improve our understanding of code. It does not really matter if this is code written by the test author himself or is legacy. To do this, some simplification of the situation is necessary.\r\n\r\nWe assume X is the unit of code under consideration. X may be a function, a class or a compiled binary. The only restriction on X is that it can accept inputs and produce measurable outputs.\r\n\r\nWithout loss of generality, we may assume that the X\'s output consists of n bits. If complicated structures like objects are present in the result, they may simply be decomposed into bits and laid out in a convenient order to fit this model. This assumption exists to simplify quantizing the output space only.\r\n\r\nWe also assume that unique inputs yield unique outputs, but this assumption does not affect the fundamental conclusion.\r\n\r\nLet us define the probabilities:\r\n\r\n<strong>P(A) = Probability that X uses the correct algorithm = p\r\n[latex]P(B)[/latex] = Probability of test T1 passing (getting the correct output) for a given input I1 = [latex]1/(2^n)[/latex]\r\n[latex]P(B|A)[/latex] = Probability of test T1 passing (getting the correct output) for a given input I1, given X uses the correct algorithm = 1\r\n</strong>\r\n\r\nTherefore, using Bayes\' Theorem:\r\n\r\n[latex]P(A|B)[/latex] = Probability that X uses the correct algorithm given test passes for a given input I1\r\n[latex]\r\n            = P(B|A).P(A)/P(B)\r\n            = p.(2^n)\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\n[latex]P(1)=p*(2^n)[/latex]\r\n\r\n*Note that after writing one test, the probability of X using the correct algorithm has increased (n>=1) by a factor of 2^n.*\r\n\r\nLet us now write another test with input I2. Note that I assume that T1 passing does not affect any probabilities other than the updated probability of X using the correct algorithm, i.e., the tests are statistically independent (I believe that\'s the term used :-).\r\n\r\n[latex]P(A)[/latex] = Probability that X uses the correct algorithm = [latex]p*(2^n)[/latex]\r\n[latex]P(B)[/latex] = Probability of test T2 passing (getting the correct output) for a given input I2 = [latex]1/(2^n)[/latex]\r\n[latex]P(B|A)[/latex] = Probability of test T2 passing (getting the correct output) for a given input I2, given X uses the correct algorithm = 1\r\n\r\nTherefore, using Bayes\' Theorem:\r\n\r\n[latex]P(A|B)[/latex] = Probability that X uses the correct algorithm given test passes for a given input I2\r\n[latex]\r\n            = P(B|A).P(A)/P(B) \\\\\r\n            = p.(2^n).(2^n)[/latex] \\\\\r\n\\\\\r\nP(2)=p.(2^n).(2^n)[/latex]\r\nAfter having written t tests, we may write:\r\n\r\n[latex]P(t)=p.[2^{nt}][/latex]\r\n\r\n*<i>t</i> tests, therefore, increase the probability (or our knowledge, in very rough terms) of X being implemented correctly, by a factor of [latex]2^nt[/latex].*\r\nProbability is inversely correlated with entropy; thus, we have also reduced the entropy of the system.\r\nIt might be useful to state that I use the term \'test\' in a broad sense. The test may range from an automated unit test to human verification.\r\n\r\nIt turns out that it should be possible to determine p. Note that t is the number of *statistically independent tests* that we can write. This implies that t has a fixed upper bound. Thus:\r\n\r\nT = total number of statistically independent tests for X\r\n[latex]\r\np.[2^(n.T)] <= 1, or,\r\np <= 1/[2^(n.T)]\r\n[/latex]', 'Tests increase our Knowledge of a System: A Probabilistic Proof', 0, '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '181-revision-10', '', '', '2011-07-25 08:05:48', '2011-07-25 16:05:48', '', 181, 'http://avishek.net/blog/?p=473', 0, 'revision', '', 0); 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (474, 1, '2011-07-25 08:09:40', '2011-07-25 16:09:40', '<strong>This was an old proof that was up on my old blog, but since I\'m no longer posting to that, I\'m reposting it here for posterity. Also, rewriting the equations in LaTeX, now that I have installed a plugin for that.</strong>\r\n\r\nI present a simple mathematical device to prove that tests improve our understanding of code. It does not really matter if this is code written by the test author himself or is legacy. To do this, some simplification of the situation is necessary.\r\n\r\nWe assume X is the unit of code under consideration. X may be a function, a class or a compiled binary. The only restriction on X is that it can accept inputs and produce measurable outputs.\r\n\r\nWithout loss of generality, we may assume that the X\'s output consists of n bits. If complicated structures like objects are present in the result, they may simply be decomposed into bits and laid out in a convenient order to fit this model. This assumption exists to simplify quantizing the output space only.\r\n\r\nWe also assume that unique inputs yield unique outputs, but this assumption does not affect the fundamental conclusion.\r\n\r\nLet us define the probabilities:\r\n\r\n<strong>P(A) = Probability that X uses the correct algorithm = p\r\n[latex]P(B)[/latex] = Probability of test T1 passing (getting the correct output) for a given input I1 = [latex]1/(2^n)[/latex]\r\n[latex]P(B|A)[/latex] = Probability of test T1 passing (getting the correct output) for a given input I1, given X uses the correct algorithm = 1\r\n</strong>\r\n\r\nTherefore, using Bayes\' Theorem:\r\n\r\n[latex]P\\left(A|B\\right)[/latex] = Probability that X uses the correct algorithm given test passes for a given input I1\r\n[latex]\r\n            = P\\left(B|A\\right).P\\left(A\\right)/P\\left(B\\right)\r\n            = p.2^n\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\n[latex]P\\left(1\\right)=p.2^n[/latex]\r\n\r\n*Note that after writing one test, the probability of X using the correct algorithm has increased (n>=1) by a factor of 2^n.*\r\n\r\nLet us now write another test with input I2. Note that I assume that T1 passing does not affect any probabilities other than the updated probability of X using the correct algorithm, i.e., the tests are statistically independent (I believe that\'s the term used :-).\r\n\r\n[latex]P\\left(A\\right)[/latex] = Probability that X uses the correct algorithm = [latex]p*\\left(2^n\\right)[/latex]\r\n[latex]P\\left(B\\right)[/latex] = Probability of test T2 passing (getting the correct output) for a given input I2 = [latex]1/\\left(2^n\\right)[/latex]\r\n[latex]P\\left(B|A\\right)[/latex] = Probability of test T2 passing (getting the correct output) for a given input I2, given X uses the correct algorithm = 1\r\n\r\nTherefore, using Bayes\' Theorem:\r\n\r\n[latex]P\\left(A|B\\right)[/latex] = Probability that X uses the correct algorithm given test passes for a given input I2\r\n[latex]\r\n            = P\\left(B|A\\right).P\\left(A\\right)/P\\left(B\\right) \\\\\r\n            = p.2^n.2^n[/latex] \\\\\r\n\\\\\r\nP\\left(2\\right)=p.2^n.2^n[/latex]\r\nAfter having written t tests, we may write:\r\n\r\n[latex]P\\left(t\\right)=p.[2^{nt}][/latex]\r\n\r\n*<i>t</i> tests, therefore, increase the probability (or our knowledge, in very rough terms) of X being implemented correctly, by a factor of [latex]2^nt[/latex].*\r\nProbability is inversely correlated with entropy; thus, we have also reduced the entropy of the system.\r\nIt might be useful to state that I use the term \'test\' in a broad sense. The test may range from an automated unit test to human verification.\r\n\r\nIt turns out that it should be possible to determine p. Note that t is the number of *statistically independent tests* that we can write. This implies that t has a fixed upper bound. Thus:\r\n\r\nT = total number of statistically independent tests for X\r\n[latex]\r\np.[2^{nT}] <= 1, or,\r\np <= 1/[2^{nT}]\r\n[/latex]\r\n', 'Tests increase our Knowledge of a System: A Probabilistic Proof', 0, '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '181-revision-11', '', '', '2011-07-25 08:09:40', '2011-07-25 16:09:40', '', 181, 'http://avishek.net/blog/?p=474', 0, 'revision', '', 0); 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (475, 1, '2011-07-25 08:11:03', '2011-07-25 16:11:03', '<strong>This was an old proof that was up on my old blog, but since I\'m no longer posting to that, I\'m reposting it here for posterity. Also, rewriting the equations in LaTeX, now that I have installed a plugin for that.</strong>\r\n\r\nI present a simple mathematical device to prove that tests improve our understanding of code. It does not really matter if this is code written by the test author himself or is legacy. To do this, some simplification of the situation is necessary.\r\n\r\nWe assume X is the unit of code under consideration. X may be a function, a class or a compiled binary. The only restriction on X is that it can accept inputs and produce measurable outputs.\r\n\r\nWithout loss of generality, we may assume that the X\'s output consists of n bits. If complicated structures like objects are present in the result, they may simply be decomposed into bits and laid out in a convenient order to fit this model. This assumption exists to simplify quantizing the output space only.\r\n\r\nWe also assume that unique inputs yield unique outputs, but this assumption does not affect the fundamental conclusion.\r\n\r\nLet us define the probabilities:\r\n\r\n<strong>P(A) = Probability that X uses the correct algorithm = p\r\n[latex]P(B)[/latex] = Probability of test T1 passing (getting the correct output) for a given input I1 = [latex]1/(2^n)[/latex]\r\n[latex]P(B|A)[/latex] = Probability of test T1 passing (getting the correct output) for a given input I1, given X uses the correct algorithm = 1\r\n</strong>\r\n\r\nTherefore, using Bayes\' Theorem:\r\n\r\n[latex]P\\left(A|B\\right)[/latex] = Probability that X uses the correct algorithm given test passes for a given input I1\r\n[latex]\r\n            = P\\left(B|A\\right).P\\left(A\\right)/P\\left(B\\right)\r\n            = p.2^n\r\n[/latex]\r\n\r\n[latex]P\\left(1\\right)=p.2^n[/latex]\r\n\r\n*Note that after writing one test, the probability of X using the correct algorithm has increased (n>=1) by a factor of 2^n.*\r\n\r\nLet us now write another test with input I2. Note that I assume that T1 passing does not affect any probabilities other than the updated probability of X using the correct algorithm, i.e., the tests are statistically independent (I believe that\'s the term used :-).\r\n\r\n[latex]P\\left(A\\right)[/latex] = Probability that X uses the correct algorithm = [latex]p*\\left(2^n\\right)[/latex]\r\n[latex]P\\left(B\\right)[/latex] = Probability of test T2 passing (getting the correct output) for a given input I2 = [latex]1/\\left(2^n\\right)[/latex]\r\n[latex]P\\left(B|A\\right)[/latex] = Probability of test T2 passing (getting the correct output) for a given input I2, given X uses the correct algorithm = 1\r\n\r\nTherefore, using Bayes\' Theorem:\r\n\r\n[latex]P\\left(A|B\\right)[/latex] = Probability that X uses the correct algorithm given test passes for a given input I2\r\n[latex]\r\n            = P\\left(B|A\\right).P\\left(A\\right)/P\\left(B\\right)\r\n            = p.2^n.2^n[/latex]\r\n\r\nP\\left(2\\right)=p.2^n.2^n[/latex]\r\nAfter having written t tests, we may write:\r\n\r\n[latex]P\\left(t\\right)=p.[2^{nt}][/latex]\r\n\r\n*<i>t</i> tests, therefore, increase the probability (or our knowledge, in very rough terms) of X being implemented correctly, by a factor of [latex]2^nt[/latex].*\r\nProbability is inversely correlated with entropy; thus, we have also reduced the entropy of the system.\r\nIt might be useful to state that I use the term \'test\' in a broad sense. The test may range from an automated unit test to human verification.\r\n\r\nIt turns out that it should be possible to determine p. Note that t is the number of *statistically independent tests* that we can write. This implies that t has a fixed upper bound. Thus:\r\n\r\nT = total number of statistically independent tests for X\r\n[latex]\r\np.[2^{nT}] <= 1, or,\r\np <= 1/[2^{nT}]\r\n[/latex]\r\n', 'Tests increase our Knowledge of a System: A Probabilistic Proof', 0, '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '181-revision-12', '', '', '2011-07-25 08:11:03', '2011-07-25 16:11:03', '', 181, 'http://avishek.net/blog/?p=475', 0, 'revision', '', 0); 
