t after writing one test, the probability of X using the correct algorithm has increased (n>=1) by a factor of 2^n.*\r\n\r\nLet us now write another test with input I2. Note that I assume that T1 passing does not affect any probabilities other than the updated probability of X using the correct algorithm, i.e., the tests are statistically independent (I believe that\'s the term used :-).\r\n\r\n[latex]P\\left(A\\right)[/latex] = Probability that X uses the correct algorithm = [latex]p*\\left(2^n\\right)[/latex]\r\n[latex]P\\left(B\\right)[/latex] = Probability of test T2 passing (getting the correct output) for a given input I2 = [latex]1/\\left(2^n\\right)[/latex]\r\n[latex]P\\left(B|A\\right)[/latex] = Probability of test T2 passing (getting the correct output) for a given input I2, given X uses the correct algorithm = 1\r\n\r\nTherefore, using Bayes\' Theorem:\r\n\r\n[latex]P\\left(A|B\\right)[/latex] = Probability that X uses the correct algorithm given test passes for a given input I2\r\n[latex]\r\n            = P\\left(B|A\\right).P\\left(A\\right)/P\\left(B\\right)\r\n            = p.2^n.2^n[/latex]\r\n\r\nP\\left(2\\right)=p.2^n.2^n[/latex]\r\nAfter having written t tests, we may write:\r\n\r\n[latex]P\\left(t\\right)=p.[2^{nt}][/latex]\r\n\r\n*<i>t</i> tests, therefore, increase the probability (or our knowledge, in very rough terms) of X being implemented correctly, by a factor of [latex]2^nt[/latex].*\r\nProbability is inversely correlated with entropy; thus, we have also reduced the entropy of the system.\r\nIt might be useful to state that I use the term \'test\' in a broad sense. The test may range from an automated unit test to human verification.\r\n\r\nIt turns out that it should be possible to determine p. Note that t is the number of *statistically independent tests* that we can write. This implies that t has a fixed upper bound. Thus:\r\n\r\nT = total number of statistically independent tests for X\r\n[latex]\r\np.[2^{nT}] <= 1, or,\r\np <= 1/[2^{nT}]\r\n[/latex]\r\n', 'Tests increase our Knowledge of a System: A Probabilistic Proof', 0, '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '181-revision-13', '', '', '2011-07-25 08:11:55', '2011-07-25 16:11:55', '', 181, 'http://avishek.net/blog/?p=476', 0, 'revision', '', 0); 
