kes care of mapping the result to the display, including flipping the y-component.\r\n\r\nThe two numbers in the <code>draw_axes</code> method of <code>Screen</code> are the intervals for marking the ticks along the two basis vectors, respectively. The matrix <strong>[[4,0],[0,2]]</strong> in the constructor of <code>CoordinateSystem</code> gives the scaling/rotation of the data <strong>as specified in the basis vector space that you\'ve defined</strong>; use it for stretching an axis that looks compressed or squeezing one which looks large.\r\n\r\nThe output looks like this:\r\n\r\n<a href="http://avishek.net/blog/wp-content/uploads/2011/08/SimpleDemo-Basis.png"><img src="http://avishek.net/blog/wp-content/uploads/2011/08/SimpleDemo-Basis-300x256.png" alt="" title="SimpleDemo-Basis" width="300" height="256" class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-563" /></a>\r\n\r\nAs always, the code and the gem are available on <a href="https://github.com/asengupta/Basis">GitHub</a>.', 'A short introduction to using Basis', 0, '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '562-revision-5', '', '', '2011-08-16 11:39:40', '2011-08-16 19:39:40', '', 562, 'http://avishek.net/blog/?p=568', 0, 'revision', '', 0); 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (572, 1, '2011-08-20 05:44:31', '2011-08-20 13:44:31', 'You can use Ruby-Processing in two ways.\r\n\r\n<ul>Use the jruby-complete.jar that Ruby-Processing ships, the Gems-in-a-Jar approach. In this mode, all gems you install will be packaged as part of the JAR.</ul>\r\n<ul>Using the JRuby already installed on your system.</ul>\r\n\r\nIf you\'re following the first approach, first head to the location where the jruby-complete.jar is located, for Ruby-Processing. There, do this:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\njava -jar jruby-complete.jar -S gem install basis-processing --user-install\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nAlternatively, if you\'re using a conventional JRuby installation, do this:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\nsudo jruby -S gem install basis-processing\r\n[/code]\r\n', 'Installing the Basis gem (updated for v0.5.1+)', 0, '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'installing-the-basis-gem', '', '', '2011-10-06 10:38:38', '2011-10-06 18:38:38', '', 0, 'http://avishek.net/blog/?p=572', 0, 'post', '', 0); 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (569, 1, '2011-08-16 11:40:25', '2011-08-16 19:40:25', 'I spent much of today cleaning up the unholy mess in <a href="https://github.com/asengupta/Basis">Basis</a>, and teasing out a few classes (and a module). To finish that off, here\'s a quick guide to using Basis. Of course, expect this to change (somewhat) frequently, but the kernel of the idea should, hopefully, remain the same.\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language="ruby"]\r\nrequire \'ranges\'\r\nrequire \'transform\'\r\nrequire \'coordinate_system\'\r\nrequire \'screen\'\r\n\r\nclass Demo &lt; Processing::App\r\n	app = self\r\n	def setup\r\n		smooth\r\n		background(0,0,0)\r\n		color_mode(RGB, 1.0)\r\n\r\n		points = []\r\n		100.times {points &lt;&lt; {:x =&gt; random(200), :y =&gt; random(300)}}\r\n\r\n		x_basis_vector = {:x =&gt; 1.0, :y =&gt; 0.0}\r\n		y_basis_vector = {:x =&gt; 0.0, :y =&gt; 1.0}\r\n\r\n		x_range = ContinuousRange.new({:minimum =&gt; 0, :maximum =&gt; 200})\r\n		y_range = ContinuousRange.new({:minimum =&gt; 0, :maximum =&gt; 300})\r\n\r\n		basis = CoordinateSystem.new(Axis.new(x_basis_vector,x_range), Axis.new(y_basis_vector,y_range), [[4,0],[0,2]], self)\r\n		screen_transform = SignedTransform.new({:x =&gt; 1, :y =&gt; -1}, {:x =&gt; 300, :y =&gt; 900})\r\n		screen = Screen.new(screen_transform, self)\r\n		screen.draw_axes(basis,10,10)\r\n		stroke(1,1,0,1)\r\n		fill(1,1,0)\r\n		points.each do |p|\r\n			screen.plot(p, basis)\r\n		end\r\n	end\r\n	  \r\n	def draw\r\n	end\r\nend\r\n\r\nw = 1200\r\nh = 1000\r\n\r\nDemo.new(:title =&gt; &quot;My Sketch&quot;, :width =&gt; w, :height =&gt; h)\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nThe <code>x_basis_vector</code> and <code>y_basis_vector</code> variables correspond to the two basis vectors of our coordinate system. The <code>Axis</code> class encapsulates them together with the range of values along each dimension. The <code>CoordinateSystem</code> class encapsulates two <code>Axis</code> objects to manipulate our basis. The <code>Screen</code> class takes care of mapping the result to the display, including flipping the y-component.\r\n\r\nThe two numbers in the <code>draw_axes</code> method of <code>Screen</code> are the intervals for marking the ticks along the two basis vectors, respectively. The matrix <strong>[[4,0],[0,2]]</strong> in the constructor of <code>CoordinateSystem</code> gives the scaling/rotation of the data <strong>as specified in the basis vector space that you\'ve defined</strong>; use it for stretching an axis that looks compressed or squeezing one which looks large.\r\n\r\nThe output looks like this:\r\n\r\n<a href="http://avishek.net/blog/wp-content/uploads/2011/08/SimpleDemo-Basis.png"><img src="http://avishek.net/blog/wp-content/uploads/2011/08/SimpleDemo-Basis-300x256.png" alt="" title="SimpleDemo-Basis" width="300" height="256" class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-563" /></a>\r\n\r\nAs always, the code and the gem are available on <a href="https://github.com/asengupta/Basis">GitHub</a>.', 'A short introduction to using Basis', 0, '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '562-revision-6', '', '', '2011-08-16 11:40:25', '2011-08-16 19:40:25', '', 562, 'http://avishek.net/blog/?p=569', 0, 'revision', '', 0); 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (570, 1, '2011-08-16 11:40:59', '2011-08-16 19:40:59', 'I spent much of today cleaning up the unholy mess in <a href="https://github.com/asengupta/Basis">Basis</a>, and teasing out a few classes (and a module). To finish that off, here\'s a quick guide to using Basis. Of course, expect this to change (somewhat) frequently, but the kernel of the idea should, hopefully, remain the same.\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language="ruby"]\r\nrequire \'ranges\'\r\nrequire \'transform\'\r\nrequire \'coordinate_system\'\r\nrequire \'screen\'\r\n\r\nclass Demo &lt; Processing::App\r\n	app = self\r\n	def setup\r\n		smooth\r\n		background(0,0,0)\r\n		color_mode(RGB, 1.0)\r\n\r\n		points = []\r\n		100.times {points &lt;&lt; {:x =&gt; random(200), :y =&gt; random(300)}}\r\n\r\n		x_basis_vector = {:x =&gt; 1.0, :y =&gt; 0.0}\r\n		y_basis_vector = {:x =&gt; 0.0, :y =&gt; 1.0}\r\n\r\n		x_range = ContinuousRange.new({:minimum =&gt; 0, :maximum =&gt; 200})\r\n		y_range = ContinuousRange.new({:minimum =&gt; 0, :maximum =&gt; 300})\r\n\r\n		basis = CoordinateSystem.new(Axis.new(x_basis_vector,x_range), Axis.new(y_basis_vector,y_range), [[4,0],[0,2]], self)\r\n		screen_transform = SignedTransform.new({:x =&gt; 1, :y =&gt; -1}, {:x =&gt; 300, :y =&gt; 900})\r\n		screen = Screen.new(screen_transform, self)\r\n		screen.draw_axes(basis,10,10)\r\n		stroke(1,1,0,1)\r\n		fill(1,1,0)\r\n		points.each do |p|\r\n			screen.plot(p, basis)\r\n		end\r\n	end\r\n	  \r\n	def draw\r\n	end\r\nend\r\n\r\nw = 1200\r\nh = 1000\r\n\r\nDemo.new(:title =&gt; &quot;My Sketch&quot;, :width =&gt; w, :height =&gt; h)\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nThe <code>x_basis_vector</code> and <code>y_basis_vector</code> variables correspond to the two basis vectors of our coordinate system. The <code>Axis</code> class encapsulates them together with the range of values along each dimension. The <code>CoordinateSystem</code> class encapsulates two <code>Axis</code> objects to manipulate our basis. The <code>Screen</code> class takes care of mapping the result to the display, including flipping the y-component.\r\n\r\nThe two numbers in the <code>draw_axes</code> method of <code>Screen</code> are the intervals for marking the ticks along the two basis vectors, respectively. The matrix <strong>[[4,0],[0,2]]</strong> in the constructor of <code>CoordinateSystem</code> gives the scaling/rotation of the data <strong>as specified in the basis vector space that you\'ve defined</strong>; use it for stretching an axis that looks compressed or squeezing one which looks large.\r\n\r\nThe output looks like this:\r\n\r\n<a href="http://avishek.net/blog/wp-content/uploads/2011/08/SimpleDemo-Basis.png"><img src="http://avishek.net/blog/wp-content/uploads/2011/08/SimpleDemo-Basis-300x256.png" alt="" title="SimpleDemo-Basis" width="300" height="256" class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-563" /></a>\r\n\r\nAs always, the code and the gem are available on <a href="https://github.com/asengupta/Basis">GitHub</a>.', 'A short guide to using Basis', 0, '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '562-revision-7', '', '', '2011-08-16 11:40:59', '2011-08-16 19:40:59', '', 562, 'http://avishek.net/blog/?p=570', 0, 'revision', '', 0); 
