INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (613, 1, '2011-08-20 10:40:38', '2011-08-20 18:40:38', 'I spent much of today cleaning up the unholy mess in <a href="https://github.com/asengupta/Basis">Basis</a>, and teasing out a few classes (and a module). To finish that off, here\'s a quick guide to using Basis. Of course, expect this to change (somewhat) frequently, but the kernel of the idea should, hopefully, remain the same.\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language="ruby"]\r\nrequire \'rubygems\'\r\ngem \'basis-processing\'\r\nrequire \'basis_processing\'\r\n\r\nclass Demo &lt; Processing::App\r\n    app = self\r\n    def setup\r\n        smooth\r\n        background(0,0,0)\r\n        color_mode(RGB, 1.0)\r\n \r\n        points = []\r\n        100.times {points &lt;&lt; {:x =&gt; random(200), :y =&gt; random(300)}}\r\n \r\n        x_basis_vector = {:x =&gt; 1.0, :y =&gt; 0.0}\r\n        y_basis_vector = {:x =&gt; 0.0, :y =&gt; 1.0}\r\n \r\n        x_range = ContinuousRange.new({:minimum =&gt; 0, :maximum =&gt; 200})\r\n        y_range = ContinuousRange.new({:minimum =&gt; 0, :maximum =&gt; 300})\r\n \r\n        basis = CoordinateSystem.new(Axis.new(x_basis_vector,x_range), Axis.new(y_basis_vector,y_range), [[4,0],[0,2]], self)\r\n        screen_transform = SignedTransform.new({:x =&gt; 1, :y =&gt; -1}, {:x =&gt; 300, :y =&gt; 900})\r\n        screen = Screen.new(screen_transform, self)\r\n        screen.draw_axes(basis,10,10)\r\n        stroke(1,1,0,1)\r\n        fill(1,1,0)\r\n        points.each do |p|\r\n            screen.plot(p, basis)\r\n        end\r\n    end\r\n \r\n    def draw\r\n    end\r\nend\r\n \r\nw = 1200\r\nh = 1000\r\n \r\nDemo.new(:title =&gt; &quot;My Sketch&quot;, :width =&gt; w, :height =&gt; h)\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nThe <code>x_basis_vector</code> and <code>y_basis_vector</code> variables correspond to the two basis vectors of our coordinate system. The <code>Axis</code> class encapsulates them together with the range of values along each dimension. The <code>CoordinateSystem</code> class encapsulates two <code>Axis</code> objects to manipulate our basis. The <code>Screen</code> class takes care of mapping the result to the display, including flipping the y-component.\r\n\r\nThe two numbers in the <code>draw_axes</code> method of <code>Screen</code> are the intervals for marking the ticks along the two basis vectors, respectively. The matrix <strong>[[4,0],[0,2]]</strong> in the constructor of <code>CoordinateSystem</code> gives the scaling/rotation of the data <em>as specified in the basis vector space that you\'ve defined</em>; use it for stretching an axis that looks compressed or squeezing one which looks large.\r\n\r\nThe output looks like this:\r\n\r\n<a href="http://avishek.net/blog/wp-content/uploads/2011/08/SimpleDemo-Basis.png"><img src="http://avishek.net/blog/wp-content/uploads/2011/08/SimpleDemo-Basis-300x256.png" alt="" title="SimpleDemo-Basis" width="300" height="256" class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-563" /></a>\r\n\r\nAs always, the code is available on <a href="https://github.com/asengupta/Basis">GitHub</a>.', 'A short guide to using Basis', 0, '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '562-revision-11', '', '', '2011-08-20 10:40:38', '2011-08-20 18:40:38', '', 562, 'http://avishek.net/blog/?p=613', 0, 'revision', '', 0); 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (615, 1, '2011-10-05 22:06:28', '2011-10-06 06:06:28', 'I spent much of today cleaning up the unholy mess in <a href="https://github.com/asengupta/Basis">Basis</a>, and teasing out a few classes (and a module). To finish that off, here\'s a quick guide to using Basis. Of course, expect this to change (somewhat) frequently, but the kernel of the idea should, hopefully, remain the same.\r\n\r\n[gist]http://gist.github.com/1266616[/gist]\r\n\r\nThe <code>x_basis_vector</code> and <code>y_basis_vector</code> variables correspond to the two basis vectors of our coordinate system. The <code>Axis</code> class encapsulates them together with the range of values along each dimension. The <code>CoordinateSystem</code> class encapsulates two <code>Axis</code> objects to manipulate our basis. The <code>Screen</code> class takes care of mapping the result to the display, including flipping the y-component.\r\n\r\nThe two numbers in the <code>draw_axes</code> method of <code>Screen</code> are the intervals for marking the ticks along the two basis vectors, respectively. The matrix <strong>[[4,0],[0,2]]</strong> in the constructor of <code>CoordinateSystem</code> gives the scaling/rotation of the data <em>as specified in the basis vector space that you\'ve defined</em>; use it for stretching an axis that looks compressed or squeezing one which looks large.\r\n\r\nThe output looks like this:\r\n\r\n<a href="http://avishek.net/blog/wp-content/uploads/2011/08/SimpleDemo-Basis.png"><img src="http://avishek.net/blog/wp-content/uploads/2011/08/SimpleDemo-Basis-300x256.png" alt="" title="SimpleDemo-Basis" width="300" height="256" class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-563" /></a>\r\n\r\nYou have a few options when plotting a point. If you specify \':bar => true\', like the line below:\r\n\r\n[sourcecode]\r\n	screen.plot(p, basis, :bar =&gt; true) {|p| rect(p[:x], p[:y], 5, 5)}\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nit will connect the point with the x-axis. If you omit `:bar => true` or don\'t specify any options, Basis will plot the points without connecting them to the X-axis.\r\nIf you omit the block at the end of the call, Basis will plot the point using a circle. Use the block to customise how you wish to represent the point graphically.\r\nYou can toggle the joining of the points with lines by setting the join attribute of Screen to on (joins points)/off (no joining). The default is false.\r\n\r\nVersion 0.5.0 introduces experimental support for mouseover interactivity without extra effort on your part. To allow interactions to happen, you must specify \':track => true\' while plotting a point, as in the line below:\r\n\r\n[sourcecode]\r\n	@screen.plot(p, :track =&gt; true) {|p| rect(p[:x], p[:y], 5, 5)}\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nTo actually enable interactivity, you must \'include\' the Interactive module in your sketch class, as in the demonstration code above. Interactivity is a work in progress at the moment.\r\n\r\nAs always, the code is available on <a href="https://github.com/asengupta/Basis">GitHub</a>.\r\n', 'A short guide to using Basis (updated)', 0, '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '562-revision-13', '', '', '2011-10-05 22:06:28', '2011-10-06 06:06:28', '', 562, 'http://avishek.net/blog/?p=615', 0, 'revision', '', 0); 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (614, 1, '2011-10-05 22:05:59', '2011-10-06 06:05:59', 'I spent much of today cleaning up the unholy mess in <a href="https://github.com/asengupta/Basis">Basis</a>, and teasing out a few classes (and a module). To finish that off, here\'s a quick guide to using Basis. Of course, expect this to change (somewhat) frequently, but the kernel of the idea should, hopefully, remain the same.\r\n\r\n[gist]http://gist.github.com/1266616[/gist]\r\n[sourcecode language="ruby"]\r\nrequire \'rubygems\'\r\nGem.clear_paths\r\nENV[\'GEM_HOME\'] = \'/home/avishek/jruby/jruby-1.6.3/lib/ruby/gems/1.8\'\r\nENV[\'GEM_PATH\'] = \'/home/avishek/jruby/jruby-1.6.3/lib/ruby/gems/1.8\'\r\n\r\nrequire \'basis_processing\'\r\n\r\nclass Demo &lt; Processing::App\r\n	include Interactive\r\n	app = self\r\n	def setup\r\n		smooth\r\n		background(0,0,0)\r\n		color_mode(RGB, 1.0)\r\n		stroke(1,1,0,1)\r\n		@highlight_block = lambda do |p|\r\n					rect_mode(CENTER)\r\n					stroke(1,0,0)\r\n					fill(1,0,0)\r\n					rect(p[:x], p[:y], 5, 5)\r\n				   end\r\n\r\n		@passive_block = lambda do |p|\r\n					rect_mode(CENTER)\r\n					stroke(1,1,0,1)\r\n					fill(1,1,0)\r\n					rect(p[:x], p[:y], 5, 5)\r\n				   end\r\n\r\n		points = []\r\n		200.times {|n|points &lt;&lt; {:x =&gt; n, :y =&gt; random(300)}}\r\n\r\n		x_basis_vector = {:x =&gt; 1.0, :y =&gt; 0.0}\r\n		y_basis_vector = {:x =&gt; 0.0, :y =&gt; 1.0}\r\n\r\n		x_range = ContinuousRange.new({:minimum =&gt; 0, :maximum =&gt; 200})\r\n		y_range = ContinuousRange.new({:minimum =&gt; 0, :maximum =&gt; 300})\r\n\r\n		@basis = CoordinateSystem.new(Axis.new(x_basis_vector,x_range), Axis.new(y_basis_vector,y_range), [[4,0],[0,2]], self)\r\n		screen_transform = SignedTransform.new({:x =&gt; 1, :y =&gt; -1}, {:x =&gt; 300, :y =&gt; 900})\r\n		@screen = Screen.new(screen_transform, self, @basis)\r\n		@screen.join=true\r\n		@screen.draw_axes(10,10)\r\n		stroke(1,1,0,1)\r\n		fill(1,1,0)\r\n		rect_mode(CENTER)\r\n		points.each do |p|\r\n			@screen.plot(p, :track =&gt; true) {|p| rect(p[:x], p[:y], 5, 5)}\r\n		end\r\n	end\r\nend\r\n\r\nw = 1200\r\nh = 1000\r\n\r\nDemo.new(:title =&gt; &quot;My Sketch&quot;, :width =&gt; w, :height =&gt; h)\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nThe <code>x_basis_vector</code> and <code>y_basis_vector</code> variables correspond to the two basis vectors of our coordinate system. The <code>Axis</code> class encapsulates them together with the range of values along each dimension. The <code>CoordinateSystem</code> class encapsulates two <code>Axis</code> objects to manipulate our basis. The <code>Screen</code> class takes care of mapping the result to the display, including flipping the y-component.\r\n\r\nThe two numbers in the <code>draw_axes</code> method of <code>Screen</code> are the intervals for marking the ticks along the two basis vectors, respectively. The matrix <strong>[[4,0],[0,2]]</strong> in the constructor of <code>CoordinateSystem</code> gives the scaling/rotation of the data <em>as specified in the basis vector space that you\'ve defined</em>; use it for stretching an axis that looks compressed or squeezing one which looks large.\r\n\r\nThe output looks like this:\r\n\r\n<a href="http://avishek.net/blog/wp-content/uploads/2011/08/SimpleDemo-Basis.png"><img src="http://avishek.net/blog/wp-content/uploads/2011/08/SimpleDemo-Basis-300x256.png" alt="" title="SimpleDemo-Basis" width="300" height="256" class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-563" /></a>\r\n\r\nYou have a few options when plotting a point. If you specify \':bar => true\', like the line below:\r\n\r\n[sourcecode]\r\n	screen.plot(p, basis, :bar =&gt; true) {|p| rect(p[:x], p[:y], 5, 5)}\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nit will connect the point with the x-axis. If you omit `:bar => true` or don\'t specify any options, Basis will plot the points without connecting them to the X-axis.\r\nIf you omit the block at the end of the call, Basis will plot the point using a circle. Use the block to customise how you wish to represent the point graphically.\r\nYou can toggle the joining of the points with lines by setting the join attribute of Screen to on (joins points)/off (no joining). The default is false.\r\n\r\nVersion 0.5.0 introduces experimental support for mouseover interactivity without extra effort on your part. To allow interactions to happen, you must specify \':track => true\' while plotting a point, as in the line below:\r\n\r\n[sourcecode]\r\n	@screen.plot(p, :track =&gt; true) {|p| rect(p[:x], p[:y], 5, 5)}\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nTo actually enable interactivity, you must \'include\' the Interactive module in your sketch class, as in the demonstration code above. Interactivity is a work in progress at the moment.\r\n\r\nAs always, the code is available on <a href="https://github.com/asengupta/Basis">GitHub</a>.\r\n', 'A short guide to using Basis (updated)', 0, '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '562-revision-12', '', '', '2011-10-05 22:05:59', '2011-10-06 06:05:59', '', 562, 'http://avishek.net/blog/?p=614', 0, 'revision', '', 0); 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (616, 1, '2011-10-05 22:07:37', '2011-10-06 06:07:37', 'I spent much of today cleaning up the unholy mess in <a href="https://github.com/asengupta/Basis">Basis</a>, and teasing out a few classes (and a module). To finish that off, here\'s a quick guide to using Basis. Of course, expect this to change (somewhat) frequently, but the kernel of the idea should, hopefully, remain the same.\r\n\r\n[gist]http://gist.github.com/1266616[/gist]\r\n\r\nThe <code>x_basis_vector</code> and <code>y_basis_vector</code> variables correspond to the two basis vectors of our coordinate system. The <code>Axis</code> class encapsulates them together with the range of values along each dimension. The <code>CoordinateSystem</code> class encapsulates two <code>Axis</code> objects to manipulate our basis. The <code>Screen</code> class takes care of mapping the result to the display, including flipping the y-component.\r\n\r\nThe two numbers in the <code>draw_axes</code> method of <code>Screen</code> are the intervals for marking the ticks along the two basis vectors, respectively. The matrix <strong>[[4,0],[0,2]]</strong> in the constructor of <code>CoordinateSystem</code> gives the scaling/rotation of the data <em>as specified in the basis vector space that you\'ve defined</em>; use it for stretching an axis that looks compressed or squeezing one which looks large.\r\n\r\nThe output looks like this:\r\n\r\n<a href="http://avishek.net/blog/wp-content/uploads/2011/08/SimpleDemo-Basis.png"><img src="http://avishek.net/blog/wp-content/uploads/2011/08/SimpleDemo-Basis-300x256.png" alt="" title="SimpleDemo-Basis" width="300" height="256" class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-563" /></a>\r\n\r\nYou have a few options when plotting a point. If you specify \':bar => true\', like the line below:\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language="ruby"]\r\n	screen.plot(p, basis, :bar =&gt; true) {|p| rect(p[:x], p[:y], 5, 5)}\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nit will connect the point with the x-axis. If you omit `:bar => true` or don\'t specify any options, Basis will plot the points without connecting them to the X-axis.\r\nIf you omit the block at the end of the call, Basis will plot the point using a circle. Use the block to customise how you wish to represent the point graphically.\r\nYou can toggle the joining of the points with lines by setting the join attribute of Screen to on (joins points)/off (no joining). The default is false.\r\n\r\nVersion 0.5.0 introduces experimental support for mouseover interactivity without extra effort on your part. To allow interactions to happen, you must specify \':track => true\' while plotting a point, as in the line below:\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language="ruby"]\r\n	@screen.plot(p, :track =&gt; true) {|p| rect(p[:x], p[:y], 5, 5)}\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nTo actually enable interactivity, you must \'include\' the Interactive module in your sketch class, as in the demonstration code above. Interactivity is a work in progress at the moment.\r\n\r\nAs always, the code is available on <a href="https://github.com/asengupta/Basis">GitHub</a>.\r\n', 'A short guide to using Basis (updated)', 0, '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '562-revision-14', '', '', '2011-10-05 22:07:37', '2011-10-06 06:07:37', '', 562, 'http://avishek.net/blog/?p=616', 0, 'revision', '', 0); 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (617, 1, '2011-10-05 22:08:17', '2011-10-06 06:08:17', 'I spent much of today cleaning up the unholy mess in <a href="https://github.com/asengupta/Basis">Basis</a>, and teasing out a few classes (and a module). To finish that off, here\'s a quick guide to using Basis. Of course, expect this to change (somewhat) frequently, but the kernel of the idea should, hopefully, remain the same.\r\n\r\n[gist]http://gist.github.com/1266616[/gist]\r\n\r\nThe <code>x_basis_vector</code> and <code>y_basis_vector</code> variables correspond to the two basis vectors of our coordinate system. The <code>Axis</code> class encapsulates them together with the range of values along each dimension. The <code>CoordinateSystem</code> class encapsulates two <code>Axis</code> objects to manipulate our basis. The <code>Screen</code> class takes care of mapping the result to the display, including flipping the y-component.\r\n\r\nThe two numbers in the <code>draw_axes</code> method of <code>Screen</code> are the intervals for marking the ticks along the two basis vectors, respectively. The matrix <strong>[[4,0],[0,2]]</strong> in the constructor of <code>CoordinateSystem</code> gives the scaling/rotation of the data <em>as specified in the basis vector space that you\'ve defined</em>; use it for stretching an axis that looks compressed or squeezing one which looks large.\r\n\r\nThe output looks like this:\r\n\r\n<a href="http://avishek.net/blog/wp-content/uploads/2011/08/SimpleDemo-Basis.png"><img src="http://avishek.net/blog/wp-content/uploads/2011/08/SimpleDemo-Basis-300x256.png" alt="" title="SimpleDemo-Basis" width="300" height="256" class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-563" /></a>\r\n\r\nYou have a few options when plotting a point. If you specify \':bar => true\', like the line below:\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language="ruby"]\r\n	@screen.plot(p, basis, :bar =&gt; true) {|p| rect(p[:x], p[:y], 5, 5)}\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nit will connect the point with the x-axis. If you omit `:bar => true` or don\'t specify any options, Basis will plot the points without connecting them to the X-axis.\r\nIf you omit the block at the end of the call, Basis will plot the point using a circle. Use the block to customise how you wish to represent the point graphically.\r\nYou can toggle the joining of the points with lines by setting the join attribute of Screen to on (joins points)/off (no joining). The default is false.\r\n\r\nVersion 0.5.0 introduces experimental support for mouseover interactivity without extra effort on your part. To allow interactions to happen, you must specify \':track => true\' while plotting a point, as in the line below:\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language="ruby"]\r\n	@screen.plot(p, :track =&gt; true) {|p| rect(p[:x], p[:y], 5, 5)}\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nTo actually enable interactivity, you must \'include\' the Interactive module in your sketch class, as in the demonstration code above. Interactivity is a work in progress at the moment.\r\n\r\nAs always, the code is available on <a href="https://github.com/asengupta/Basis">GitHub</a>.\r\n', 'A short guide to using Basis (updated)', 0, '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '562-revision-15', '', '', '2011-10-05 22:08:17', '2011-10-06 06:08:17', '', 562, 'http://avishek.net/blog/?p=617', 0, 'revision', '', 0); 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (618, 1, '2011-10-05 22:11:31', '2011-10-06 06:11:31', 'I spent much of today cleaning up the unholy mess in <a href="https://github.com/asengupta/Basis">Basis</a>, and teasing out a few classes (and a module). To finish that off, here\'s a quick guide to using Basis. Of course, expect this to change (somewhat) frequently, but the kernel of the idea should, hopefully, remain the same.\r\n\r\n<strong>UPDATE</strong>: Basis is now at version 0.5.0 with experimental support for mouseover interactivity. More work is incoming, but the demo code below is up-to-date, for now. The code below should be the same as <a href="https://github.com/asengupta/Basis/blob/master/lib/demo.rb">demo.rb on GitHub</a>.\r\n[gist]http://gist.github.com/1266616[/gist]\r\n\r\nThe <code>x_basis_vector</code> and <code>y_basis_vector</code> variables correspond to the two basis vectors of our coordinate system. The <code>Axis</code> class encapsulates them together with the range of values along each dimension. The <code>CoordinateSystem</code> class encapsulates two <code>Axis</code> objects to manipulate our basis. The <code>Screen</code> class takes care of mapping the result to the display, including flipping the y-component.\r\n\r\nThe two numbers in the <code>draw_axes</code> method of <code>Screen</code> are the intervals for marking the ticks along the two basis vectors, respectively. The matrix <strong>[[4,0],[0,2]]</strong> in the constructor of <code>CoordinateSystem</code> gives the scaling/rotation of the data <em>as specified in the basis vector space that you\'ve defined</em>; use it for stretching an axis that looks compressed or squeezing one which looks large.\r\n\r\nThe output looks like this:\r\n\r\n<a href="http://avishek.net/blog/wp-content/uploads/2011/08/SimpleDemo-Basis.png"><img src="http://avishek.net/blog/wp-content/uploads/2011/08/SimpleDemo-Basis-300x256.png" alt="" title="SimpleDemo-Basis" width="300" height="256" class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-563" /></a>\r\n\r\nYou have a few options when plotting a point. If you specify \':bar => true\', like the line below:\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language="ruby"]\r\n	@screen.plot(p, basis, :bar =&gt; true) {|p| rect(p[:x], p[:y], 5, 5)}\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nit will connect the point with the x-axis. If you omit `:bar => true` or don\'t specify any options, Basis will plot the points without connecting them to the X-axis.\r\nIf you omit the block at the end of the call, Basis will plot the point using a circle. Use the block to customise how you wish to represent the point graphically.\r\nYou can toggle the joining of the points with lines by setting the join attribute of Screen to on (joins points)/off (no joining). The default is false.\r\n\r\nVersion 0.5.0 introduces experimental support for mouseover interactivity without extra effort on your part. To allow interactions to happen, you must specify \':track => true\' while plotting a point, as in the line below:\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language="ruby"]\r\n	@screen.plot(p, :track =&gt; true) {|p| rect(p[:x], p[:y], 5, 5)}\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nTo actually enable interactivity, you must \'include\' the Interactive module in your sketch class, as in the demonstration code above. Interactivity is a work in progress at the moment.\r\n\r\nAs always, the code is available on <a href="https://github.com/asengupta/Basis">GitHub</a>.\r\n', 'A short guide to using Basis (updated)', 0, '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '562-revision-16', '', '', '2011-10-05 22:11:31', '2011-10-06 06:11:31', '', 562, 'http://avishek.net/blog/?p=618', 0, 'revision', '', 0); 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (619, 1, '2011-10-05 22:12:14', '2011-10-06 06:12:14', 'I spent much of today cleaning up the unholy mess in <a href="https://github.com/asengupta/Basis">Basis</a>, and teasing out a few classes (and a module). To finish that off, here\'s a quick guide to using Basis. Of course, expect this to change (somewhat) frequently, but the kernel of the idea should, hopefully, remain the same.\r\n\r\n<strong>UPDATE</strong>: Basis is now at version 0.5.0 with experimental support for mouseover interactivity. More work is incoming, but the demo code below is up-to-date, for now. The code below should be the same as <a href="https://github.com/asengupta/Basis/blob/master/lib/demo.rb">demo.rb on GitHub</a>.\r\n[gist]http://gist.github.com/1266616[/gist]\r\n\r\nThe <code>x_basis_vector</code> and <code>y_basis_vector</code> variables correspond to the two basis vectors of our coordinate system. The <code>Axis</code> class encapsulates them together with the range of values along each dimension. The <code>CoordinateSystem</code> class encapsulates two <code>Axis</code> objects to manipulate our basis. The <code>Screen</code> class takes care of mapping the result to the display, including flipping the y-component.\r\n\r\nThe two numbers in the <code>draw_axes</code> method of <code>Screen</code> are the intervals for marking the ticks along the two basis vectors, respectively. The matrix <strong>[[4,0],[0,2]]</strong> in the constructor of <code>CoordinateSystem</code> gives the scaling/rotation of the data <em>as specified in the basis vector space that you\'ve defined</em>; use it for stretching an axis that looks compressed or squeezing one which looks large.\r\n\r\nThe output looks like this:\r\n\r\n<a href="http://avishek.net/blog/wp-content/uploads/2011/08/SimpleDemo-Basis.png"><img src="http://avishek.net/blog/wp-content/uploads/2011/08/SimpleDemo-Basis-300x256.png" alt="" title="SimpleDemo-Basis" width="300" height="256" class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-563" /></a>\r\n\r\nYou have a few options when plotting a point. If you specify \':bar => true\', like the line below:\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language="ruby"]\r\n	@screen.plot(p, basis, :bar =&gt; true) {|p| rect(p[:x], p[:y], 5, 5)}\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nit will connect the point with the x-axis. If you omit `:bar => true` or don\'t specify any options, Basis will plot the points without connecting them to the X-axis.\r\nIf you omit the block at the end of the call, Basis will plot the point using a circle. Use the block to customise how you wish to represent the point graphically.\r\nYou can toggle the joining of the points with lines by setting the join attribute of Screen to on (joins points)/off (no joining). The default is false.\r\n\r\nExperimental support exists for mouseover interactivity without extra effort on your part. To allow interactions to happen, you must specify \':track => true\' while plotting a point, as in the line below:\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language="ruby"]\r\n	@screen.plot(p, :track =&gt; true) {|p| rect(p[:x], p[:y], 5, 5)}\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nTo actually enable interactivity, you must \'include\' the Interactive module in your sketch class, as in the demonstration code above. Interactivity is a work in progress at the moment.\r\n\r\nAs always, the code is available on <a href="https://github.com/asengupta/Basis">GitHub</a>.\r\n', 'A short guide to using Basis (updated)', 0, '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '562-revision-17', '', '', '2011-10-05 22:12:14', '2011-10-06 06:12:14', '', 562, 'http://avishek.net/blog/?p=619', 0, 'revision', '', 0); 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (620, 1, '2011-10-05 22:12:30', '2011-10-06 06:12:30', 'I spent much of today cleaning up the unholy mess in <a href="https://github.com/asengupta/Basis">Basis</a>, and teasing out a few classes (and a module). To finish that off, here\'s a quick guide to using Basis. Of course, expect this to change (somewhat) frequently, but the kernel of the idea should, hopefully, remain the same.\r\n\r\n<strong>UPDATE</strong>: Basis is now at version 0.5.0 with experimental support for mouseover interactivity. More work is incoming, but the demo code below is up-to-date, for now. The code below should be the same as <a href="https://github.com/asengupta/Basis/blob/master/lib/demo.rb">demo.rb on GitHub</a>.\r\n[gist]http://gist.github.com/1266616[/gist]\r\n\r\nThe <code>x_basis_vector</code> and <code>y_basis_vector</code> variables correspond to the two basis vectors of our coordinate system. The <code>Axis</code> class encapsulates them together with the range of values along each dimension. The <code>CoordinateSystem</code> class encapsulates two <code>Axis</code> objects to manipulate our basis. The <code>Screen</code> class takes care of mapping the result to the display, including flipping the y-component.\r\n\r\nThe two numbers in the <code>draw_axes</code> method of <code>Screen</code> are the intervals for marking the ticks along the two basis vectors, respectively. The matrix <strong>[[4,0],[0,2]]</strong> in the constructor of <code>CoordinateSystem</code> gives the scaling/rotation of the data <em>as specified in the basis vector space that you\'ve defined</em>; use it for stretching an axis that looks compressed or squeezing one which looks large.\r\n\r\nThe output looks like this:\r\n\r\n<a href="http://avishek.net/blog/wp-content/uploads/2011/08/SimpleDemo-Basis.png"><img src="http://avishek.net/blog/wp-content/uploads/2011/08/SimpleDemo-Basis-300x256.png" alt="" title="SimpleDemo-Basis" width="300" height="256" class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-563" /></a>\r\n\r\nYou have a few options when plotting a point. If you specify \':bar => true\', like the line below:\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language="ruby"]\r\n	@screen.plot(p, basis, :bar =&gt; true) {|p| rect(p[:x], p[:y], 5, 5)}\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nit will connect the point with the x-axis. If you omit `:bar => true` or don\'t specify any options, Basis will plot the points without connecting them to the X-axis.\r\nIf you omit the block at the end of the call, Basis will plot the point using a circle. Use the block to customise how you wish to represent the point graphically.\r\nYou can toggle the joining of the points with lines by setting the join attribute of Screen to on (joins points)/off (no joining). The default is false.\r\n\r\nExperimental support exists for mouseover interactivity without (too much) extra effort on your part. To allow interactions to happen, you must specify \':track => true\' while plotting a point, as in the line below:\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language="ruby"]\r\n	@screen.plot(p, :track =&gt; true) {|p| rect(p[:x], p[:y], 5, 5)}\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nTo actually enable interactivity, you must \'include\' the Interactive module in your sketch class, as in the demonstration code above. Interactivity is a work in progress at the moment.\r\n\r\nAs always, the code is available on <a href="https://github.com/asengupta/Basis">GitHub</a>.\r\n', 'A short guide to using Basis (updated)', 0, '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '562-revision-18', '', '', '2011-10-05 22:12:30', '2011-10-06 06:12:30', '', 562, 'http://avishek.net/blog/?p=620', 0, 'revision', '', 0); 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (621, 1, '2011-10-06 09:05:59', '2011-10-06 17:05:59', 'I spent much of today cleaning up the unholy mess in <a href="https://github.com/asengupta/Basis">Basis</a>, and teasing out a few classes (and a module). To finish that off, here\'s a quick guide to using Basis. Of course, expect this to change (somewhat) frequently, but the kernel of the idea should, hopefully, remain the same.\r\n\r\n<strong>UPDATE</strong>: Basis is now at version 0.5.0 with experimental support for mouseover interactivity. More work is incoming, but the demo code below is up-to-date, for now. The code below should be the same as <a href="https://github.com/asengupta/Basis/blob/master/lib/demo.rb">demo.rb on GitHub</a>.\r\n[gist]http://gist.github.com/1266616[/gist]\r\n\r\nThe <code>x_basis_vector</code> and <code>y_basis_vector</code> variables correspond to the two basis vectors of our coordinate system. The <code>Axis</code> class encapsulates them together with the range of values along each dimension. The <code>CoordinateSystem</code> class encapsulates two <code>Axis</code> objects to manipulate our basis. The <code>Screen</code> class takes care of mapping the result to the display, including flipping the y-component.\r\n\r\nThe two numbers in the <code>draw_axes</code> method of <code>Screen</code> are the intervals for marking the ticks along the two basis vectors, respectively. The matrix <strong>[[4,0],[0,2]]</strong> in the constructor of <code>CoordinateSystem</code> gives the scaling/rotation of the data <em>as specified in the basis vector space that you\'ve defined</em>; use it for stretching an axis that looks compressed or squeezing one which looks large.\r\n\r\nThe output looks like this:\r\n\r\n<a href="http://avishek.net/blog/wp-content/uploads/2011/08/SimpleDemo-Basis.png"><img src="http://avishek.net/blog/wp-content/uploads/2011/08/SimpleDemo-Basis-300x256.png" alt="" title="SimpleDemo-Basis" width="300" height="256" class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-563" /></a>\r\n\r\nYou have a few options when plotting a point. If you specify \':bar => true\', like the line below:\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language="ruby"]\r\n	@screen.plot(p, basis, :bar =&gt; true) {|p| rect(p[:x], p[:y], 5, 5)}\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nit will connect the point with the x-axis. If you omit `:bar => true` or don\'t specify any options, Basis will plot the points without connecting them to the X-axis.\r\nIf you omit the block at the end of the call, Basis will plot the point using a circle. Use the block to customise how you wish to represent the point graphically.\r\nYou can toggle the joining of the points with lines by setting the join attribute of Screen to on (joins points)/off (no joining). The default is false.\r\n\r\n<strong>Running the Code (with extra notes for versions >= 0.5.1)</strong>\r\n\r\nRunning the code is as simple as typing:\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language="bash"]\r\nrp5 run demo.rb`\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nIf you\'re not using the Gems-in-a-Jar approach, you might have to use:\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language="bash"]\r\nrp5 run --jruby demo.rb`\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nThe reason for the `--jruby` switch is to force Ruby-Processing to use the installed version of JRuby, instead of it\'s own jruby-complete.jar\r\n\r\nAdditionally, starting with version 0.5.1, you will have to specify the environment variable JRUBY_OPTS to force JRuby to use the 1.9 version of the interpreter, like so:\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language="bash"]\r\nexport JRUBY_OPTS=--1.9`\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\n<strong>Notes on Interactivity</strong>\r\n\r\nExperimental support exists for mouseover interactivity without (too much) extra effort on your part. To allow interactions to happen, you must specify \':track => true\' while plotting a point, as in the line below:\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language="ruby"]\r\n@screen.plot(p, :track =&gt; true) {|p| rect(p[:x], p[:y], 5, 5)}\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nTo actually enable interactivity, you must do a few things:\r\n\r\n* \'include\' the Interactive module in your sketch class, as in the demonstration code above.\r\n* Build the data sample index from the data, by calling `@index = @screen.build`.\r\n* `@highlight_block` specifies what to plot when the data point is hovered upon.\r\n* `@passive_block` specifies what to plot when the data point is **not** being hovered on.\r\n\r\nInteractivity is a work in progress at the moment; some of the above steps may change or be removed.\r\n\r\nAs always, the code is available on <a href="https://github.com/asengupta/Basis">GitHub</a>.\r\n', 'A short guide to using Basis (updated)', 0, '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '562-revision-19', '', '', '2011-10-06 09:05:59', '2011-10-06 17:05:59', '', 562, 'http://avishek.net/blog/?p=621', 0, 'revision', '', 0); 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (622, 1, '2011-10-06 09:07:48', '2011-10-06 17:07:48', 'I spent much of today cleaning up the unholy mess in <a href="https://github.com/asengupta/Basis">Basis</a>, and teasing out a few classes (and a module). To finish that off, here\'s a quick guide to using Basis. Of course, expect this to change (somewhat) frequently, but the kernel of the idea should, hopefully, remain the same.\r\n\r\n<strong>UPDATE</strong>: Basis is now at version 0.5.0 with experimental support for mouseover interactivity. More work is incoming, but the demo code below is up-to-date, for now. The code below should be the same as <a href="https://github.com/asengupta/Basis/blob/master/lib/demo.rb">demo.rb on GitHub</a>.\r\n[gist]http://gist.github.com/1266616[/gist]\r\n\r\nThe <code>x_basis_vector</code> and <code>y_basis_vector</code> variables correspond to the two basis vectors of our coordinate system. The <code>Axis</code> class encapsulates them together with the range of values along each dimension. The <code>CoordinateSystem</code> class encapsulates two <code>Axis</code> objects to manipulate our basis. The <code>Screen</code> class takes care of mapping the result to the display, including flipping the y-component.\r\n\r\nThe two numbers in the <code>draw_axes</code> method of <code>Screen</code> are the intervals for marking the ticks along the two basis vectors, respectively. The matrix <strong>[[4,0],[0,2]]</strong> in the constructor of <code>CoordinateSystem</code> gives the scaling/rotation of the data <em>as specified in the basis vector space that you\'ve defined</em>; use it for stretching an axis that looks compressed or squeezing one which looks large.\r\n\r\nThe output looks like this:\r\n\r\n<a href="http://avishek.net/blog/wp-content/uploads/2011/08/SimpleDemo-Basis.png"><img src="http://avishek.net/blog/wp-content/uploads/2011/08/SimpleDemo-Basis-300x256.png" alt="" title="SimpleDemo-Basis" width="300" height="256" class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-563" /></a>\r\n\r\nYou have a few options when plotting a point. If you specify \':bar => true\', like the line below:\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language="ruby"]\r\n	@screen.plot(p, basis, :bar =&gt; true) {|p| rect(p[:x], p[:y], 5, 5)}\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nit will connect the point with the x-axis. If you omit `:bar => true` or don\'t specify any options, Basis will plot the points without connecting them to the X-axis.\r\nIf you omit the block at the end of the call, Basis will plot the point using a circle. Use the block to customise how you wish to represent the point graphically.\r\nYou can toggle the joining of the points with lines by setting the join attribute of Screen to on (joins points)/off (no joining). The default is false.\r\n\r\n<h2>Running the Code (with extra notes for versions >= 0.5.1)</h2>\r\n\r\nRunning the code is as simple as typing:\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language="bash"]\r\nrp5 run demo.rb`\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nIf you\'re not using the Gems-in-a-Jar approach, you might have to use:\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language="bash"]\r\nrp5 run --jruby demo.rb`\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nThe reason for the `--jruby` switch is to force Ruby-Processing to use the installed version of JRuby, instead of it\'s own jruby-complete.jar\r\n\r\nAdditionally, starting with version 0.5.1, you will have to specify the environment variable JRUBY_OPTS to force JRuby to use the 1.9 version of the interpreter, like so:\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language="bash"]\r\nexport JRUBY_OPTS=--1.9`\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\n<h2>Notes on Interactivity</h2>\r\n\r\nExperimental support exists for mouseover interactivity without (too much) extra effort on your part. To allow interactions to happen, you must specify \':track => true\' while plotting a point, as in the line below:\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language="ruby"]\r\n@screen.plot(p, :track =&gt; true) {|p| rect(p[:x], p[:y], 5, 5)}\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nTo actually enable interactivity, you must do a few things:\r\n\r\n* \'include\' the Interactive module in your sketch class, as in the demonstration code above.\r\n* Build the data sample index from the data, by calling `@index = @screen.build`.\r\n* `@highlight_block` specifies what to plot when the data point is hovered upon.\r\n* `@passive_block` specifies what to plot when the data point is **not** being hovered on.\r\n\r\nInteractivity is a work in progress at the moment; some of the above steps may change or be removed.\r\n\r\nAs always, the code is available on <a href="https://github.com/asengupta/Basis">GitHub</a>.\r\n', 'A short guide to using Basis (updated)', 0, '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '562-revision-20', '', '', '2011-10-06 09:07:48', '2011-10-06 17:07:48', '', 562, 'http://avishek.net/blog/?p=622', 0, 'revision', '', 0); 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (623, 1, '2011-10-06 09:49:51', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', 'Auto Draft', 0, '', 'auto-draft', 'open', 'open', '', '', '', '', '2011-10-06 09:49:51', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', 0, 'http://avishek.net/blog/?p=623', 0, 'post', '', 0); 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (624, 1, '2011-08-20 06:29:22', '2011-08-20 14:29:22', 'If you\'re using Ruby-Processing, you\'ll be working with the jruby-complete.jar. To install <a href="https://github.com/asengupta/Basis">Basis</a>, you simply type:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\njava -jar jruby-complete.jar -S gem install basis-processing --user-install\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nI\'ve also created a <strong>basis_processing.rb</strong> so that you don\'t need to include all the files individually, so just use <code>require \'basis_processing\'</code>\' in your code to get started.\r\n', 'Installing the Basis gem', 0, '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '572-revision-5', '', '', '2011-08-20 06:29:22', '2011-08-20 14:29:22', '', 572, 'http://avishek.net/blog/?p=624', 0, 'revision', '', 0); 
